<FIRST>r i AM-Norway     10-02 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norway Coalition Agrees To Topple Labor Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three opposition parties agreed on a basic
platform for a new non-socialist coalition and stand ready to
topple the minority government of Prime Minister Gro Harlem
Brundtland, an opposition leader said Monday.
   The emerging coalition was expected to submit a no-confidence
motion in Parliament this month if Mrs. Brundtland refuses to
resign, the national news agency NTB said.
   Conservative Party chairman Jan P. Syse, who probably would
become prime minister under the new coalition's plan, declined to
reveal details of its platform until the three parliamentary groups
review and approve the recommended policies.
   ``Lots of work remains to be done, including distribution of
ministerial posts,'' Syse said on national NRK radio.
   The alliance of Conservative, Christian Democratic and Center
parties won a total of 62 seats in the 165-seat parliament in Sept.
11 elections. Mrs. Brundtland's Labor party won 63 seats, and the
Socialist Left Party, allied with Labor, won 17.
   There was one independent.
   The right-wing Party of Progress, with 22 seats, held the
balance of power. Its chairman, Carl I. Hagen, says he would
support a no-confidence vote against Mrs. Brundtland, but would not
pledge future loyalty to the new coalition unless his party became
a full partner.
   ``We are ready to present such a no-confidence motion, if
necessary,'' Syse said in a radio interview.
   Mrs. Brundtland told Labor's central board on Sunday she will
decide the future of her government only after seeing the
opposition's platform.
   The three non-socialist leaders demanded she resign as early as
possible ``in order not to delay the coalition's and the
Parliament's work,'' NTB reported.
   ``She can chose to step down after Labor has presented its 1990
state budget proposal to the parliament on Oct. 12, or she risks
being toppled by a general no-confidence vote on Oct. 24,'' the
agency said.
</TEXT>
