<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Tate     10-02 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Tate,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former SMU president Willis Tate Dead at 77</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willis M. Tate, who served as president of
Southern Methodist University for nearly 20 years, died of an
apparent heart attack while on a trip with his wife in Colorado,
the school announced Monday. He was 77.
   Tate, who died Sunday night, was the university's president from
1954 to 1971 and again from July 1974 to October 1975. He retired
as chancellor in 1976 and since then had served as president
emeritus of SMU.
   Tate was an all-conference tackle and an honorable mention
All-American in 1931, when SMU won the Southwest Conference
football championship.
   He received his bachelor degree of arts in 1932 and his master's
of arts in sociology in 1935, both from SMU. After serving as
teacher and school principal in San Antonio, Tate returned to SMU
in 1945 as assistant dean of students.
   ``He will be remembered as the protector of academic freedom
during the difficult times in the 1950s and 1960s and as a strong
supporter of curriculum reforms,'' said SMU President A. Kenneth
Pye.
   Tate also presided over the establishment of SMU's School of the
Arts and the launching of doctoral programs on campus.
   He and his wife, the late Joel Estes Tate, had two children.
Tate is survived by Marian Cleary Tate, whom he married in 1988,
his two children and three grandchildren.
</TEXT>
