<DOCNO> AP891002-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2359EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e PM-APonTV:TabloidRatings     10-02 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV: Tabloid Ratings,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>In the Tabloid TV Battle, `Current Affair' and `Hard Copy' Fight
for No. 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first reports from the new tabloid
television wars are in, and ``A Current Affair'' and ``Hard Copy''
both have opened strongly while ``Inside Edition'' and ``USA Today
on TV'' appear doomed.
   In this fall's jammed field of reality-based shows, other early
casualties look to be ``Crimewatch Tonight,'' ``Trial by Jury'' and
``USA Today Weekend.''
   According to the initial Nielsen Syndication Service ratings,
Fox's nightly ``A Current Affair'' was the seventh most popular
syndicated show at the start of the new television season.
Finishing ahead of ``Entertainment Tonight'' and ``Donahue'' in the
ratings, ``A Current Affair'' was seen in more than 6.9 million
homes, the survey said.
   ``Every time a new show starts like `Hard Copy,' `Inside
Edition' or `Crimewatch Tonight' it becomes more competitive,''
said Peter Brennan, co-executive producer of ``A Current Affair.''
   ``But the strange thing...is that when `Inside Edition' started
we never had better numbers. So far, in the first week against
`Hard Copy,' we've done the highest numbers we've ever done.''
   Brennan said ``A Current Affair'' has attempted to fight off its
challengers by trying to ``give more serious thought to the stories
we do. You try to avoid doing the celebrity rip-offs and the easy
T&amp;A shock-value stories.''
   He said critics who blast ``A Current Affair's'' coverage of
news and personalities as tawdry aren't fair to the show's intent.
   ``The worst kind of criticism that's written says that shows
like `A Current Affair' seek to horrify, shock and offend,''
Brennan said. ``Because if somebody shocks and horrifies and
offends me on a regular basis, I'm going to turn off. And I won't
let my kids to watch it, either.''
   Because it debuted Sept. 18, ``Hard Copy'' was not included in
the first Nielsen syndication report. But the news-oriented
program, once entitled ``Tabloid,'' has performed strongly in Los
Angeles, Chicago, New York and San Francisco, according to its
producers.
   Furthermore, ``Hard Copy'' consistently has boosted some
stations' ratings from four months ago, the show's representatives
say. In Hartford, Conn., for example, ``Hard Copy'' is delivering
to WVIT an audience 60 percent larger than ``Win, Lose or Draw''
did in May.
   ``For a new show, we got off to a pretty solid start,'' says
Mark Monsky, executive producer of ``Hard Copy.'' ``We came off the
blocks very quickly. Right now we have to prove to the people who
did tune us in that what they got was just a little bit of what
they could get.''
   In its first few weeks on the air, ``Hard Copy'' has reported
exclusives on Imelda Marcos and the death of her husband and the
bombing of the Pan Am airliner over Scotland.
   ``I think our intention is very clear. At the top of the show,
we want to be very close to what's going on,'' Monsky said. ``And
then we want to go deeper and deeper in trying to explore the
widest possible range of the people involved.''
   The top five shows in the syndicated market for the week ending
Sept. 17 are, in order, ``Wheel of Fortune,'' ``Jeopardy,'' ``The
Oprah Winfrey Show,'' ``The Cosby Show'' and the weekend version of
``Wheel of Fortune.''
   ``Inside Edition'' finished at No. 22, ``USA Today'' landed at
No. 32 and ``Crimewatch Tonight'' was No. 46. ``Trial by Jury'' was
No. 62 and the weekend version of ``USA Today'' was No. 77.
   In one strange twist, the makers of ``Inside Edition'' have
discussed the possibility of inviting celebrities on the show to
rebut any distortions written about them in the supermarket
tabloids.
   However ``Inside Edition'' is revamped, though, it seems likely
it will be replaced by ``30 Minutes.'' Producer Av Westin, a
veteran of ABC News, has joined ``Inside Edition'' maker King World
Productions to create the new syndicated news magazine.
   New reality shows added to network schedules all have debuted
poorly. Of the 81 shows covered in last week's regular Nielsen
survey, ABC's ``Primetime Live,'' hosted by Sam Donaldson and Diane
Sawyer, finished 49th. CBS' ``Rescue 911,'' with William Shatner,
landed in 55th. And CBS' ``Saturday Night With Connie Chung'' came
in 71st.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BURNETT RETURNS...Production has opened for ``Carol and
Company,'' a new NBC comedy program that will star Carol Burnett.
The series, which has no announced debut date, marks Miss Burnett's
first ongoing role in series television in 10 years....SEARCH FOR
BISMARK...``National Geographic Explorer'' will broadcast exclusive
footage of Dr. Robert Ballard's search of the World War II
battleship Bismark on Oct. 29 in a one-hour documentary.
