<FIRST>r w AM-NomineeBlocked 2ndLd-Writethru a0743 10-02 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nominee Blocked, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0743,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Nominee Blocked By Senate Panel While It Studies HUD Funds</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Editing throughout to include more detail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel is delaying confirmation of
President Bush's nominee to head the Urban Mass Transportation
Administration while it investigates work done by his auditing
firm, Senate sources say.
   The Senate Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs Committee is
examining the relationship between nominee Brian Clymer's suburban
Philadelphia accounting firm and an economic development
organization nearby, according to Senate aides who spoke only on
condition of anonymity.
   The organization, the Delaware County Partnership for Economic
Development, is the subject of a broad audit by the Department of
Housing and Urban Development, HUD Inspector General Paul Adams
said in an interview Friday.
   The Senate panel unanimously backed Clymer's nomination on Sept.
8, but has since put a ``hold'' on sending it for a vote for the
full Senate.
   Clymer, 42, is the former vice chairman of the Southeastern
Pennsylvania Transportation Authority. UMTA assists state and local
governments in improving mass transportation systems. He has
declined requests to be interviewed about the matter.
   The local partnership, which has received $500,000 in HUD grants
in the past year, was founded in 1983 by U.S. Rep. Curt Weldon,
R-Pa., who has said he is not involved in its daily affairs. The
congressman ordered a consultant to investigate the partnership
earlier this year when it was disclosed that several of Weldon's
campaign supporters had received no-bid contracts.
   Of particular interest to the Senate panel are no-bid contracts
that the Philadelphia Inquirer reported were awarded to Clymer's
firm by the partnership to audit its books.
   Clymer has been Weldon's campaign treasurer in the last three
elections.
   Anthony J. Dunleavy, the consultant retained at Weldon's
request, said in his report to Weldon that this year's contract
given Clymer's firm was properly bid. However, the Inquirer
reported that Dunleavy said that previous year's contracts with
Clymer's firm were not awarded through competitive procurement
policies required by the federal government. The newspaper said
federal money was used.
   In his report to Weldon, which has been made public, Dunleavy
also said the partnership misspent $125,000 in federal funds on
ineligible items such as a promotion film and advertising. William
Tancredi, a top official of the partnership, resigned in July after
coming under fire for his handling of the organization's finances.
   Adams, the inspector general, said HUD was conducting a general
audit of the partnership that was ``not limited in any way, shape
or form.''
   HUD was doing another audit in Delaware County when ``a
combination of things occurred concurrently'' that convinced it of
the need to look into the partnership, Adams said. He declined to
be more specific.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
