<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0729 10-02 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs separates on Dapporto moved as a0699, on Fairbank as a0748,
on O'Meara as a0744.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>William Fairbank</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Fairbank, a professor emertitus
of physics at Stanford University who pioneered in low-temperature
superconductivity, died Saturday after a heart attack. He was 72.
   Fairbank's first experiment in superconductivity _ the ability
of some materials to offer no resistance to an electrical current
if they are cooled to near absolute zero _ was in 1947 with his
brother, Henry, also a physicist.
   Stanford said Fairbank's influence on physics included the
university's development of the superconducting accelerator, in
which superconductivity is achieved at two degrees above absolute
zero. That led to the first demonstration of a free electron laser.
   Fairbank was born in Minneapolis on Feb. 24, 1917. He graduated
from Whitman College in Washington and earned his Ph.D. from Yale
University in 1948.
   Before joining Stanford faculty in 1959, he taught at the
University of Washington, Amherst College and Duke University, and
worked on the staff of the Radiation Laboratory at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Carlo Dapporto</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comic actor Carlo Dapporto, known in Italy as the
King of the Joke, died of a heart attack Sunday at a clinic in
Rome, the Italian news agency ANSA reported. He was 88.
   Dapporto was known for the roles he played in a series of films
in the 1950s and for his appeances on variety shows on radio and
television.
   His greatest success came in the Ettore Scola film ``La Famiglia
(The Family).'' He portrayed an old man in a role written for him
by Scola and played opposite his son Massimo.
   He is survived by his son.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Harold R. Fatzer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Kansas Supreme Court Chief Justice
Harold R. Fatzer was found dead of a self-inflicted gunshot wound
to the head Saturday at his Topeka home. He was 79.
   Fatzer, who served on the Kansas Supreme Court from 1956 to 1977
and was chief justice from 1971 to 1977, was state attorney general
from 1949 to 1954.
   Fatzer attended Kansas State University and graduated from
Washburn University School of Law in 1933. He was Edwards County
attorney until 1941, when he became chief counsel for the state
Board of Social Welfare.
   After serving with the Army in World War II, Fatzer was elected
to his own two-year term as attorney general in November 1950, and
was re-elected in 1952 and 1954.
   He was appointed to the state Supreme Court on March 1, 1956,
with 10 months remaining in his third term as attorney general. He
served on the high court until he retired in September 1977.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Walter A. O'Meara</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter A. O'Meara, an advertising man who
served the OSS as well as the 1952 presidential campaign of Adlai
Stevenson and became a best-selling author, died Friday in
Cohasset, Mass. He was 92.
   His best-sellers among his 16 books included ``Grand Portage,''
a novel based on the life of fur trader Daniel Harmon, and
``Minnesota Gothic,'' a mystery novel.
   A native of Minneapolis, he graduated from the University of
Wisconsin at Madison with a journalism degree in 1920.
   After working at the Duluth News Tribune, O'Meara joined the J.
Walter Thompson advertising agency in Chicago. He later worked for
Benton and Bowles advertising in New York City.
   During World War II, he was chief of planning for the Office of
Strategic Services, predecessor of the CIA, and headed the
information department for the Office of Price Administration. He
was media director for Adlai Stevenson's 1952 presidential
campaign. O'Meara left advertising in 1950 to pursue his writing
career.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Christine Word Atkinson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORELAND, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christine Word Atkinson, a retired
elementary school teacher and mother of humorist Lewis Grizzard
Jr., died Sunday of scleroderma. She was 77.
   Mrs. Atkinson taught first-grade pupils at various elementary
schools in Coweta County for 20 years before retiring on disability
in 1972.
   Her son, a syndicated columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, is the author of several books.
   Miss Word married Lewis M. Grizzard Sr. in 1941. They later
divorced, and Grizzard died in 1970. She married H.B. Atkinson in
1954.
   Surviving in addition to her son are two sisters, Jesse Norman
and Una Word Coutee, both of Norman; and a brother, Dr. Johnny Word
of Bowden.
