<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-StarWars     10-02 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Star Wars,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Members Doubt Senate Rationale on Star Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of Star Wars believe the Senate
strengthened its hand in negotiations with the House by restoring
funds for the missile shield, but House members are casting doubt
on that rationale.
   The Senate slashed $900 million from President Bush's fiscal
1990 request of $4.9 billion for Star Wars last Tuesday, then came
back two days later and restored two-thirds of the money.
   What transpired in 48 hours were proclamations that the initial
vote signaled the demise of the program, formally known as the
Strategic Defense Initiative, introduced six years ago by President
Reagan as a nuclear-age antidote to a strike against the United
States.
   There also was a negotiating session between House and Senate
conferees thrashing out the defense authorization bill in which
confident House members argued that the true Senate Star Wars
number was the $3.7 billion adopted Tuesday in the appropriations
bill, not the $4.5 billion the Senate approved last month in
authorization legislation.
   The House, which had agreed to $3.1 billion for the program,
wanted a final figure closer to their total.
   Faced with that argument, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the
Armed Services Committee, took his case to the Senate for a
stronger negotiating position. He succeeded by a narrow margin,
53-47.
   Despite the win, lawmakers stressed that the House wouldn't be
fooled by the Senate reversal. Shortly after the second vote, some
Star Wars opponents said so in no uncertain terms.
   ``It tells you about the depth of their feelings,'' said Rep.
Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., a member of the House Armed Services
Committee and one of the conferees.
   ``Those kind of flip-flops don't make the Senate look very
serious,'' she added.
   But on Friday some senators argued that they did nothing to fool
the House.
   ``We're on record as supporting a higher number,'' said Sen.
Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., a member of the Armed Services Committee.
``The Senate signaled it did not want a significant cut.''
   He added: ``There's nothing for the House to see through.''
   While the authorizers enter their fifth week of negotiations on
their respective defense plans, the appropriators are scheduled to
begin in another two weeks.
   The House and Senate versions of the appropriations bills differ
greatly on the major strategic weapons such as Star Wars, the B-2
stealth bomber and land-based nuclear missiles. The two blueprints
also include different funding totals for the Marine Corps' V-22
Osprey, the vertical-takeoff plane, and the F-14D Tomcat jet
fighter.
   Bush had sought to cancel the two conventional programs.
   In addition, the House slashed $1.1 billion for the Advanced
Tactical Fighter plane while the Senate cut $1.8 billion earmarked
for the Trident 2 nuclear missile, the submarine-launched weapons
that has had two successive test failures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
