<FIRST>r a PM-PhantomWindfalls     10-02 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phantom Windfalls,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank's Contractors Get Blindside Hit from IRS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALINAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of independent contractors for a
bank are being scrutinized by the Internal Revenue Service, which
thinks they earned thousands of dollars every time they washed a
window or turned a screw.
   A computer at Wells Fargo &amp; Co. multiplied the earnings of
contractors, maintenance workers, lawyers and other professionals
by 100 before passing the information on to the IRS, the Salinas
Californian reported in its editions Saturday.
   And the IRS, eager to collect Uncle Sam's cut of the phantom
windfall, has written to the contractors, demanding explanations
for the discrepancies between the Wells Fargo reports and the
recipients' 1987 tax returns.
   ``I was panicked. They moved the decimal point two places to the
right,'' said real estate appraiser Harold M. Samuelson. ``They're
in quite a snit about it.''
   Samuelson, who says he made $2,400 from Wells Fargo, was listed
in IRS files as earning $240,000.
   There could be hundreds of such errors, said Cheryl Mortimer,
Wells Fargo spokeswoman. The bank acknowledged the number may be
higher but said the most people who could be listed wrongly would
be 25,000 _ the capacity of the suspect computer.
   ``It probably shook a lot of people up,'' said Russell Koch,
Samuelson's tax adviser, who has discussed the error with Wells
Fargo officials.
   The San Francisco-based bank, with 640 branches throughout the
state, hires about 2 million people each year on a contract basis,
said spokesman Kim Kellog.
   The inflated income reports have been tentatively traced to one
of Wells Fargo's many computers that handle IRS Form 1099, which is
submitted for all non-employees who perform more than $600 worth of
work for the company. The cause of the malfunction remains unknown.
   Koch said taxpayers called to account for non-existent income
should be able to prove the bank's figures were inaccurate but
could face a large amount of paperwork.
   But IRS spokesman Larry Wright said that any problems in setting
the record straight should be minimal.
   ``It's just a couple of additional zeroes,'' he said. ``It's not
a problem for the taxpayer. We send out hundreds of thousands of
letters like those, and it's not unusual to have some problems.''
</TEXT>
