<HEAD>Six Killed In Head-On Collision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The four ...' to CORRECT spelling to Pourchier,
sted Poehier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The driver of a sports car crossed the
center line of a highway, struck a motorcycle and then collided
head-on with a car, killing himself and five other people, police
said. Two others were injured.
   The driver, whose name was being withheld, apparently hit the
motorcycle first, which then slammed another motorcycle on Route
30, police said Saturday. The car then struck the station wagon
carrying five people from Hanover, Pa.
   Four of the five were killed, along with both occupants of the
sports car. The remaining passenger from the station wagon and one
motorcyclist were taken to a Baltimore hospital. Police said they
did not have a report on the other motorcyclist.
   State police said excessive speed and alcohol contributed to the
accident.
   The four victims from the station wagon were identified as
Gregory Oppedal, 42; his children Erica Oppedal, 15, and Damon
Oppedal, 12; and Jessica Pourchier, 13, a neighbor. Oppedal's wife,
Nancy Oppedal, 42, was listed in critical condition. The
motorcyclist, Wayne Schultz, 30, was in serious condition after
doctors removed his left leg.
   The passenger in the sports car was identified as Scott Brown,
23, of Littlestown, Pa., who also owned the car.
