<DOCNO> AP891002-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 0111EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ChildrenandFamilies     10-02 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children and Families,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Children Locked in Poverty, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of children, particularly blacks and
Hispanics, are being launched on ``courses of failure'' because
they live in poverty, says a congressional report that warns there
appears little prospect for improvement.
   Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., said the report released Sunday
paints a ``disturbing'' portrait of American children, many of whom
never benefited from the economic expansion of the 1980s under the
Reagan administration.
   ``We're launching millions of children on courses of failure,''
said Miller, who heads a committee on families.
   Most disturbing, he said, is that ``I really see very little
that holds out the prospect that this will change. ... The prospect
is that those incomes are going to stagnate.''
   Neither the White House nor Congress has been willing to put
enough resources into social programs to give families the support
they need so children can grow up well-fed, healthy and educated
enough to participate in the economy, he said.
   However, Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., ranking Republican on the
panel, took issue with the chairman's conclusion that the federal
government, under a Republican president, has ignored the problem.
   Bliley said the net that is keeping so many children in poverty
was not cast by Reagan but is the result of social forces that are
breaking up families and sexual behaviors that are leading more
girls to become teenage mothers.
   ``We have known for two decades that single parenthood is a
prescription for poverty, regardless of race,'' Bliley said. ``How
you solve these problems I really don't know.''
   Bliley agreed with Miller that Congress was not likely to vote
more money for social programs overall.
   ``You can always use more money, but I don't see it there with
the budget crunch we're in,'' he said.
   The 300-page report by the House Select Committee on Children,
Youth and Families compiles statistics from a variety of sources.
   The figures show that children are the poorest segment of the
U.S. population. In 1987, nearly 21 percent of children under age
18 and more than 22 percent of children under age 6 lived in
families with incomes below the poverty line, compared with 12
percent of the elderly and 14 percent of people of all ages.
   The childhood poverty rate rose from 15 percent in 1970 to more
than 18 percent in 1980 and more than 22 percent in 1983 before
dropping to 20.5 percent in 1986.
   Poverty has been more persistent for black and Hispanic
children, for whom the rates have risen since 1970. In 1987, more
than 48 percent of black children and nearly 42 percent of Hispanic
children lived in poverty.
   In 1988, 71 percent of children were living with two parents,
while about 24 percent were living with only their mother or
father. In 1981, about 74 percent were living with both parents and
about 20 percent were living with a single parent.
   About 42 percent of children in 1986 were living with two
working parents, while 29 percent were in two-parent families where
only the father worked. About 15 percent lived with one parent who
was in the labor force and about 8 percent were in single-parent
homes where the parent was unemployed.
</TEXT>
