<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Clouthier     10-02 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Clouthier,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Mexican Politician Killed In Car Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto M04</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manuel J. Clouthier, who as a candidate in
the 1988 presidential election brought conservative ideas back to
Mexican politics, died in an auto accident in his native Sinaloa
state. He was 55.
   Thousands of supporters marched through the streets of the state
capital, Culiacan, late Sunday carrying the blue-and-white flags of
his National Action Party with a black-bow ribbon sewed on one
corner as a sign of mourning.
   In Mexico City, about 200 supporters gathered around the Angel
of Independence monument holding signs that read, ``Thank you,
Maquio,'' Clouthier's nickname.
   Clouthier and political colleague Javier Calvo Manriquez died
Sunday when the car they were in crashed head on into a truck
loaded with papayas, police said.
   The accident occurred halfway between Culiacan and the Pacific
beach resort of Mazatlan. A police news bulletin said the driver of
the truck, Aurelio Flores Gomez, was detained for questioning.
   When he died, Clouthier was stumping the state to help National
Action mayoral candidates running in Oct. 15 balloting.
   Friends, political foes and former business associates mourned
the burly, white-bearded politician who finished third in Mexico's
1988 election, which was won by President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
and marred by fraud.
   Salinas, on a one-week visit to the United States, telephoned
his condolences to National Action Party leaders, the government
news agency Notimex said.
   Rosario Ibarra de Piedra, a leading human rights activist,
called Clouthier's death ``a great loss for the political fight in
Mexico.''
   ``He was a strong, courageous man of very defined political
ideology. But I learned to appreciate him as a Mexican struggling
to open the way of democracy for the Mexican people,'' Heberto
Castillo, a socialist political foe, told reporters.
   Clouthier gained wide popularity after the 1988 campaign for his
denunciations of election fraud and criticisms of the centrist
Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has held power in Mexico
since its founding in 1929.
   Conservative politics had been frowned upon since the overthrow
of dictator Porfirio Diaz in the Mexican Revolution.
   Conservative parties like National Action were discredited until
Clouthier, angered by former President Jose Lopez Portillo's
expropriation of private banks in 1982, entered politics.
   ``Lopez Portillo turned me into a politician when he did that. I
saw the power and the rigidity of the presidential system and I
decided to struggle to change that,'' a friend quoted Clouthier as
saying.
   Clouthier sold most of his investments in industrial companies
and dedicated himself to truck farming and politics.
   He managed to unify his fractious party into a political force
and rally Mexico's splintered conservatives. He ran for Sinaloa
governor in 1986 but lost to the governing party candidate in
balloting also allegedly marred by fraud.
   Clouthier, whose family has lived in Sinaloa for more than a
century, was born in Culiacan on June 13, 1934. An agricultural
engineer by profession, he headed leading business organizations
for more than two decades.
   Clouthier studied at the Technological Institute of Monterrey,
graduating with a degree in agronomy and botany. He taught biology
at the University of Sinaloa.
   He is survived by his wife, Leticia Carrillo de Clouthier, and
their 10 children.
</TEXT>
