<FIRST>u i PM-NorthernIreland     10-02 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Heavily Damages Town Center, Slightly Injures Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded outside the
police station of a small town 20 miles northwest of Belfast,
heavily damaging the town center and slightly injuring three
people, police said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the blast late
Sunday in Randalstown, but suspicion inevitably fell on the Irish
Republican Army, which is fighting British rule in Northern Ireland.
   Belfast police headquarters said in a statement that the injured
were two civilians and a police officer.
   Police said the bomb exploded as police officers were evacuating
scores of families from their homes in the area following a
telephoned warning by an anonymous caller.
   They said the attackers put the 500-pound bomb in a hijacked
van, then left the vehicle outside the police station, which like
many police stations in Northern Ireland is fortified against bomb
attacks and manned only part-time.
   The building, unoccupied at the time, was extensively damaged
while dozens of nearby homes, shops and offices were wrecked,
police said.
   They said only the prompt action of the security forces in
evacuating homes had prevented a major disaster.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to unite the predominantly
Protestant province with the mainly Catholic Republic of Ireland
under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
