<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0414 10-02 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0414,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Downward, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with closing Nikkei, dollar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar ended marginally lower against the
Japanese yen at the end of Monday trading, while the key index on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange erased earlier gains and inched down.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 13.79
points, or 0.04 percent, ending at 35,622.97. It shed 53.22 points
on Friday.
   Dealers said the index rose earlier when market players were
reassured by Liberal Democratic Party candidate Itsuo Nomura's
victory over his Socialist rival in a by-election for a seat in the
less-powerful upper house of Parliament Sunday.
   However, the index started falling as participants sold issues
for profit-taking, partly fearful of the recent rapid rise in share
prices, they said.
   In currency dealings, the dollar ended at 139.30 yen, down 0.05
yen from last Friday's close of 139.35 yen. It opened lower at
138.77 yen, and moved between 138.65 yen and 139.48 yen.
   The dollar passed the 139-yen mark shortly after the market
opened, as participants bought the currency for profit-taking, but
trading became mixed afterwards, traders said.
   The dollar's downtrend was further prompted by the the governing
party's victory in the by-election and dollar-selling by the U.S.
Federal Reserve Board last week, said one trader with a major
commercial Japanese bank in Tokyo who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
