<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     10-02 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a sight that would have impressed Noah,
though this procession was one-by-one, not two-by-two.
   First came Mini, an 8,000-pound elephant, followed by a skittish
llama, ponies, baby African pigmy goats, a chimpanzee named Casey,
an owl, thousands of bees, a 3-foot lizard, a bowl of algae, and
even a rat.
   This was no marching zoo, but the Fifth Annual Feast of St.
Francis of Assisi at the Cathedral Church of St. John the Divine,
where about 6,000 people came Sunday to have their pets blessed and
to celebrate ``the beauty of God's sacred creation.''
   ``Women, men, boys, girls and animals _ it's a great day,''
announced the Rt. Rev. Paul Moore Jr., 13th bishop of the Episcopal
church, at the start of his sermon.
   Most brought dogs _ of every imaginable shape, size and color.
The stars were the animals in the procession. They slowly came up
the aisle and gathered around the altar.
   The elephant snorted. A camel surveyed the scene with his
drooping eyes. Goats baaaaahed. A parrot screeched. A shy
chimpanzee clutched her owner tightly. Francis, the pet rat,
twitched and sniffed.
   ``He was very brave, I think the church had a calming affect on
him,'' said the rat's owner, who indentified herself only as
Susanne. ``He sat next to the owl and had a great time.''
   Peter Brandon was proud of his emerald winged macaw after the
procession.
   ``He was good this year. He didn't say anything. Last year, we
were up on the altar near a microphone and he suddenly screeched
out `Come on! Let's go!'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Baltimore Orioles didn't quite make history
as the first big-league ball club to climb from the cellar to the
top in one season, but that didn't bother the thousands of fans who
welcomed them home in rain.
   ``I can't imagine what it would have been like if it had been a
dry day or if we'd actually won it,'' pitcher Dave Johnson said
after Sunday's airport rally.
   The team arrived from Toronto, where the Blue Jays on Saturday
ended the Orioles' hopes of winning the American League East title.
The battle of the birds ended with the Orioles two games behind.
   A parade was scheduled for today.
   Manager Frank Robinson thanked the crowd with a joke:
   ``In 1982 in San Francisco, we finished two games out and they
gave me 24 hours to get out of town,'' said Robinson, a former
Giants manager. ``Here, we finish two games out and we get pep
rally and a parade.''
