<FIRST>r i PM-Refugees-Arrival     10-02 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees-Arrival,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tired Refugees Weep With Joy On Arrival In West Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Refugees, Bjt ^By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young East German woman screamed,
``We made it, we made it,'' as she sobbed with happiness, squeezed
into a throng of hundreds of other refugees arriving in this
northern Bavarian city.
   The refugees, many with small children in tow, looked tired but
still showed nearly unbounded joy as crowds of West Germans
welcomed them after their overnight journey to the West.
   Elke Ebecke, her 12-year-old son Thomas and 3-year-old daughter
Christine, tried to push through the refugees and well-wishers on
the train platform.
   ``My husband managed to make it across through Hungary three
weeks ago, but we didn't go,'' the 32-year-old woman said, her eyes
wet with tears.
   Mrs. Ebecke, from the Leipzig area, was on the second train
packed with East German refugees that arrived from Prague,
Czechoslovakia.
   ``My husband doesn't even know we're here yet,'' she said.
   Annamarie Lenz, 52, told of how Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher of West Germany announced late Saturday to refugees at
Bonn's embassy in Prague that they would be permitted to go West.
   ``I was just walking by in the embassy garden when he said it.
Such a cheer went up from all the people. It was unbelievable,''
she said. ``I had applied three times in two years to leave for the
West, but they turned me down each time. I went to Prague, because
I thought this was my only chance.''
   The refugees formed long lines at public telephones in the train
station to call families in East Germany or relatives in the West.
   Outside the station, many refugees picked out donated clothing
stacked high on yellow railway carts. Most had arrived with just
one or two canvas bags packed with their belongings.
   Red Cross, police and railway workers mingled with the crowd,
many smiling and chatting. Some handed out hot drinks, bananas and
bowls of soup to the refugees.
   At a table in the train station snack bar sat 21-year-old Mike
Mueller and his wife Monique, 19.
   Mueller, a cook, and his wife, a waitress, said they were fed up
with harsh political conditions at home.
   ``They (Communist authorities) control everything you do,''
Mueller said. ``We applied to go to Hungary on vacation, but they
turned us down. We didn't need permission to go to Prague, so we
went to the embassy and joined the others, hoping to get out.''
   Mrs. Mueller said, ``You can't get ahead over there (in East
Germany). You always have the feeling you are being watched. You
are afraid to discuss anything with your friends.''
   She said the East German news media ``lie and try to tell us the
West just wants to make slaves of us. They really think we're so
stupid we don't know better.''
   East German news media have claimed that West Germany is luring
East Germans as a source of cheap labor.
   Peter Shutz, an auto mechanic, said East German authorities
``try to control everything we do. The young are tired of putting
up with that. It's a dictatorship. All I can say is I'm happy to be
here ... If I work hard over here I know I can get ahead.''
   Shutz was asked why he and other refugees turned down an earlier
East German offer of travel to the West within six months on
condition they first leave the embassy in Prague and return home.
   ``There aren't many people who would fall for something like
that,'' he said.
   Uwe Thuemmel, a 30-year-old East German truck driver, said he
had planned to take advantage of that offer and had traveled to
Prague from Plauen, near the Czechoslovak border.
   ``I left my wife and family at home, thinking I would be back in
three days. But then Genscher's announcement came, so I decided to
leave without my family,'' he said. ``I hope they'll be able to
follow me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
