<DOCNO> AP891002-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 0410EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China     10-02 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Celebrates National Day, People Don't</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist China marked its 40th anniversary with
fireworks displays and dances on Tiananmen Square, which thousands
of police patrolled to ensure the celebrations would not be
disrupted.
   Thousands of police mingled with the 130,000 performers, and
residential areas around the square were cordoned off hours before
Sunday's show. Only people with passes were allowed to enter.
   A million people joined anniversary events around a tightly
guarded Beijing on Sunday. Along city streets, potted flowers were
arranged in designs that praised socialism and the Communist Party.
   The highlight was the nationally televised 3{-hour dance and
fireworks display on Tiananmen Square.
   The symbolic seat of power in China, the square has been under
military guard since troops on June 3-4 put down the pro-democracy
movement, killing hundreds of unarmed civilians.
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping, 85, watched the performance from
the Tiananmen Gate rostrum above a huge portrait of Mao Tse-tung.
From the same spot, Mao declared the founding of the People's
Republic on Oct. 1, 1949.
   Communist Party General Secretary Jiang Zemin, Premier Li Peng
and 84-year-old Chen Yun, an ideological hard-liner who rarely
appears in public, joined Deng.
   Western ambassadors boycotted the show to demonstrate continued
concern over China's suppression of dissent and most foreign guests
were from socialist countries such as the Soviet Union, North
Korea, East Germany and Czechoslovakia.
   The most prominent American to sit with the leaders was former
Secretary of State Alexander Haig, now a private businessmen. He is
in Beijing for a business symposium.
   The official Xinhua News Agency quoted Deng as telling North
Korean Politburo member Li Jong Ok that the spring political
turmoil ``was bad, but in the final analysis it is beneficial to
us, because it made us more sober-minded.''
   Deng, said that because of the spread of Western ideas before
the military crackdown, ``for a period of time some of our
ideological front was lost.''
   But he said now ``social order has returned to normal.''
   Despite frequent assertions that all is normal in Beijing, the
city remains under martial law and security was extremely tight
around Tiananmen. Police and troops, some armed with rifles,
patrolled city streets.
   Those who danced on the square and other places were carefully
selected for their political reliability and non-participation in
the spring demonstrations.
   Some offices and factories provided cash bonuses for employees
who volunteered to dance on the anniversary.
   The government led up to the national day with television and
radio and press reports about China's achievements over the past
four decades in developing industry and agriculture, and caring for
its 1.1 billion people.
   There has been little mention of the political and economic
upheavals under Communist rule. Reports have been couched within
the central theme that only socialism can save China and only the
Communist Party is qualified to rule the nation.
   ``There is no doubt that the socialist system is superior to the
capitalist system,'' the Communist Party's official People's Daily
said in an editorial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
