<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Thomson     10-02 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Thomson,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Composer, Critic Virgil Thomson Dead at 92</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virgil Thomson, the Pulitzer Prize-winning
composer and music critic whose career spanned more than half a
century, has died at age 92.
   Thomson, who had been in failing health for a long time, died in
his sleep early Saturday in his room at Manhattan's Chelsea Hotel
where he had lived almost 50 years, said his secretary, Jay
Sullivan.
   Thomson won the Pulitzer Prize for music for his score to the
documentary film ``Louisiana Story,'' in 1949 _ the only time the
Pulitzer has been awarded for a movie score.
   ``The death of Virgil T is like the death of an American city:
it is intolerable,'' said composer-conductor Leonard Bernstein.
``Virgil was loving and harsh, generous and mordant, simple but
cynical, son of the hymnal yet highly sophisticated. ...
   ``But he will always remain brightly alive in the history of
music, if only for the extraordinary influence his witty and
simplistic music had on his colleagues.''
   Thomson's long career included orchestral and choral works as
well as incidental music for plays by authors from Shakespeare to
Truman Capote.
   In 1988, Thomson was one of 12 recipients of the National Medal
of Arts, an award created by Congress four years earlier at the
suggestion of President Reagan.
   Born in Kansas City, Mo., Thomson began to play piano at age 5
and, as a teen-ager, worked as a church organist.
   In 1922, he graduated from Harvard University and moved to
Paris, where he was among a group of young American musicians such
as Aaron Copland to study with Nadia Boulanger. In Paris, he also
met the iconoclastic composer Erik Satie, who was a great influence
on him.
   While in Paris, he met Gertrude Stein and wrote one of his most
famous works, the opera ``Four Saints in Three Acts,'' with her as
librettist in 1928. It premiered in Hartford, Conn., in 1934 and
had a short but successful run on Broadway.
   He settled in New York in 1940 and joined the staff of the New
York Herald Tribune, where he was music critic until 1954.
   In 1982, he won a National Book Critics Circle Award for ``A
Virgil Thomson Reader.''
   Thomson's latest book, ``Music with Words,'' is to be released
officially Oct. 18 by Yale University Press. Sullivan described it
as a ``how-to book for composers, people who are interested in
setting words to music or music to words.''
   In an interview with The Associated Press before his 90th
birthday, the cherubic, white-haired Thomson said, ``I've got
nothing wrong with me except I'm deaf and overweight. You don't die
from those.''
   Thomson said the hearing problem kept him from enjoying musical
performances more than 10 years ago, but he continued to compose
and kept busy on the lecture circuit.
   He recalled that his first Tribune music review said violinist
Jascha Heifetz played ``silk underwear music,'' but joked that when
some other critic is unkind about his own music, ``I'm convinced
the writer is an ignorant pipsqueak and probably in the pay of my
enemies.''
   Thomson, who never married, is survived by a niece, Betty
Stouffer, of Longwood, Fla. He will be buried in a family plot in
Slater, Mo., Sullivan said.
   A memorial service is planned at the Cathedral of St. John the
Divine in New York on Nov. 25 _ what would have been Thomson's 93rd
birthday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
