<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-02 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall, Dollar Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index fell back from
its record high morning close today, and the dollar declined
against the Japanese yen for the sixth consecutive trading day.
   The dollar closed at 139.30 yen, down 0.05 yen from last
Friday's 139.35-yen finish. It opened at 138.77 yen and moved
between 138.65 yen and 139.48 yen. The dollar now has fallen 5.70
yen in six days.
   Market players, reassured by the governing Liberal Democratic
Party's parliamentary by-election victory on Sunday, tended to buy
the yen in early trading, said Minori Takeuchi, a trader with
Chemical Bank.
   ``But the dollar rose afterward in mixed trading, mainly for
technical position adjustments,'' she said.
   She added that market players were reluctant to buy the dollar
at the 139.50-yen level for fear of Bank of Japan intervention.
   The central bank has been selling dollars over the last week to
check the U.S. currency's recent rise. The amount of selling was
unknown, and the bank does not comment on its exchange market
activities.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost
13.79 points, or 0.04 percent, ending at 35,622.97. In early
trading, it had climbed to 35,701.33, its highest ever morning
closing. The index had shed 53.22 points on Friday.
   The Liberal Democrats' by-election victory also prompted the
index's early gain, said Masahiro Umemori, a stock analyst with
Nomura Securities.
   ``But the index started falling later mainly because
participants became afraid of recent rapid rises in share prices,''
he said, noting the index's 500-point gain last week.
   ``Afternoon trading was directionless, too,'' he said.
   A rumor that West Germany might raise its interest rates soon
also discouraged investors, Umemori said.
   ``The rumor even said there might be a coordinated interest rate
hike in a few countries,'' he added, without elaboration.
   Trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated at 750
million shares, down from 900 million last Friday.
   Electrical issues such as Sony and Pioneer and steel issues were
losers.
</TEXT>
