<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms Sweep South And Chill Threatens Cows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms swept through the South early today after
tornadoes whipped through Georgia. Temperatures dipped in Wyoming,
where farmers were warned to protect their cattle from the cold.
   A tornado watch was posted for portions of eastern and central
South Carolina and southeastern North Carolina. On Sunday, a
tornado touched down west of Moultrie, Ga., destroying several
mobile homes. Storm gusts damaged trees and power lines near
Vienna, Ga.
   Early this morning, thunderstorms hit Charleston, S.C., and rain
fell on Jacksonville, Fla.
   Flash-flood watches Sunday night were posted over western South
Carolina, western North Carolina, western Virginia and southern
West Virginia.
   More than 2{ inches of rain drenched Myrtle Beach Air Force
Base, S.C., on Sunday night, and more than 1 inch fell on Augusta,
Ga., and Greensboro, N.C.
   Sunday was another hot day for portions of the Mississippi
Valley and the Plains. High temperature records for Oct. 1 were
broken in Austin, Texas, where it was 98 degree; Corpus Christi,
Texas, with 96; and Duluth, Minn., which tied its record of 80
degrees.
   Up to 4 inches of snow was expected early today over the higher
elevations of south-central Montana. Gusts of 20 to 35 mph were
expected to drop wind chills to minus 10 degrees.
   Farmers in northern Wyoming were warned to protect livestock
from cold early today. Temperatures were forecast into the mid- or
lower 40s, and light rain could change to snow during the night.
   With the colder air moving South, showers were forecast to
develop and become snow in the mountains of northwest Nevada early
today.
   Today's temperatures include:
   _East: Albany, N.Y. 52 partly cloudy; Atlanta 67 fair; Boston 55
partly cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 77 thunderstorm; Chattanooga 65
partly cloudy; Cincinnati 67 cloudy; Cleveland 62 cloudy; Detroit
