<FIRST>r w PM-ChinaProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0444 10-02 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Chinese Pro-Democracy Members Lead Washington March</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, adds 3 grafs at end to include Canadian protests.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former members of the Tiananmen Square
democracy movement are urging Americans and ``peace-loving people
all over the world'' to continue pressing for freedom in China.
   Three former members of the pro-democracy movement led about
3,500 demonstrators Sunday to protest the 40th anniversary of
communist rule in their homeland.
   The marchers walked in a downpour from the Lincoln Memorial to
the Chinese Embassy here to protest the violent crackdown on the
student democracy movement in Beijing's Tiananmen Square. Nearly
2,000 other marchers demonstrated in Los Angeles and San Francisco,
and hundreds marched in Canada.
   ``The Chinese government must stop killing,'' said Shen Tong,
one of the three pro-democracy leaders, who fled China after the
crackdown last summer. ``We appeal to peace-loving people all over
the world to stand together with us and fight for a China in which
basic freedoms are guaranteed.''
   Another of the three emigres, Wu'er Kaxi, told a small news
conference outside the Chinese Embassy that ``the attitude of the
American people as well as that of Congress has been clear since
the events'' of the crackdown. Asked whether he had any specific
criticisms or demands of the Bush administration, he replied, ``No
comment.''
   Shen, Wu'er and the third leader, LiuYan, were in Washington for
a fast and protest. Police estimated the crowd of marchers at 3,500.
   In San Francisco, 1,200 people shouted and waved signs outside
the Chinese consulate in a noisy but peaceful protest against
National Day, the celebration of the 40th anniversary of the
People's Republic of China.
   Protesters during the three-hour demonstration said four decades
of communism had been a failure for China and blasted the Chinese
government's repression of the pro-democracy movement.
   Many of the signs pledged to remember the ``martyrs'' of
democracy, hundreds of students who were killed when troops fired
on Beijing's Tiananmen Square last June.
   Police reported no arrests or problems because of the protests.
   In Los Angeles, some 700 people gathered peacefully outside the
Chinese consulate downtown waving human rights signs, singing peace
songs and cheering speeches by university students, Christian
clergyman and community leaders.
   The crowd, mainly Chinese natives, formed a semicircle on the
street in front of a military tank, two tents, a 5-foot Goddess of
Liberty statue and a gray coffin, on which dozens of spectators
placed white flowers.
   The Joint Committee of Chinese Students and Scholars sponsored
the two-hour protest which included a re-enactment of the student
massacre and a mock trial.
   Ting Huang, a computer engineer and native Chinese, donned a
T-shirt with a picture of Deng Xiaoping, the 85-year-old senior
leader in China. The words above the photo stated ``Wanted for
Murder.''
   ``I'm here to protest continuing human rights violations in
China, secret arrests and imprisonment,'' Huang said.
   On Oct. 1, 1949, Mao Zedong declared the founding of the
People's Republic of China.
   About 500 people demonstrated in front of the Chinese embassy in
Ottawa, while 300 rallied in Toronto.
   ``We are going to use every occasion to help people remember
June 4 and tell the world we will never forget, nor will we stop
fighting for democracy,'' said Dennis Lu, president of the Canadian
Federation of Chinese Students and Scholars in Toronto.
   Several protesters wore brown paper bags on their heads, fearing
for the safety of relatives still in China.
</TEXT>
