<FIRST>r i PM-Australia-Protest     10-02 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Protest,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>500 Arrested in Five-Day Protest at U.S. Military Facility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NURRUNGAR, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-nuclear protesters have ended a
five-day protest at a U.S.-Australian military intelligence base
after 500 demonstrators were arrested, some after breaking into the
base.
   About 50 soldiers were called in to reinforce base security
forces and police at the base in southern Australia. In the action
that ended Sunday, protesters broke into the facility several
times, police said.
   Today, Defense Minister Kim Beazley ordered an investigation
into security measures at the base.
   Demonstrators picked the intelligence-gathering base 360 miles
northwest of Adelaide as a protest site because they consider it a
likely target in the event of a superpower nuclear confrontation.
   Police said 217 of the 500 protesters were arrested inside the
Nurrungar base's security zone.
   The media were prohibited from covering a march from the
security gate to the main complex by protesters who broke into the
grounds. Six journalists were arrested during protests on Saturday.
   A Sydney newspaper said the protest was ``an embarrassment for
Australia's defense forces and must give American military
authorities cause for concern.''
   ``If we are to have U.S. bases and equipment here we should be
able to protect them,'' said today's editorial in The Sydney Daily
Telegraph.

</TEXT>
