<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos-Actor     10-02 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos-Actor,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor George Hamilton Reportedly Named as Marcos Co-Conspirator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor George Hamilton has been described by
federal authorities as an unindicted co-conspirator of former
Philippines first lady Imelda Marcos, a newspaper reported today.
   Hamilton's name appeared on documents filed in U.S. District
Court in connection with the case against Mrs. Marcos, according to
New York Newsday.
   ``I can't give you any information,'' said Hamilton's agent, Tom
Corman.
   An indictment last October charged that Mrs. Marcos and her
husband, the late Philippines President Ferdinand E. Marcos, stole
$168 million from the Philippine treasury.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Charles G. LaBella would not say why
Hamilton was on the list of unindicted co-conspirators, according
to Newsday.
   Also named were Manhattan real estate developers, Joseph and
Ralph Bernstein, who are brothers, and the Marcos' children, Irene,
Imee and Ferdinand Jr., the newspaper said.
   The Bernstein brothers have told a congressional hearing that
they managed the Marcoses' New York real estate investments.
   An unindicted co-conspirator may have done something to advance
an alleged criminal conspiracy, but did not necessarily know they
were doing it.
   The list of unindicted co-conspirators was included in a
pretrial motion filed by one of Mrs. Marcos' co-defendants,
California Overseas Bank.
   The actor, known for his perpetual tan and for his portrayal of
a vampire in the movie ``Love at First Bite,'' has denied rumors
that he and Mrs. Marcos were romantically linked.
   Hamilton's name previously has come up in connection with legal
action against the Marcoses, specifically, in a lawsuit by the
Philippines government against the Marcoses.
   Alan D. Bersin, an attorney for the Philippines, said the suit
alleges that the Marcoses invested in a Beverly Hills house owned
by Hamilton.
   Hamilton has said he has done nothing wrong.
   In March 1986, Hamilton said through his attorney, Michael
Sherman, that Marcos had no financial involvement in the estate.
   Hamilton bought the estate, once owned by Charlie Chaplin, for
$1.2 million in 1981. The deal was financed by Hamilton's own
money, Wells Fargo Bank and the seller, Sherman said.
   In late 1983, Hamilton used the increased value of the property
to get a five-year loan from Calno Holdings N.V. in the Netherlands
Antilles. Calno reportedly has ties with the Marcos family.
</TEXT>
