<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Phat     10-02 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Phat,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Vice President Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Huynh Tan Phat, a leading member of the
Viet Cong and later vice president of Vietnam's State Council, has
died at age 76, the Vietnam News Agency reported.
   The report, seen in Bangkok today, said Phat died Saturday in Ho
Chi Minh City. Radio Hanoi said he would be buried Thursday in the
southern city, formerly called Saigon.
   A graduate in architecture from Hanoi University, Phat joined
the anti-French underground and was imprisoned by the colonial
government. Some reference books say Phat initially may have held
anti-communist views.
   He rose in the ranks of the Democratic Party in South Vietnam
but repression of that party by President Ngo Diem forced Phat into
the resistance in the late 1950s.
   Phat emerged as the chief theoretician of the National
Liberation Front, the key southern Communist-led movement whose
members were often called Viet Cong.
   After the Communist victory in Vietnam in 1975, Phat was one of
the few members of the Viet Cong to hold a leadership position in a
Hanoi government and Communist Party dominated by northern
Vietnamese.
   He served as vice chairman of the Council of State and chairman
of the Presidium of the Vietnam Fatherland Front, one of a number
of mass organizations under party and government control.
</TEXT>
