<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 0649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MassacreWarning     10-02 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Massacre Warning,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunman Told Fellow Print Shop Worker His Intentions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired pressman's murderous schemes
were common knowledge at the plant where he returned last month and
shot to death eight people before killing himself, according to a
report.
   Joseph Wesbecker revealed his plans on several occasions to
former co-worker James R. Lucas, but the warnings were ignored by
other co-workers and supervisors and they were never taken up with
management, The Courier-Journal reported Sunday.
   Wesbecker, 47, shot 20 of his former co-workers, killing eight
of them before taking his own life Sept. 14.
   Lucas said the first warning came in late 1987 or early 1988,
inside the Standard Gravure Corp. plant, where Wesbecker opened a
brown paper sack and showed Lucas a .38-caliber snub-nosed revolver.
   Lucas recalls that Wesbecker said he was angry at supervisors:
``That if any one of them came up to him and said anything other
than what pertained to work-related conversation, that he was going
to blow their brains out.''
   Another warning came just a few weeks ago, Lucas said, when
Wesbecker confided the names of six people he intended to kill
during a conversation at the kitchen table at Lucas' house.
   All had been pressroom supervisors or were managers of the
plant. Only one, employee relations manager Paula Warman, was
injured in the attack.
   Wesbecker, who was placed on long-term disability early in the
year because of psychiatric problems, also described putting
plastic explosives into a remote-controlled airplane, Lucas said.
   Lucas said he believed his tormented friend was serious, and
began warning others.
   But for a variety of reasons _ the airplane scheme's
improbability, the frequency of bitterness among Standard Gravure
workers, and others' affection for Wesbecker _ Lucas said his fears
weren't shared by others.
   The schemes became common knowledge among pressroom workers and
supervisors, but upper management was never informed of it, the
Courier-Journal reported.
   Donald Cox, pressroom superintendent and one of Lucas' targets,
said he didn't take Lucas' warnings seriously because he doubted
Wesbecker was skilled enough to pull off the airplane scheme. He
also said he believed Wesbecker was satisfied with the arrangements
of his disability leave.
   Lucas, however, said he knew better.
   ``I knew something was going to happen, but I didn't know when
or what time or where it was coming from,'' he said. ``Every day I
hid in different dark spots of the plant. I didn't go in the
pressroom or stay around the presses,'' he said.
   ``I think what he was doing, he was reaching out to me and I
didn't grasp it,'' he said. ``God forgive me, I didn't grasp it.''
</TEXT>
