<FIRST>r a PM-NewspaperCompetition     10-02 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspaper Competition,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ingersoll Group Mulls Cleveland, Columbus, Others for Expansion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The publisher of the new St. Louis Sun would
consider starting newspapers in 10 other cities if the Sun
succeeds, according to a published report.
   There is no timetable for the projects being considered by
Ingersoll Publications Co., Robert Jelenic, vice president of
Ingersoll and president of the Sun, told Crain's Cleveland Business.
   ``It could be one year or it could be five years,'' Jelenic
said. ``Right now, we're not going around looking at other places.
We're focused on the St. Louis Sun.''
   Ingersoll, based in Princeton, N.J., started the Sun last week,
bucking an industry trend toward closing and consolidation of
big-city papers.
   Other cities the company would consider entering if the Sun
succeeds, Jelenic said, are Cleveland; Columbus, Ohio; Atlanta,
Buffalo, N.Y.; Las Vegas; Los Angeles, Miami, San Diego, Washington
and Orlando, Fla.
   Ingersoll Publications, owned and managed by Ralph Ingersoll II,
owns 40 daily news papers and 150 weeklies.
</TEXT>
