<DOCNO> AP891002-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 0651EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Arafat     10-02 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Arafat,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Urges Tokyo To Cut Trade with Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat, in Japan for the first
time as a guest of the government, said today that this oil-poor
nation must be sensitive to Arab concerns and cut its trade with
Israel, a news report said.
   ``It is not necessary for you to think of our interests, think
of your own interests,'' Japan's Kyodo News Service quoted Arafat
as saying.
   Japan would be making a ``fatal mistake'' by ignoring the
Palestinians, who have the support of 200 million Arabs in a vital
region, it quoted Arafat as saying in a speech at the Foreign
Ministry.
   Japan's trade with Israel last year was roughly $1.2 billion, a
300 percent increase over 1985, according to Israeli government
figures. Japan, meanwhile, relies on oil from the Arab Middle East
for much of its fuel needs.
   Arafat, here on a four-day visit, is expected to discuss his
views on the Middle East peace process in meetings set for Tuesday
with Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu and Foreign Minister Taro
Nakayama.
   Officials have said Arafat was invited as chairman of the
Palestine Liberation Organization, not as president of the
self-proclaimed state of Palestine. Though Arafat had visited Japan
in 1981, he was then a guest of legislators, not the government.
   Foreign Ministry officials said the government invitation was
intended to show Japan's appreciation for Arafat's denunciation of
violence in December. One official said the formal invitation also
was aimed at bolstering Arafat's moderate policy amid reported
pressures from PLO hard-liners advocating a return to terrorist
tactics.
   Later today, Arafat was to attend a ceremony to rename the PLO's
Tokyo office the ``Permanent Mission of Palestine.''
   Japanese officials said the government approved the renaming
with the understanding that the office's legal status would remain
unchanged. Japan is the third country to allow such a renaming,
following France and Italy.
   Japan, like the United States and other Western industrialized
countries, holds that Palestine has yet to meet generally accepted
international law criteria for statehood. Japan has full diplomatic
relations with Israel.
   The PLO was created in 1964, bringing together several competing
Palestinian groups, including Arafat's Al Fatah.
   By 1970, it was conducting guerrilla and terrorist operations
against Israel from bases inside neighboring Jordan. The PLO
currently is based in Tunisia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
