<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 0704EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GangViolence     10-02 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gang Violence,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekend Anti-Gang Sweeps Net Thousand Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people died in weekend gang violence
despite a police crackdown on street hoodlums that resulted in more
than 1,000 arrests, authorities said.
   Gilmar Arias, 19, was found shot to death in the city's harbor
area about 9 a.m. Sunday, said Los Angeles Police Officer Jim
Farris. Arias apparently was the victim of a drive-by shooting.
   Nelson R. Alas, 15, an alleged gang member, was shot and killed
early Sunday in Hollywood, said Detective Bill Humphry. Alas and
another youth were on a bicycle when they were confronted by
members of a rival gang.
   A 25-year-old man died early Saturday in a drive-by killing in
Pacoima, about 15 miles north of downtown Los Angeles, Police Sgt.
Al Yarborough said.
   The man's name was not released.
   Seven people were injured in gang-related attacks, police said.
   Of the 1,092 people arrested, 629 were gang members, police
said. There were 624 arrests Saturday night and 468 arrests on
Friday.
   Most of the arrests were for investigation of misdemeanors,
including drunken driving, narcotics possession and curfew
violations. Police seized 18 guns, 16 of them owned by gang members.
