<FIRST>r p PM-JackieMason-Slur 2ndLd-Writethru a0493 10-02 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackie Mason-Slur, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0493,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newsweek: Comedian Slurred NYC Mayoral Candidate Earlier</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The Newsweek...', to CORRECT that remarks in
Voice were made at dinner party, not during interview.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jackie Mason, who apologized last week
for racial remarks about mayoral candidate David Dinkins,
previously used a slur against the black Democrat in talking to
Newsweek writers, the magazine says.
   Mason called Dinkins ``a fancy shvartze with a mustache,''
Newsweek reported in this week's edition.
   Shvartze is a Yiddish word for a black person. It is often
considered derogatory.
   The Newsweek report followed Mason's resignation last week from
Republican mayoral candidate Rudolph Giuliani's campaign amid an
uproar over remarks Mason made about blacks and published in the
weekly newspaper Village Voice. The remarks were made at a dinner
party at which a Voice writer was present.
   The Voice quoted Mason, an ordained rabbi, as saying Jewish
support for Dinkins was based on guilt because Jews were ``sick
with complexes.''
   The Newsweek remark was made almost a month before the Voice
article appeared.
   Newsweek said that after Mason made his remark about Dinkins to
the writers at a luncheon, Giuliani joined in the laughter and
didn't rebuke Mason.
   Last week, in reacting to Mason's comments published in the
Voice, Giuliani said he had never heard Mason speak that way before.
   On Sunday, Giuliani denied hearing the remark and questioned the
Newsweek article.
   ``As I recall there were four reporters there. I emphasize that
the four reporters did not report it, which means they didn't hear
it or they didn't attach any significance to it at the time,''
Giuliani said.
   Charles Perkins, a Giuliani spokesman, said he heard the remark
and mentioned it to Giuliani, who told Mason's manager ``he thought
it was inappropriate and Jackie should be more careful with his
language.''
   The editor of Newsweek, Maynard Parker, was quoted in today's
New York Times as saying if he had known about the remark at the
time, ``We would have published it four weeks ago.''
   Dinkins, told that Giuliani said he had not heard the remark,
said: ``Put down, `He smiled.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
