<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 0850EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MormonConference     10-02 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mormon Conference,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church President Too Frail To Offer Customary Closing Remarks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in his four-year
ministry, 90-year-old Mormon Church President Ezra Taft Benson was
too feeble to provide the traditional closing address to the
faithful, a church official said.
   ``He has not felt he would speak in this session,'' Gordon B.
Hinckley, Benson's first counselor, said Sunday before the church's
159th Semiannual General Conference ended.
   In recent conferences, Benson, a former U.S. agriculture
secretary, has either delivered or had read for him at least two
talks over two days. Benson's sole address this weekend was a
Saturday sermon on the elderly read for him by Thomas H. Monson,
his second counselor.
   During a session on the priesthood Saturday night, Benson,
seemingly confused, arose and walked to the podium during a sermon
by Hinckley, who cut his remarks short. Benson then said ``amen''
and was helped to his seat.
   Mormon presidents, considered by church members to be prophets,
serve for life.
   On Sunday, members of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles recalled
Mormonism's pioneer heritage of hardship and devotion as they
praised the modern faithful for their self-sacrifice.
   By giving 10 percent of their income to the church, by serving
full-time missions or by remaining at home with young children,
Mormons today are exhibiting the same tenacity as church founder
Brigham Young and his followers, said Elder Dallin H. Oaks.
   ``In every nation, in every worthy occupation and activity,
members of this church face hardships, overcome obstacles and
follow the servants of the Lord Jesus Christ as valiantly as the
pioneers of any age,'' Oaks said.
   Oaks also touched on what was a prominent theme of the
gathering: obedience to the all-male hierarchy of The Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
   ``In our day, as in the days of earlier pioneers, those in the
lead wagons set the direction and signal onward, but it is the
faithful men and women in the wagons which follow that provide the
momentum and motive power for this great work,'' said Oaks.
   None of the speakers at the conference in the Tabernacle on
Temple Square referred directly to last month's excommunication of
George P. Lee, the first high church official in 46 years to have
his membership revoked.
   The church said Lee, a Navajo Indian who has differed with some
church officials in interpreting the Indians' role in the church,
was cut off for apostasy, or abandonment of faith, and conduct
unbecoming a church member.
   The leadership in the Mormon church is headed by the
three-member First Presidency, followed by the Quorum of the Twelve
Apostles, which supervises the First Quorum of the Seventy, the
group to which Lee belonged. Members of the three panels are known
as general authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
