<FIRST>r i PM-Australia-MissingCrew     10-02 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Missing Crew,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Boaters Found Safe After Four Months</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AUK2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLENHEIM, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 42-foot sailboat missing for
almost four months with four men aboard, including an American,
washed ashore with all crew members safe, a relative said today.
   The three-hulled sailboat overturned in heavy seas in early June
and the four survived by collecting rainwater and eating fish,
seaweed and apples, said Malcolm Tomes, brother-in-law of the
boat's skipper.
   The missing boat, the Rose Noelle, washed ashore on Great
Barrier Island about 60 miles northeast of Auckland late Saturday,
Tomes said.
   The boat left Picton, on the northern coast of New Zealand's
South Island, on June 1. The crew planned a three-week Pacific
Islands cruise that was to take them as far as Tonga.
   On board was the boat's owner and skipper, New Zealander John
Glennie, an experienced sailor who designed the boat for
long-distance cruising; Phillip Hoffman and Rick Hellriegel of New
Zealand; and Jim Nalepka, 38, of Minneapolis, Minn., who was in the
second of two years as caterer for the Outward Bound program in New
Zealand.
   Nalepka's sister, Kathy Moynihan of New Brighton, Minn., said
her family was overjoyed.
   ``We never gave up hope. He kept hoping he was safe. ...This is
wonderful,'' she said.
   Glennie said today that late on June 3, a strong southerly wind
grew to a 60-knot gale.
   ``About six o'clock in the morning there was a huge wave, and it
just flipped the boat upside down,'' Glennie said.
   The Rose-Noelle floated on its crossbeams, with the cabin top
about two feet below water, he said. The craft was stable and would
not sink unless it had broken apart, Glennie said.
   The boat was reported missing on June 24, after it failed to
arrive in Tonga. The last radio contact with the crew came on June
9 from near the Kermadec Islands, about 620 miles northeast of New
Zealand.
   The four survivors, who are all in good health, on Saturday
spent their first night on land in 120 days. On Sunday, they broke
into an empty cabin, where they found warm clothes.
   John Dalmeida, head of the Outward Bound school in Anakiwa, New
Zealand, told the Star Tribune of Minneapolis that the four planned
to go to Auckland to a hospital for tests.
   ``I received a collect call from someone named Jim,'' Dalmeida
said. ``We weren't going to accept it at first. We don't have a Jim
working here anymore....but it turned out to be him. None of us
could believe it. He said, `We're alive. Do I still have my job?'''
   ``They said it is a long, miraculous story,'' said Dalmeida.
``They spent lots of time praying, as you might imagine, and when
they hit land they couldn't believe they were saved.''
   Peter Speck, an island resident, was first to meet the tired
sailors at the cabin.
   ``At first I thought these guys were nuts,'' said Speck. ``They
were talking about being upside down for four months. I couldn't
believe it.''
   Their families had given them up for dead, Tomes said.``We were
absolutely ecstatic to hear John's voice on the phone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
