<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     10-02 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Lawmakers Divided Over Syrian Presence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-Gloom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese leaders met for a third day
today in an effort to end their country's 14-year-old civil war,
but they remained deeply divided over the Syrian army's presence in
Lebanon.
   Saudi officials sought to smooth over the differences as the 63
deputies of Lebanon's National Assembly convened in this Saudi
Arabian mountain resort.
   Conference sources conceded that discord between the 33
Christian and 30 Moslem deputies, largely mirroring the sectarian
divide in Lebanon, was hampering progress.
   Druse Moslem chieftain Walid Jumblatt and Shiite Moslem leader
Nabih Berri, Syria's main allies in Lebanon, oppose a peace plan
proposed by the Arab League because they claim proposed political
reforms do not go far enough in stripping the Christians of their
long-held domination of government, parliament, the judiciary and
army.
   The two warlords, whose support will be essential for any
agreement reached in Taif, flew to Tehran Sunday night for talks
with Iranian leaders. Iran is Syria's ally.
   Tehran Radio, monitored in Cyprus, quoted Berri as expressing
``strong opposition'' to the Arab League plan.
   Despite the political problems, a cease-fire called by the Arab
League Sept. 22 to end six months of fierce artillery battles
between the Syrians and Christians seemed to be holding.
   In Beirut today, Syrian troops and their militia allies fired on
a Lebanese military helicopter trying to rescue the pilot of an air
force jet fighter that crashed in the Mediterranean off north
Lebanon, military sources said.
   Syrian troops in speedboats later picked up the pilot,
identified as Maj. George Sirhal, and took him to the
Syrian-controlled northern port of Tripoli, the sources said. The
Syrians promised to return him.
   The Syrian Army, which has 40,000 troops in Lebanon, controls 70
percent of the Mediterranean country. It entered Lebanon in 1976, a
year after the civil war broke out, under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   Conference sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a
sizeable group of parliamentarians, mostly Moslems, want the
Syrians to remain in Lebanon.
   Others proposed a phased Syrian withdrawal from Moslem sectors
of Beirut to the Bekaa Valley in east Lebanon, the Syrians' main
stronghold, over two years while the country's constitutional
structure, virtually dismantled by the war, is rebuilt.
   ``Who would take over the responsibility of keeping law and
order if the Syrians left with the (Lebanese) army divided?'' said
Zaher Khatib, a Sunni Moslem.
   But most of the Christian deputies, backed by some Moslems
allied with Iraq, Syria's archrival in the Arab world, demanded an
immediate Syrian withdrawal.
   ``The Syrian military presence in Lebanon is illegimate ... the
Syrians should be made to withdraw from Lebanon within a short
period,'' said George Saadeh, a Maronite who leads the right-wing
Phalange Party.
   Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun has opposed accepting
political reforms aimed at giving Moslems an equal share of power
with the long-dominant Christians, until the Syrians pull out.
   The Taif meeting, the first by Lebanon's parliament outside
Lebanese territory, was convened by the Arab League to negotiate
political reforms and formulate a ``national reconciliation
charter.''
</TEXT>
