<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 0932EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-Haig     10-02 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Haig,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haig Urges China To Keep Doors Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Secretary of State Alexander Haig, one of
the few prominent Americans to visit China since it crushed a
pro-democracy movement, urged the country today to keep its doors
open to the West.
   Haig, in a speech delivered to a business symposium, stressed
that relations between China and the United States, now at a low
ebb, are fundamental for Asian stability.
   ``The Chinese people should continue to look outward for their
own benefit and for the benefit of both the region and the world,''
Haig said at an economic cooperation symposium hosted by the China
International Trust and Investment Corp.
   Haig, one of the most prominent Americans to visit China since
the June military crackdown, has been given a warm welcome here. He
was invited to sit at the head table with Premier Li Peng during a
National Day reception Saturday, and he joined China's top leaders
on the Tiananmen Square rostrum for a 40th anniversary show Sunday
evening.
   Washington curtailed high-level official contacts to protest the
June violence, in which troops killed hundreds and perhaps
thousands of people in Beijing during suppression of crush
pro-democracy demonstrations.
   Haig, a private citizen, is now president of the international
advisory firm Worldwide Associates.
   ``Danger, setback and upheaval are the constant companions of
economic change,'' Haig said. ``Yet the wisest course, however
troubled in the short term, is the one that offers the most
progress for the greatest number.
   ``That is why we all support the Chinese resolve to continue
with the program of economic reform.''
   The conservatives now in control in Beijing have pledged that
there will be no change in China's policy of economic reform.
   However, a retrenchment policy that began when inflation and
growth got out of hand last fall and accelerated after the June
events has raised fears that China is returning to reliance on
central control of the economy.
   Haig devoted a large part of his speech to making the point that
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is now carrying out reforms
in his country because the West forced the Soviet military hand.
   ``Gorbachev's `new thinking' was therefore in my judgment the
product of a realistic analysis that the lagging Soviet economy
could not bear the additional burden of a dead-ended and isolated
foreign policy.''
   Haig warned that even today, the Soviets produce half of all the
world's military material and its forces are still largely
offensive.
   ``Let us be careful that in the course of what may be a
compulsive, competitive frenzy of disarmament that at the end we
are not worse off than we were before,'' he said.
</TEXT>
