<FIRST>r a PM-SegregatedChurch     10-02 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Segregated Church,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Segregated Church Allows Blacks To Attend Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black student praised the congregation of
an all-white church that allowed him to attend worship services
after turning him away the week before.
   ``They are good people,'' the Rev. Vincent Taylor of Akron, Ohio
said after attending services Sunday at Central Baptist Church.
``The church needs to be commended.''
   Taylor, a 24-year-old divinity student at Selma University, was
joined by three other black men who walked into the sanctuary
before the start of services at the 1,300-member church.
   ``The church has allowed Christ to prevail and the gates of hell
to be defeated,'' he said. There were no incidents and the men were
greeted warmly on the front steps as they prepared to leave.
   ``This is a wonderful, great day,'' said the church's pastor,
the Rev. George Jones.
   He said the 18-member board of deacons met Friday night and
``made the decision to seat anyone who comes to worship.''
   The full congregation will vote Oct. 11 on whether to back the
deacons, he said. The formal policy of not admitting blacks dates
from the days of civil rights demonstrations in the 1960s.
   ``I cannot speak for the congregation, (but) I think if it's
ever rescinded, now is the time it would be,'' the pastor said.
   On Sept. 24, Taylor and two women students at the predominately
black Christian college arrived at the church planning to attend
the service, but a deacon told them the church had a policy
excluding them from worshiping there.
   Taylor said he was ``shocked and encouraged'' Saturday when a
telephone call to Jones revealed a change in the policy. After the
service, he called Jones ``a great preacher.''
   Taylor said much of the controversy over his bid to attend
services at Central Baptist had been blown out of proportion. He
also denied ever saying that a $50 bet with one of his professors
prompted him to seek entry.
</TEXT>
