<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-FosterCare     10-02 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Foster Care,480</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Supreme Court Refuses to Revive Maryland Suit About Foster Home
^By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive an
allegedly abused foster child's federal lawsuit against the social
workers and government agency that placed him in his foster home.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court
ruling in a Maryland case that no such right to sue exists.
   Charles Milburn Jr., now 20, was not quite 2 years old when in
1971 the Anne Arundel County Department of Social Services placed
him with foster parents Karl and Wendy Tucker of Glen Burnie.
   His parents voluntarily had placed him in the custody of the
social services agency.
   Milburn's federal lawsuit against the Tuckers, individual social
workers and the county agency said he was subjected to physical
abuse for nearly two years before being removed from the Tuckers'
home.
   The suit, which sought $66 million in damages, said his injuries
included two leg fractures, a facial laceration and severe burns
that left his hands permanently scarred and disabled.
   The suit alleged that Mrs. Tucker, with her husband's knowledge,
inflicted all the injuries _ including her immersing the
youngster's hands in boiling water.
   Milburn's suit, based on alleged violations of his
constitutional due-process rights, was thrown out by U.S. District
Judge Joseph C. Howard, and the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
upheld the dismissal last March 31.
   Such lawsuits must establish that the alleged harm was caused by
the government or some government agent. The 4th Circuit ruled that
the Tuckers did not fit the definition of government agents.
   ``The state of Maryland was not responsible for ... the
(alleged) physical child abuse itself,'' the appeals court said.
``It exercised no coercive power over the Tuckers; neither did it
encourage them.''
   The appeals court noted that a parallel lawsuit filed in state
court, alleging Maryland tort law violations, is awaiting action.
   The Supreme Court last February ruled that public officials may
not be sued in federal court when their alleged gross negligence
permits a child to be abused by a parent.
   That decision in a Wisconsin case said a state does not have a
constitutional duty to protect people, including abused children,
who are not in the state's custody.
   Writing for the court then, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
said, ``As a general matter, we conclude that a state's failure to
protect an individual against private violence simply does not
constitute a violation of the (Constitution's) due process clause.''
   That constitutional provision bars deprivation of life, liberty
and property without due process of law.
   A footnote in the February decision, however, said the justices
were leaving undecided whether due-process considerations would
arise in the case of children abused by foster parents.
   The case is Milburn vs. Anne Arundel County Department of Social
Services, 89-96.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
