<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia-Violence     10-02 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia-Violence,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Parties Clash, Two Reported Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Namibia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clashes between two political factions
vying to lead Namibia into independence left two people dead and at
least 30 injured, officials and news reports said today.
   A 27-year-old man was clubbed to death when he and four friends
stopped at a small shop in the northern town of Oshakati on
Saturday, said Gerhard Roux, spokesman for Namibia's adminstrator,
Louis Pienaar.
   Roux said the victim and his friends were supporters of the
Democratic Turnhalle Alliance and were attacked by about 80 backers
of the South-West Africa People's Organization, the party favored
in the country's elections next month.
   Also, a SWAPO supporter was beaten to death in Oshakati and the
homes and shops of party members were attacked in northern towns
during the weekend, The Star of Johannesburg said.
   Roux said at least 30 people were hurt Sunday, one critically,
when people disrupted rallies held by the Democratic Turnhalle
alliance around Oshakati.
   The clashes included gunfire, grenades, fires and looting,
according to the South-West Africa Broadcasting Corp., which is
controlled by the South African government.
   The elections are for the national assembly that will be
empowered to draw up a constitution for Namibia, which has been
ruled by South Africa for 74 years.
   South Africa, which agreed to relinquish control of Namibia
under a regional peace accord, has not announced a date for
independence but it is expected to be early next year.
   The predominantly black SWAPO, which waged a 23-year bush war
against South African rule, is a leftist-leaning party that draws
its strongest support from the Ovambo people of northern Namibia.
   The alliance, a moderate, multiracial coalitiion, is expected to
be the second-leading vote getter out of the 10 parties contesting
the race.
   There have been sporadic cases of violence since the election
campaign began formally in July, and it has increased as the
election nears.
</TEXT>
