<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-BurningTree     10-02 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Burning Tree,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maryland Club That Won't Admit Women Fails To Regain Tax Break</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A golf club that has counted presidents and
members of Congress among its members failed today in a Supreme
Court bid to regain a tax break revoked because of the club's
refusal to admit women as members.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that Maryland
officials did not violate the rights of Burning Tree Club members
by scraping a tax break worth more than $300,000 a year.
   Burning Tree has 440 members and is located just outside the
nation's capital in the affluent suburb of Bethesda, Md., The club
had a long-term agreement with the state to preserve its open
spaces in return for favorable property-tax treatment.
   But in 1986, the Maryland Legislature canceled the agreement.
The club, an all-male bastion since its founding in 1922, was told
it must either admit women or have its land taxed at full value.
   Maryland officials also said the club's refusal to admit women
violated the state's Equal Rights Amendment enacted in 1972.
   The Maryland Court of Appeals ruled in March that a law forcing
the club to choose between admitting women or losing its tax break
did not violate the members' freedom-of-association rights.
   The law ``does not even prohibit Burning Tree from
discriminating,'' the state's highest court said. ``It simply
provides that if Burning Tree continues to discriminate, its
property will be assessed in the same manner as the property of
other taxpayers in the area.''
   Burning Tree officials argued their club should be exempt from
recent Supreme Court rulings empowering government officials to end
sex discrimination at such large, national organizations as the
Jaycees and Rotary Clubs.
   Burning Tree's appeal said the club is a more intimate group and
has a limited purpose: providing a ``congenial'' setting for men
devoted to the game of golf.
   The Maryland appeals court, however, ruled that the state is
only withdrawing a benefit, not forcing the club to accept women.
   ``The state is simply declining to subsidize any organization
that engages in discriminatory activities,'' the state court said.
``Just because Burning Tree's members may have associational rights
does not oblige the state to subsidize the exercise of those
rights.''
   A Supreme Court ruling in 1988 gave states and local communities
power to ban sex and race bias at private clubs smaller than the
Jaycees and Rotary. The court upheld a New York City law banning
discrimination by private clubs with more than 400 members.
   Two justices who joined that unanimous opinion, Harry A.
Blackmun and Anthony M. Kennedy, once belonged to male-only clubs.
   The case is Burning Tree vs. Maryland, 88-1970.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-ArmySchools     10-02 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Army Schools,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Agrees to Review Army School Case From Georgia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether the Army must bargain with unions over the wages and fringe
benefits received by teachers at Army-run schools.
   The court said it will review a ruling that the Army had a legal
duty to bargain with teachers at two Fort Stewart, Ga., schools
attended by children of military personnel.
   The teachers union, an affiliate of the National Education
Association, sought a 13.5 percent wage increase in 1987 and
various fringe benefit improvements for teachers at the two
elementary schools.
   The Federal Labor Relations Authority ordered the Army to
negotiate with the union over the demands, and that order was
upheld in November 1988 by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The appeals court rejected arguments that the proposed wage hike
and benefit improvements would interfere with the Army's right to
set its own budget.
   ``Although the proposals obligate the Army to spend funds for
salaries in the succeeding fiscal year, the government will
appropriate funds before the Army incurs these obligations,'' the
appeals court said.
   The appeals court also rejected the Army's claim that it should
be permitted to set teacher salaries according to how much teachers
are paid in local public schools.
   There is no compelling need for such comparability, the 11th
Circuit court said.
   In the appeal acted on today, Bush administration lawyers said
other groups of federal workers _ whose salaries are not fixed by
law _ could be affected if the appeals court's approach is adopted
nationwide.
   The appeal said other federal appeals courts have ruled that the
Army is under no such obligation.
   In urging the justices to reject the government's appeal,
lawyers for the teachers union said only a tiny fraction of federal
workers _ less than one percent _ might be affected if the appeals
court's approach prevailed nationwide.
   The case is Fort Stewart Schools vs. Federal Labor Relations
Authority, 89-65.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
