<FIRST>r i PM-Afghan-Rebels     10-02 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghan-Rebels,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels to Lobby For U.N. Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebels said today they will
send a delegation to New York to lobby for Afghanistan's seat at
the United Nations, which is now occupied by the Soviet-backed
government.
   Najibullah Lafrie, information minister in the guerrillas'
self-proclaimed government-in-exile, said the group also would meet
with U.S. State Department officials to discuss fighting the flow
of heroin from war-torn Afghanistan.
   The four-man delegation, led by the rebels' interior minister,
Yunis Khalis, will be present for the U.N. General Assembly debate
on Afghanistan in late October or early November, the information
minister said.
   The Moslem rebels have yet to achieve any U.N. status.
   Seven resistance parties based in Pakistan formed what they said
was an interim government in February after the Soviet Union
completed its troop withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   The Marxist government in Kabul still controls major cities with
heavy material support from Moscow, but the insurgents virtually
rule the countryside.
   Four Moslem countries officially recognize the rebel government.
But the main backers of the rebels _ Pakistan and the United States
_ do not because it doesn't include several guerrilla groups based
inside Afghanistan and in Iran.
   The information minister said the rebel government would offer
to help stop the flow of opium and its refined derivative, heroin,
from Afghanistan.
   ``Our government shall play an outstanding role in the
elimination of the menace of drugs and narcotics,'' he said.
   The rebels have denied allegations that they occasionally have
traded drugs for weapons in their 11-year-old fight to topple the
Kabul government.
   Afghanistan and northwestern Pakistan have a centuries-old
tradition of opium poppy cultivation.
</TEXT>
