<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Patronage     10-02 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Patronage,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Agrees to Hear Case from Illinois About Political Patronage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today set the stage for an
important ruling on political patronage, agreeing to decide whether
public employers may be forced to put aside partisanship when
hiring, promoting and transferring workers.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by two men and a woman who
said their job status suffered because they didn't support the
Republican Party in Illinois.
   The court also agreed to hear a related appeal by Illinois
officials seeking to preserve patronage powers in determining when
government workers may be laid off and rehired.
   Cynthia Rutan, Franklin Taylor and James Moore asked the court
to reinstate their lawsuit against Illinois Gov. James Thompson and
state and local GOP officials.
   They said their rights of free speech and association, protected
by the Constitution's First Amendment, were violated.
   Ms. Rutan said she repeatedly was denied promotions to
supervisory positions in the state Rehabilitative Services
Department because she did not support Republicans candidates.
   Taylor, an equipment operator, allegedly was denied an Illinois
Transportation Department transfer to another county because party
officials opposed it.
   And Moore said the state Corrections Department has refused to
hire him since 1978 because he could not get the backing of key
Republican leaders.
   ``Those who are politically favored are promoted, transferred or
hired,'' they said. ``Those who are not so favored are not
promoted, transferred or hired.''
   They sued for more than $1 billion in damages, and sought to
have control of the state employment system shifted to a
court-appointed federal receiver.
   A federal judge threw out their suit, and the 7th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals, by a 7-2 vote in February, upheld the dismissal.
   The appeals court, relying on a series of Supreme Court
decisions, said public employees enjoy broad First Amendment
protection from being fired or threatened with firing. But the high
court has not extended the same constitutional safeguards to
hiring, promotion and transfer, the appeals court said.
   The Supreme Court, in a 1980 ruling that significantly weakened
the patronage system, said government workers may not be fired
solely because of their political affiliation unless that was an
appropriate requirement for carrying out their jobs.
   The 7th Circuit court said, ``Employment decisions not involving
dismissals ... are significantly less coercive and disruptive than
discharges ...A person denied a promotion or transfer ... still
retains his job and his ability to meet his financial obligations.''
   The appeals court said a judge should be reluctant to intrude
into the political process and become ``a platonic guardian over
state employment systems.''
   Changes in the patronage system are better left to legislatures,
the appeals court added.
   But the appeals court ruled in favor of two workers laid off
from state jobs, saying layoffs are similar in key respects to
firings. It ordered additional hearings in those cases.
   The cases are Rutan vs. Illinois Republican Party, 88-1872, and
Frech vs. Rutan, 88-2074.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Bail     10-02 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Bail,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Consider Bail Issue in New Mexico Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
increasing the federal government's power to keep some accused
criminals behind bars while they await trial.
   The court said it will review a ruling in a New Mexico case that
forces the government to free, on bail, some defendants deemed to
be dangerous or a risk to flee before trial.
   A federal appeals court said pretrial release is required _ even
for a defendant who otherwise could be held in custody _ if a
pretrial detention hearing is not held the first time that person
appears before a judge or magistrate.
   The justices in 1987 upheld a federal law allowing denial of
bail before trial to people deemed dangerous to the community, even
if accused of non-violent crimes.
   Before the 1984 law, called the Bail Reform Act, pretrial bail
generally would be denied only if a judge determined the defendant
was likely to flee.
   In practice, however, federal judges could get around the old
law by setting very high bail, ostensibly aimed at guaranteeing the
defendant's appearance in court but effectively keeping the accused
in custody while awaiting trial.
   A provision in the 1984 law states that a hearing to determine
whether pretrial detention is justified must be held ``immediately
upon the person's first appearance before the judicial officer,
unless that person or the attorney for the government seeks a
continuance.''
   A federal trial judge and the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled that the ``first appearance'' provision of the law had been
ignored in the case of Guadalupe Montalvo-Murillo, charged with
possessing nearly $1 million worth of cocaine.
   Montalvo-Murillo, a citizen of Mexico then legally living in
this country, was stopped last February while driving a pickup
truck near the Mexican border at Orogrande, N.M.
   U.S. Customs Service agents found 72 pounds of cocaine, with a
wholesale value of almost $1 million, in the truck.
   At a Feb. 16 proceeding, a federal magistrate put off a
detention hearing until Feb. 21. After that hearing, the magistrate
decided to release Montalvo-Murillo on $50,000 bail and other
conditions.
   Government prosecutors appealed to a federal judge, who ruled
that Montalvo-Murillo posed both a danger to the community and a
risk to flee.
   But the judge ruled that the New Mexico magistrate, in
postponing the detention hearing for five days, violated the
federal bail law's ``first appearance'' rule. The judge said the
only appropriate remedy was the defendant's release on bail.
   Montalvo-Murillo was freed on $88,500 bail, and has been a
fugitive from justice ever since. He is believed to have fled to
Mexico.
   The 10th Circuit court upheld the judge's ruling that the only
remedy for denying a defendant a timely detention hearing is
release on bail _ even if the result of the hearing would have been
holding the defendant without bail.
   In the appeal acted on today, government lawyers argued that
automatic release for such procedural infractions is not required
by the 1984 law.
   ``The court of appeals erred in imposing a remedy so plainly at
odds with the objectives of the Bail Reform Act,'' the appeal said.
   Lawyers for Montalvo-Murillo urged the court to reject the
government's appeal, contending among other things that their
client's status as a fugitive makes his case moot.
   The case is U.S. vs. Montalvo-Murillo, 89-163.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1053EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Dworkin     10-02 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Dworkin,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Pornography Appeal in California Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by
an anti-pornography activist who says sexually explicit photographs
and caricatures in Hustler magazine libeled her and invaded her
privacy.
   The court, without comment, refused to revive a $150 million
lawsuit by feminist author Andrea Dworkin.
   A federal judge threw out the suit, and the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals upheld the dimissal last January.
   The Hustler references to Dworkin were opinion, not statements
of fact, and therefore are protected by the free-speech guarantees
in the Constitution's First Amendment, the appeals court said.
   ``Dworkin errs by limiting opinion to high-minded discourse,''
the appeals court said.
   Shielding all opinion from lawsuits ``means that outrageous and
outlandish statements are sometimes protected,'' the appeals court
said. But it added, ``Ludicrous statements are much less insidious
and debilitating than falsities that bear the ring of truth. We
have little doubt that the outrageous and outlandish will be
recognized for what they are.''
   The appeals court also noted that the Supreme Court in 1988
threw out a $200,000 award against Hustler won by television
evangelist Jerry Falwell, who accused the magazine of causing him
emotional distress by publishing a pornographic parody.
   In that decision, the justices gave broad free-speech protection
to parodies and satire.
   Dworkin said she was viciously lampooned by Hustler and its
publisher, Larry Flynt, because of her opposition to pornography.
She is the author of an Indianapolis ordinance, since declared
unconstitutional, that defined pornography as a violation of
women's civil rights and permitted lawsuits against pornographers.
   Dworkin sued over features published in three 1984 issues of
Hustler. One was a cartoon of two women engaged in lesbian sex in
which one woman says to the other, ``You remind me so much of
Andrea Dworkin.''
   A second feature included a series of photographs that referred
to ``the Andrea Dworkin fan club.'' A photograph in a third issue
identified a woman engaged in sex as Dworkin's mother.
   Dworkin sued in Wyoming but the case was transferred to a
federal court in Los Angeles at the request of Hustler.
   The case is Dworkin vs. Hustler, 88-1900.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1054EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Libel     10-02 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Libel,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Libel Award Against Rhode Island Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a $278,600
libel award against a Pawtucket, R.I., newspaper.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that news
stories may be libelous even if they contain no false statement.
   Today's action sets no national legal precedent, but instead
leaves unresolved conflicting lower court rulings on the issue.
   The Pawtucket Evening Times, published by a subsidiary of the
Ingersoll Newspapers group, was ordered to pay $28,600 in
compensatory damages and $250,000 in punitive damages to Dr. Paul
Healey, a prominent Pawtucket surgeon who chaired the local YMCA's
board of directors.
   The Rhode Island Supreme Court upheld the jury award last March
3, ruling that an Evening Times article falsely implied that Healey
was asked, and refused, to interrupt a YMCA board meeting to help a
heart attack victim.
   Jerry Lampinski had gone to the board's June 23, 1980 meeting to
criticize the firings of two YMCA staff members but was ordered by
Healey to leave.
   Lampinski then joined a group of protesters about 200 yards from
the room where the board meeting was being held. He collapsed
minutes later.
   Lampinski was given first aid almost immediately, and an
ambulance arrived within 10 minutes. The heart attack, however, was
fatal.
   An Evening Times article two days later reported that
Lampinski's sons were angry over the YMCA board's treatment of
their father.
   The article said the family felt Lampinski ``should have been
given early attention by either a doctor or a paramedic at the
board meeting.''
   The next paragraph said, ``Dr. Paul J. Healey is Y president and
was at the meeting when Lampinski collapsed.''
   The following paragraph noted that Lampinski collapsed 200 yards
from where the board was meeting, and the article went on to quote
a YMCA official refuting any implication that Healey or any other
board member was lax in responding to an emergency.
   The official was quoted as saying that board members, when told
of Lampinski's collapse, also were told that ``the situation was
well in hand and already being taken care of.''
   In its ruling, Rhode Island's highest court said the June 25
article that included the Lampinski family criticism could have
``created the implication that (Healey) was asked and refused to
help Lampinski and that there was enough time for (him) to render
aid.''
   The state court added: ``The evidence could support a finding
that (the newspaper) knew these implications were false or that it
acted in reckless disregard of whether these implications were true
or false ... The defamation here really consists of what was left
unprinted as well as what was actually printed.''
   Using a legal definition employed by other state courts, the
Rhode Island court said publishing an opinion can be libelous ``if
it implies the allegation of undisclosed defamatory facts as the
basis for the opinion.''
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the Evening Times
argued that the legal definition used by the state court violates
free-speech rights.
   ``Only false statements of fact,'' and not the reporting of
someone's stated opinion, can be libelous, they said.
   The newspaper's appeal was supported in a
``friend-of-the-court'' brief sumbitted by five news media
organizations _ the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press,
the National Association of Broadcasters, the Newsletter
Association, the Radio-Television News Directors Association and
the Society of Professional Journalists.
   They said the Evening Times had been punished ``for attempting
to fairly and neutrally report both sides of a controversial local
matter.''
   The case is New England Newspapers Inc. vs. Healey, 88-1939.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1056EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Booklets     10-02 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Booklets,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Anti-Abortion Protesters Lose Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people convicted of trespassing for
handing out anti-abortion booklets to students outside a Texas high
school lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that distribution
of the ``pro-life'' literature on school grounds was not protected
by the Constitution's free-speech guarantees.
   John Harris, Patricia Murphy and Charles Reed were arrested
outside Friendswood High School in Galveston County on Jan. 22,
1987, after refusing to leave.
   A state jury convicted them of criminal trespass, and a judge
sentenced each to 90 days probation and 40 hours of community
service.
   The high school, where more than 1,000 students attend classes,
is fronted by a public road that has no adjacent sidewalk. There is
no access to students from the roadside because most arrive by car
or bus, and are dropped off on school grounds.
   In the appeal acted on today, the three convicted trespassers
contended that their peaceful action before the start of classes
should be constitutionally protected.
   ``The vehicle unloading area and adjacent grounds in front of
the school ... should be considered a limited public forum'' where
distribution of literature is allowed, the appeal argued.
   Under past free-speech rulings, a limited public forum is an
area opened for use by certain speakers or on certain occasions.
   But a Texas appeals court ruled that the Friendswood High
grounds are not any kind of public forum, and the handing out of
booklets there is not constitutionally protected. The appeals court
upheld the convictions.
   ``The place is not an area which by tradition has been devoted
to public assembly or debate by the general public ... there is no
evidence that it had ever been opened by the school authorities as
a place for public expressive activity,'' the state court said.
   It added: ``A limited public forum cannot be created ... simply
because members of the public are permitted to come and go at
will.''
   The case is Harris vs. Texas, 88-2077.
</TEXT>
