<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Bankruptcy     10-02 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Bankruptcy,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Will Hear Pennsylvania Victims' Rights Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court said today it will consider
placing new limits on the ability of convicted criminals to avoid
making restitution to their victims by declaring bankruptcy.
   The court agreed to hear an appeal by Pennsylvania officials
seeking to recover $4,145 from a couple who pleaded guilty to
welfare fraud.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled against Pennsylvania
welfare officials last March in the case of Edward and Debora
Davenport of Bucks County.
   The Davenports pleaded guilty in 1985 to welfare fraud. Each was
sentenced to one year probation and ordered to make monthly
restitution payments of $208 until $4,145 was collected.
   The Davenports sought protection in 1987 under Chapter 13 of the
federal bankruptcy code.
   As amended by Congress in 1978, Chapter 13 is designed to give
debtors various court-supervised options to repay part of what they
owe and eventually be rid of their debts.
   A federal bankruptcy judge ruled in 1988 that the couple
fulfilled its Chapter 13 obligations without making the restitution
payments to the state.
   The 3rd Circuit court upheld the judge's decision. The appeals
court said excusing the Davenports from the restitution payments is
in line with the 1978 amendments Congress made to the bankruptcy
code.
   Otherwise, the appeals court said, ``restitution conceivably
could deplete all the debtor's resources before any distribution is
made to the other creditors.''
   The appeals court ruling seems to conflict with a 1986 Supreme
Court ruling that barred criminals from using another part of the
bankruptcy code, Chapter 7, to avoid restitution.
   Unlike the Chapter 13 provisions, people who declare bankruptcy
under Chapter 7 must liquidate their assets. The proceeds then are
divided among creditors.
   The appeals court said the 1986 Supreme Court ruling is limited
to Chapter 7.
   The appeals court said Chapter 7, unlike Chapter 13, specifies
that ``a fine, penalty or forfeiture payable to and for the benefit
of a governmental unit'' is not considered a debt for purposes of
bankruptcy.
   If Chapter 13 improperly creates ``a haven for criminals,'' it
is up to Congress, not the courts, to correct the problem, the
appeals court said.
   ``Where Congress has enacted legislation which arguably affects
state criminal proceedings, it is not the function of this court to
cure any perceived defects in that legislation,'' the appeals court
said.
   In the appeal acted on today, Pennsylvania officials noted that
restitution payments are an option to be considered by sentencing
judges in all states, and are required in many states.
   The case is Pennsylvania vs. Davenport, 89-156.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Safety     10-02 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Safety,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Lets States File Charges for Safety and Health Neglect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that allows states to file criminal charges against employers
accused of neglecting the health and safety of workers.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling in an Illinois
case that federal workplace regulations do not bar such state
prosecutions.
   Five officials of Chicago Magnet Wire Corp. are awaiting trial
on charges they recklessly injured 42 workers by exposing them to
toxic chemicals, extreme heat and other unsafe conditions at a
wire-coating plant.
   Prosecutors said conditions at the plant were extremely
hazardous, and accused the officials of callously disregarding
worker safety.
   Prosecutors said air in the plant was filled with smoke and
chemical fumes, temperatures reached 300 degrees on catwalks and
employees were not allowed to wear masks.
   The state said workers often passed out from the heat and fumes,
and on at least one occasion the plant manager laughed at an
employee who suffered enamel burns.
   Chicago Magnet Wire officials argued that the criminal charges
should be thrown out because the federal government pre-empted
state prosecutions when it enacted the Occupational Safety and
Health Act of 1970.
   The officials said permitting such prosecutions would allow
``wholly uninformed and, most likely, wholly unconcerned'' local
prosecutors and juries to decide when a factory is unsafe. They
said the job should be left to ``experienced and knowledgeable
federal officials setting uniform national workplace safety
standards.''
   Their appeal was supported by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and
other business groups that said allowing criminal prosecutions will
cause ``regulatory chaos.''
   In refusing to squelch the prosecution, the Illinois Supreme
Court last February said, ``State criminal law can provide a
valuable and forceful supplement to insure that workers are
adequately protected and that particular egregious conduct receives
appropriate punishment.''
   The Chicago Magnet Wire officials indicted were Anthony Jordan,
president; Kevin Keane, plant manager; Frank Asta, maintenance
foreman; Allan Simon, plant engineer; and Gerald Colby, an
engineering and maintenance supervisor.
   If convicted, they face maximum sentences of 10 to 20 years in
prison.
   The case is Asta vs. Illinois, 88-1783.
</TEXT>
