<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Insurance     10-02 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Insurance,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says States May Require Auto Insurance Despite Religious Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let states require
automobile insurance for motorists who say it violates their
religious convictions.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by a South Dakota
man who believes having insurance belittles a promise from God to
provide in any situation.
   Lindy Cosgrove of Reliance, S.D., was stopped by a state trooper
in January 1988 while driving on a road closed because of a
blizzard.
   When he did not produce proof he had car insurance, Cosgrove was
charged with violating a state law requiring motorists to
``maintain financial responsibility'' for motor vehicles.
   The law requires either liability insurance or the posting of a
$75,000 bond or $50,000 certificate of deposit to protect others
who might be injured by a motorist.
   Cosgrove pleaded not guilty, saying that since 1972 he has
refused, because of his religious beliefs, all forms of insurance.
   As evidence of his sincerity, Cosgrove said he and his wife
refused free insurance from their employers.
   Cosgrove was fined $75, and his license could be revoked under
the state law.
   The South Dakota Supreme Court ruled in May that while
Cosgrove's religious beliefs apparently are sincere, the state has
a legitimate interest in requiring car insurance.
   The law ``is clearly designed to protect the public,'' the state
court said. Without the law, damages caused by car accidents
``could be borne by the public at large rather than those who are
responsible,'' the state court said.
   It added that the options of a bond or certificate of deposit
permit Cosgrove to maintain financial responsibility for his
driving without purchasing insurance.
   But Cosgrove said the bond or the certificate would be a
tremendous economic burden for him.
   The alternatives ``place an unmistakable burden on Cosgrove's
free exercise of his religious beliefs,'' his lawyers said.
   They also argued that the state's interest in requiring
insurance is less than compelling because many motorists _ tourists
from out of state, for example _ are permitted to drive without
insurance.
   The Supreme Court in 1985, by a 4-4 vote, barred Nebraska
officials from requiring a driver's license photograph for a woman
who believes the Bible forbids such a ``graven image.'' But that
tie vote, while upholding a lower court ruling in favor of the
woman, established no national precedent.
   In other cases, the high court has ruled for individuals whose
observance of the Sabbath conflicted with state authority.
   Last March, the justices unanimously barred states from denying
unemployment benefits to people who refuse to work on their Sabbath
even if the refusal is based on individual religious belief rather
than a religious group's doctrine.
   The case acted on today is Cosgrove vs. South Dakota, 89-10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0100 </DOCNO>
