<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Postal     10-02 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Postal,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Appeal by Older Postal Inspectors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by
older U.S. Postal Service inspectors who say they are being forced
illegally to transfer to other cities.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the
inspectors are not victims of illegal age discrimination.
   The Postal Service, which employs more than 1,900 inspectors,
has faced a problem of chronic staff shortages in 14 major
metropolitan areas.
   The service in 1980 adopted what it calls its career path policy
to ease the big-city shortages.
   Inspectors are urged to volunteer for work in the big cities. As
an incentive, inspectors who have spent two years in one of the big
cities are exempt from similar transfers later on when they reach
senior-level status.
   Also, anyone who has served five years in one of the 14
metropolitan areas is eligible to be asked for reassignment.
   Another provision of the career path policy puts senior-level
inspectors who have not worked in the big cities at the top of the
list for involuntary transfers.
   It is that so-called senior-first rule that was challenged by
the older inspectors. They said the policy disproportionately harms
inspectors over age 40.
   A federal judge ruled that the provision violates the federal
Age Discrimination in Employment Act, which is aimed at protecting
older workers against arbitrary bias.
   The judge's ruling was overturned in December 1988 by the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals here.
   The appeals court said the senior-first rule should not be
examined in isolation.
   ``The senior-first rule was not a free-standing element of an
employment program,'' the appeals court said. ``Under the career
path policy, every (senior-level) employee was expected to spend
five years in a major metropolitan area. Thus, each (senior-level)
employee can fulfill this uniform service requirement through
either an early voluntary, or a later involuntary, transfer.''
   The appeals court said the Postal Service properly refused to
adopt an alternative system of random transfers because that would
have reduced the incentive for voluntary moves to big cities.
   In the appeal acted on today, the senior inspectors said they
have been hit with significant hardship by the transfer rule.
   After living for years in the same location, they said the
system forced them to uproot their families and move to areas with
a higher cost of living.
   Regardless of the Postal Service's motives, the senior
inspectors said the senior-first rule is illegal because it has a
disproportionate impact on older workers.
   Bush administration lawyers urged the justices to reject the
appeal, saying, the system ``ensures that the burdens of employment
are distributed fairly while giving postal inspectors as much
control as possible over their careers.''
   The case is Arnold vs. Postmaster General, 89-8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
