<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-DeRoburt     10-02 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-DeRoburt,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>President of Nauru in South Pacific Loses Bid to Revive Libel Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the tiny South Pacific
republic of Nauru today lost a Supreme Court appeal aimed at
reviving his libel lawsuit against a Guam newspaper.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that President
Hammer DeRoburt was not libeled by the Pacific Daily News.
   The newspaper, owned by Gannett Inc., reported in 1978 that
DeRoburt secretly made an illegal $600,000 loan to a Marshall
Islands political faction that favored separating the islands from
Micronesia.
   DeRoburt said the article and a related one were false. He said
the loan was legal, was a matter of public record and was made
before DeRoburt was elected president.
   Nauru is an indepedent island nation of about eight square miles
with some 4,000 residents. It is among the wealthiest nations per
capita because of vast phosphate deposits.
   After years of legal maneuvering, a federal jury in Hawaii
decided in favor of the newspaper in 1985. The jury found that
DeRoburt failed to prove actual malice _ that the newspaper
knowingly printed falsehoods or acted with reckless disregard for
the truth.
   A key issue in the case was the identity of two confidential
sources relied on by the newspaper.
   DeRoburt at one point alleged that the sources did not exist.
His lawyers wanted the jury told it could presume there were no
sources.
   But during trial, the reporter who wrote the first article named
two sources, including one who by that time had died.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the jury verdict in
October 1988. The appeals court said DeRoburt's lawyers, in effect,
abandoned their claim that no sources existed.
   They ``chose to present (DeRoburt's) case in a manner
inconsistent with a theory of no sources,'' the appeals court said.
For the judge ``to then instruct the jury that it should
conclusively presume that there were no sources would have been
contrary to the evidence presented at trial by both parties and
contrary to the truth,'' the appeals court said.
   In the appeal acted on today, DeRoburt urged the justices to
overturn their 1964 ruling that established the ``actual malice''
defense in libel suits filed by public officials.
   In the alternative, DeRoburt's lawyers said the burden of
proving there was no actual malice should be shifted to the
newspaper when it has withheld, concealed or destroyed relevant
evidence.
   DeRoburt alleged that the reporter who wrote the first 1978
article destroyed his notes.
   The case is DeRoburt vs. Gannett, 89-9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
