<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Escheat     10-02 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Escheat,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Rejects Abandoned Property Case from Connecticut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to bar states
from using abandoned property laws to recover some unclaimed
insurance benefits.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by an insurance
company ordered to turn over to Connecticut $2.5 million in
unclaimed benefits.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last February that
the state's power to collect the money is not pre-empted by the
federal Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA), which
regulates pensions and other employee benefit programs.
   Aetna Life Insurance Co., which provides group health and
accident coverage for workers, said it should be allowed to keep
unclaimed benefits and use the money to lower its premiums or
increase benefits.
   The insurance company said tens of millions of dollars could be
at stake if all states sought to recover unclaimed benefits.
   Connecticut in 1981 amended its laws on abandoned property _ or
escheating _ to enable the state to acquire property left unclaimed
after three, rather than seven, years.
   The state said Aetna must turn over to it $2.5 million in
unclaimed benefits.
   A federal judge ruled in favor of Aetna but the 2nd Circuit
court reversed that decision.
   ``We think that the impact of Connecticut's escheat law on ERISA
benefit plans is too tenuous, remote and peripheral to require
pre-emption'' of the state law by the federal statute, the appeals
court said.
   The case is Aetna vs. Borges, 88-1883.
</TEXT>
