<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Dues     10-02 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Dues,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Workers Who Don't Want to Pay Equivalent of Union Dues Lose
Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear an
appeal by non-union Pennsylvania state employees who oppose paying
the equivalent of dues to a union that represents them in
collective bargaining.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that the
employees' rights were not violated when they were forced to
financially support the union's negotiating efforts.
   The employees are challenging the deduction from their paychecks
of what is known as agency fees. The fees average $263 a year per
worker and are paid in lieu of union dues.
   The American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees
(AFSME) is the collective-bargaining agent for Pennsylvania's state
employees, union and non-union members alike.
   The union signed an agrement with state officials July 28, 1988,
to deduct the agency fees from some 18,000 non-union employees
beginning the following month.
   Fifteen non-union employees sued in federal court to block the
deductions. They said the fees violate their constitutional rights
because some of the money would be used to support causes and
politicians they do not support _ including Gov. Robert Casey of
Pennsylvania.
   After the suit was filed, the union agreed to place the fees in
an escrow account _ barring their use by the union _ until an
arbitrator decides whether the union may use the money or refund it.
   The non-union members then sought a court order returning the
money to them and barring the union from collecting any further
deductions pending outcome of the case.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals denied the injunction last
February, ruling that the non-union employees failed to show they
will suffer irreparable harm if the fees continue to be placed in
escrow.
   The appeals court relied heavily on a 1986 Supreme Court
decision that set guidelines for the use of agency fees. In that
ruling, the justices allowed fee deductions from non-union workers
as long as the money is not used, even temporarily, to ``finance
ideological activities unrelated to collective bargaining.''
   The 3rd Circuit court rejected arguments by the non-union
Pennsylvania employees that temporarily depriving them of the fees
violates their free-speech rights even if the money is held in
escrow.
   The case is Hohe vs. Casey, 89-51.
</TEXT>
