<HEAD>Police Fire Tear Gas At Thousands of Anti-Bhutto Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas and used batons
today to disperse about 2,000 Pakistanis who tried to demonstrate
at a house where Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto is staying
during her official visit, witnesses said.
   The witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said police
fired at least 15 rounds of tear gas and used steel-tipped batons
when the demonstrators tried to force their way to the state-run
guest house.
   Ms. Bhutto was in the guest house when the demnonstration
occurred.
   Ms. Bhutto arrived in Dhaka Sunday on a three-day visit, the
first by a Pakistani head of government in 15 years.
   The demonstrators were among the 250,000 people who demand
repatriation to Pakistan. They opted for Pakistani citizenship in
1971 when Bangladesh became independent by breaking away from
Pakistan after a 9-month-long liberation war.
   The demonstrators wanted to submit a memorandum to Ms. Bhutto
pleading their case.
   The stranded Pakistani live in 66 camps across Bangladesh.
   Bangladesh and Pakistan, meanwhile, signed a cultural protocol
to promote exchanges on education, information and arts and culture.
   The agreement was signed after Ms. Bhutto held talks with
Bangladesh President Hussain Muhammad Ershad.
   Pakistani Foreign Affairs Advisor Iqbal Akhand told reporters
that the two leaders held ``free and frank discussions'' on all
issues. ``We have no problem between us,'' He said without
elaborating.
   Bangladesh Foreign Minister Anisul Islam said the two leaders
would meet again. ``It is a goodwill visit,'' Islam said without
elaborating.
   The two leaders also dicussed the issue of the stranded
Pakistanis.
   After the talks Ms. Bhutto flew to Jaipurhat, 130 miles north of
Dhaka to the lay the foundation stone of an orphanage.
   Earlier today, she visited the national mausoleum for the
independence war martyars at Savar, outskirts of Dhaka.
   The Pakistani prime minister paid homage to the martyrs who
fought against Pakistani during the liberation war.
