<DOCNO> AP891002-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan     10-02 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Demand Release of Dissident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 people demonstrated Monday
outside a jail to demand the release of a Taiwanese dissident who
was arrested as he sneaked back into the country after 10 years of
exile in the United States.
   Inside the jail, which was heavily guarded by barricades and
hundreds of riot police, High Court prosecutor Chen Yao-neng
questioned the dissident, publisher Hsu Hsin-liang, about sedition
charges filed against him in connection with riots 10 years ago.
   The demonstrators, mostly members of the oppositon Democratic
Progressive Party, waved banners and shouted ``Hsu Hsin-liang not
guilty!'' They demanded he be released on bail. Several protesters
set off firecrackers to celebrate Hsu's return.
   The four-hour protest ended without incident.
   Prosecutors have rejected a request by Hsu's lawyer, Chen
Shui-pien, that Hsu be freed on bond.
   Hsu, 48, was arrested Wednesday after coast guard officials
found him hiding in a fishing boat off the southern Taiwanese port
of Kaohsiung as he was attempting to sneak back into the country.
   He had tried three other times since 1979 to return to Taiwan
but was turned back when airliners observed a Taiwan government
demand he not be allowed to board Taiwan-bound flights. Government
officials feared Hsu's return would trigger political unrest.
   Military prosecutors in 1980 filed sedition charges against Hsu
for his alleged involvement in anti-government riots in Kaohsiung
in 1979.
   The riots broke out two months after Hsu left for the United
States, but authorities said he helped organized them.
   Military authorities also accused Hsu of advocating
anti-government movements that support an independent Taiwan.
   The Nationalist government, which fled to Taiwan after losing a
civil war to Communist forces in 1949 on the Chinese mainland,
still claims to be the ruler of all China and opposes an
independent state of Taiwan.
   Hsu has denied the charges against him.
</TEXT>
