<FIRST>r w AM-ConstructionSpending     10-02 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Construction Spending,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Spending Posts Its Biggest Advance This Year in August</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending posted its biggest
advance this year in August, the government said Monday, but the
gain was in government and non-residential building while the
single-family housing industry continued to sag.
   The Commerce Department said overall spending increased 1.8
percent last month, up $7.3 billion to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of $421.8 billion, the first gain since May's 1.4 percent
advance.
   Analysts expect building construction to remain at the current
level for the remainder of the year as the economy continues to
grow at a modest pace.
   ``All signals point to not too much change from recent trends,''
economist Mark Obrinsky of the Federal National Mortgage
Association said. ``I don't think we're going to see a boom or a
bust in either residential or non-residential construction.''
   Analysts have been looking for a slight pickup in construction
spending ever since interest rates began falling earlier in the
year. Fixed-rate mortgage rates declined from a peak of 11.22
percent in March to 10.22 at the end of August and to 10.16 last
week, according to a survey by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Co.
   The Commerce Department said the August advance was the biggest
since a 2.3 percent increase last December and followed declines of
0.6 percent in July and 0.8 percent in June. The July figure had
been revised downward from a miniscule 0.02 percent gain.
   Government building, a volatile sector representing about 20
percent of construction spending, was up 5.3 percent in August, led
by a 4.2 percent rebound in highway building which had fallen 4.5
percent in July.
   ``That's a number which from time to time shows a big one-month
increase and quite often will come back to the previous trend-level
in the following months and I suspect we'll see that this time,''
Obrinsky said.
   Residential construction, which accounts for nearly half of
construction spending, posted a tiny fractional increase of 0.05
percent to an annual rate of $198.9 billion. But single-family
construction fell 0.2 percent to an annual rate of $113.1 billion
while apartment building gained 0.4 percent to $23.5 billion.
   Obrinsky said he expects the pace of housing starts to improve
in the fourth quarter, but at a modest pace.
   Non-residential construction was up 2.9 percent to an annual
rate of $100.3 billion, led by advances of 4.5 percent in office
buildings and 1.8 percent in factories.
   Total construction was up 3.4 percent from the level of building
a year ago.
</TEXT>
