<HEAD>Kaifu Promises Political Reform, Review of Sales Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu pledged Monday to
press ahead with political reform and a review of a widely
unpopular new sales tax in his first policy speech since taking
office in August.
   Kaifu addressed Parliament after the Liberal Democratic Party's
victory in a weekend election indicated the scandal-ridden party's
fortunes are improving. ``The restoration of trust in politics is
this Cabinet's most important task,'' he said. ``I am thus
determined to continue to make a good-faith effort to move ahead on
political reform.''
   On Sunday, Kaifu's party won a by-election to fill a vacancy in
Parliament's upper house after the death of a Liberal Democratic
lawmaker.
   As the first national-level election under the Kaifu
administration, it was closely watched. The opposition campaigned
mainly on pledges to work for abolition of the 3 percent sales tax,
which took effect in April and contributed to the Liberal
Democrats' loss of its upper house majority for the first time in
34 years in July elections.
   Kaifu said his party is reviewing the sales tax, which it rammed
through Parliament late last year, but he ruled out abolishing the
levy.
   ``The consumption tax is absolutely indispensable in light of
the need to equalize the tax burden and to meet Japan's future
needs,'' he said.
its weekday schedule from 74
flights a day to 48, said Robert Priddy, Air Midwest's chief
executive officer.
   Air Midwest, which operates as Braniff Express at the Kansas
City airport, said it would eliminate service between Kansas City
and seven Midwestern cities: Joplin, Mo.; Grand Island, Neb.; Sioux
City, Iowa; Waterloo, Iowa; Moline, Ill.; Peoria, Ill.; and
Madison, Wis.
   Robert C. Dynan, vice president of Braniff Express operations,
said most of the passengers on the canceled routes connected with
Braniff flights, meaning there now wasn't enough traffic to keep
flying to those cities.
   Priddy said the reduced Air Midwest schedule, which still would
serve 19 cities, could be maintained without feeding Braniff
flights.
   He said the cuts would force some layoffs of Air Midwest's 150
employees at Kansas City, although he did not know how many.
   ``It's an awfully sad thing, but I really don't have that much
choice at this point,'' Priddy said.
   Braniff, which is trying to reorganize as a smaller carrier,
said it would offer a total of 46 flights nationwide Monday serving
11 cities, and 40 of those flights would start or end at Kansas
City.
   The schedule is for two round-trip flights each to 10 cities
from Kansas City: Chicago; Dallas-Fort Worth; Los Angeles; Newark,
N.J.; New York City-LaGuardia; Orlando, Fla.; Phoenix, Ariz.; San
Diego; San Francisco; and Washington-National.
   Another three round-trip flights will run between Orlando, where
Braniff is based, and other cities.
   The schedule will use 12 Boeing 727-200s, each of which can
carry 169 passengers. None of Braniff's five new Airbus A320 jets
will be used.
   A federal bankruptcy judge ruled last week that an Irish
financial service company could suspend its contract to supply
Braniff with additional A320s.
   On Sunday, Braniff operated only four departures from Kansas
City. Because traffic was so low in Terminal A, several lounges and
snack bars were closed.
