<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Witters 1stLd-Writethru a0557 10-02 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Witters, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0557,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blind Aspiring Minister Seeking Financial Aid Loses Appeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS first two grafs to show Scotus denied review; DID NOT
grant review. Picks up graf 3, The justices.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blind, aspiring minister who for nine years
has sought financial aid from Washington state so he can attend
Bible college lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court, without comment, let stand the state's refusal to
subsidize vocational training for Larry Witters. He argued that the
refusal violates his religious freedom.
   The justices in 1986 ruled unanimously that the state's
providing Witters with financial aid would not violate the
constitutionally required separation of church and state.
   The 1986 decision overturned a Washington Supreme Court ruling
that had said giving Witters money under a state
vocational-training program for the blind would promote religion
impermissibly.
   Witters' case then returned to the state Supreme Court, which
last April 20 ruled, by a 5-4 vote, that letting Witters receive
the state funding would violate a state constitution ban.
   A provision of Washington's constitution says, ``No public money
... shall be appropriated for or applied to any religious ...
instruction.''
   In the appeal acted on today, Witters argued that the state
constitution's provision violates his religious freedom protected
by the federal Constitution's First Amendment.
   His case crystalizes the inherent tension between two First
Amendment clauses _ one banning official ``establishment'' of
religion and one banning official interference with ``the free
exercise'' of religion.
   Witters, who is legally blind, was first denied aid in 1980. As
a result, he was forced to drop out of the Inland Empire School of
the Bible in Spokane and take a dish-washing job in a medical
laboratory.
   His appeal said Washington had excluded Witters ``from receiving
the benefits of public welfare legislation because of his faith.''
   The appeal likened the state's treatment of Witters to an
attempt by Missouri to ban religious clubs from meeting on state
college campuses and Tennessee's attempt to bar ministers from
holding elective office.
   The nation's highest court struck down both of those state
attempts as unconstitutional infringements of religious rights.
   In urging the justices to reject Witters' appeal, Washington
Attorney General Kenneth Eikenberry argued, ``The problem with what
(Witters) wants arises from the type of instruction which he wishes
the state to fund, not from his career goal or from the institution
he wishes to attend.''
   Eikenberry said Witters would be eligible for state funding if
he took non-religious courses, even at the Bible school.
   The case is Witters vs. Washington Department of Services for
the Blind, 89-94.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Afghan     10-02 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Afghan,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Calls On Afghan Rebels To Unite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hashemi Rafsanjani of Iran
called on fractious Afghan rebel groups Monday to unite to form an
Islamic government in Kabul and to reject U.S. support.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
also quoted Rafsanjani as calling for an end to superpower
intervention in Afghanistan, where U.S.-backed Moslem rebels have
been fighting 11 years to oust the Soviet-backed government.
   Opening an international seminar on the Afghan issue, the
president urged all Afghan groups to cooperate in their fight for
self-determination and ``to isolate ideologies alien to Afghan
culture and tradition.''
   The seven-group guerrilla alliance is based in Pakistan.
   The Sunni Moslem alliance has been at odds with another
guerrilla coalition of Shiite Moslems based in Iran, which is
overwhelmingly Shiite.
   IRNA quoted Rafsanjani as saying only Islam could guarantee
Afghanistan's territorial integrity and independence.
   ``We are for an independent, Islamic and non-aligned
Afghanistan,'' he declared.
   Iran has been taking a growing role in efforts to form an
interim government dominated by the guerrillas, known as
mujahedeen, following the Soviet military withdrawal from
Afghanistan in February.
   The Iranian effort has developed as Tehran's relations with
Moscow have improved, in large part because of the Soviet
withdrawal.
   The Soviets regularly consult the Iranians on developments in
Afghanistan, Iran's northeastern neighbor.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati told delegates to
the Tehran conference that recognizing Washington's role in
Afghanistan contradicted the interests of Afghanistan's Moslem
people, IRNA reported.
   ``The future of Afghanistan does not depend on a certain person
or group, but rather on the Afghan nation which has suffered a
great deal and should decide the country's fate,'' he added.
   That was an apparent reference to the split in guerrilla ranks.
</TEXT>
