<DOCNO> AP891002-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1354EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     10-02 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>31 Killed Despite Government Cease-fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-one people died in the
bloodiest 24-hour period since the government declared a unilateral
cease-fire last week, military officials reported Monday.
   Twenty-four people were murdered by Sinhalese radicals, six were
killed by soldiers they had ambushed, and a jailed Sinhalese
extremist committed suicide, the officials said.
   A soldier and a child were wounded in the ambush Sunday at
Girikola village, 25 miles south of Colombo, said the officials,
whose names cannot be used under briefing rules.
   The deaths brought the total to 59 since the government
proclaimed the cease-fire Wednesday. It originally was called for
three days, then extended until 6 a.m. Tuesday.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa instructed the military to halt
operations against members of the People's Liberation Front, a
Sinhalese radical group, but said they were allowed to defend
themselves.
   He declared the truce to give the radicals among the Sinhalese,
Sri Lanka's predominant ethnic group, an opportunity to end their
2-year-old uprising and join peace talks. At least 5,000 people
have been killed in the violence.
   The People's Liberation Front rejected negotiations and
continued its campaign of killings and arson, but the government
said 869 extremists had surrendered during the cease-fire.
   Military officials said the 24 people killed by Sinhalese
radicals included two soldiers whose vehicle was blown up. They
said the other victims were police informants, members of
policemen's families or supporters of the government.
   At least 14 post offices, 17 government buildings and three
buses were burned, the officials reported.
   Violence increased after Premadasa took office in January, after
elections the extremists claimed were fraudulent.
   They oppose the 1987 peace accord with ethnic Tamil separatists
and the presence of Indian soldiers assigned to supervise the peace
plan. India has said it will withdraw its troops by Dec. 31.
   About 11,000 people have been killed in the Tamil war, which
began in 1983.
   Tamils, predominantly Hindu, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people and claim discrimination by the Sinhalese, most
of whom are Buddhists.
   India became involved because it is the regional power and has a
Tamil population of 60 million. Most live in Tamil Nadu state, just
across the Palk Strait from Sri Lanka.
</TEXT>
