<FIRST>u a PM-EastStLouisTeachers     10-02 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East St Louis Teachers,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>East St. Louis Teachers Reject Binding Arbitration, Begin Picketing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers in this financially
strapped city went out on strike today after rejecting a salary
offer that would have left many ``taking home less pay than last
year,'' a union official said.
   Union members were setting up pickets at all 36 schools in the
district, said Terry Turley, president of the East St. Louis
Federation of Teachers Local 1220.
   Samuel Morgan, principal at East St. Louis Senior High School,
said classes were canceled for the district's 16,000 students. Most
of the staff members at his school were picketing, Morgan said, and
members of other unions, such as the custodians, were honoring the
picket lines.
   The East St. Louis Board of Education had proposed binding
arbitration to settle disputes over wage increases and insurance
payments. The district, which has a $12.5 million debt, is trying
to get the teachers to pay a larger share of health insurance costs.
   Turley said union members met Sunday and voted 347-227 to reject
binding arbitration, effectively voting to strike in the
fourth-largest school district in the state. The 1,200 teachers,
teachers' aides, clerks and attendance officers represented by the
union had been working without a contract since school started Aug.
28, Turley said.
   Turley declined to disclose the terms of the board's final
offer, but said rising insurance costs would have offset pay
increases for some teachers. Last year, the teachers were under a
wage freeze.
   Last week, State Superintendent of Education C. Robert Leininger
said the district stands to lose $60 million in state funds for
failing to implement an emergency debt-reduction plan.
   The plan called for firing 250 teachers, shifting the cost of
dependent health care coverage to employees and closing or
consolidating four schools to save $11 million by the end of this
year.
</TEXT>
