<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-BarDues     10-02 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Bar Dues,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court To Decide Bar Association Dues Issue in California Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether attorneys may withhold their state bar association dues if
the association uses the money to campaign for various causes and
issues.
   The justices said they will hear arguments by 21 California
lawyers who say their free-speech rights are being violated because
they are forced to pay dues to the bar group in order to continue
practicing law in the state.
   The attorneys said the money is being used to promote numerous
ideological causes, including a nuclear weapons freeze and handgun
control, that they do not support.
   The California Supreme Court ruled in February that the lawyers'
rights were not violated, except if money is used by the bar
association to help finance campaigns of candidates for public
office.
   ``We conclude that the state bar may use dues to finance any
activity, except election campaigning, which is germane to its
statutory mission to promote the improvement of the administration
of justice,'' the state court said.
   The ruling conflicts with decisions by other state courts that
limit the power of state bar associations to use members' dues for
ideological purposes.
   The California court said the bar association, with power to
license and discipline lawyers, is more like a state agency than a
labor union.
   The U.S. Supreme Court has limited the power of unions to spend
dues money for public-issue lobbying.
   The California court noted that every lawyer in the state must
be a member of the bar to practice law there.
   Also, the state court said, the bar association is run by a
governing board that includes six of 22 members appointed by the
governor with approval of the state Senate.
   ``The California Constitution, statutes and judicial decisions
... appear to envision the bar as a governmental agency,'' the
state court said.
   Therefore, the state court continued, the bar association may
use its revenues ``for any purposes within its authority.''
   Issues of public health, safety and welfare fall within that
category, the state court said.
   But the state court said the bar association went too far in
1982 when it distributed material supporting justices of the state
Supreme Court who were up for re-election.
   The material permissibly supported the independence of the
judiciary, the state court said. But ``its primary purpose, we
believe, was to assist in the election campaign on behalf of the
justices.'' That exceeded the association's authority, the state
court added.
   The case is Keller vs. State Bar of California, 88-1905.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0153 </DOCNO>
