<SECOND>AM-Denmark-Homosexuals, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0613,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>11 Homosexuals Couples Marry in Controversial Ceremony</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 8th graf, `Like the...' to tell how couple formed last
name. Pickup 9th, ``We decided...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAN OLSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 40 years of living together,
Axel and Eigil Axgil spent a happy first day as a ``married
couple'' Monday.
   Axel, 74, and Eigil, 67, were among the first 11 male couples to
exchange vows Sunday as Denmark became the first country to give
homosexual couples legal status and the right to join in a
``registered partnership.''
   Hundreds of homosexuals applauded, waved flags and threw rice on
them on the Town Hall steps, while Christian fundamentalists
demonstrated on the other side of the square. One demonstrator
waving a Bible called it ``Sodom's Day.''
   ``Homosexuality is a sin,'' he said.
   Parliament in May approved a gay rights bill by a lopsided
majority. Only the small People's Christian party opposed the
measure.
   The law, which took effect Sunday, gives homosexual couples
nearly equal rights as heterosexual couples but bars them from
adopting children. They have the same inheritance rights, tax
advantages and the right to share a last name.
   Under the new law, at least one partner must have Danish
citizenship and live in Denmark.
   Like the other 10 couples, Axel and Eigil solemnly answered
``yes'' to deputy mayor Tom Ahlberg when he asked if they consented
to tie each other in ``a registered partnership.'' They combined
their first names to form a common last name.
   ``We decided to get officially `married' because we have the
same feelings for each other as heterosexual couples,'' said Axel,
speaking on Danish television. He and Eigil later left town for
several days, friends said, apparently on a honeymoon.
   No lesbian couples have been registered. ``We don't like to be
in the front line,'' one woman said after Sunday's ceremony.
   ``The next step will be the acquisition of the right to adopt
stepchildren from one of the partners from an earlier heterosexual
marriage and the right to be blessed in a church,'' said Ivan
Larsen, who was among the couples and is a pastor of the Danish
Evangelist Lutheran Church.
   ``If I had the right to marry a homosexual couple in my church,
I would certainly like to do so, but for the time being we'll have
to wait,'' Larsen said.
   ``When it (the partnership) becomes official, it lasts longer,''
said Larsen's partner, school psychologist Ove Carlsen, who moved
into the church parsonage two years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1316EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-CatastrophicCare 2ndLd-Writethru a0571 10-02 0923</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Catastrophic Care, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0571,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showdown Expected on Catastrophic Care Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS grafs 2-3 pvs to update with Foley comments today; picks
up 4 graf pvs: At the...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fate of Medicare catastrophic health care
coverage for 33 million Americans hangs in the balance as Congress
considers repealing the program to cool the ``blast furnace heat''
of angry senior citizens.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley today chided the Bush
administration for its silence on the program, which could be voted
on this week, and added: ``I'm told the president opposes the
repeal but I haven't seen any evidence of it.''
   Foley, D-Wash., supports a continuation of the program and said
President Bush's refusal to take a more vocal stand on the issue
puts Congress in ``an awkward position.'' Votes also may occur this
week in the Senate.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said today, ``Our
position basically is that we want to retain the benefits and
mitigate the premium costs.'' But the administration has not yet
endorsed or rejected any of the major alternatives the House is
expected to consider, he added.
   The program's defenders have launched a last-ditch effort to
save it by pushing a revision that would scrap major features of
the program, cancel the unpopular surtax that helps finance it, and
retain new prescription drug benefits scheduled to begin in January.
   ``We're on the heart-lung machine trying to keep the program
going,'' said John Rother, legislative director of the American
Association for Retired Persons. ``But it's obvious that some major
changes are going to have to be made.''
   The Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act is aimed at providing
protection for the elderly and disabled against financial ruin in
the event of a prolonged hospital stay or other high medical costs.
   The plan limits the amount that beneficiaries must pay for
hospital care, physician services, medical supplies and
prescription drugs and expands other health care benefits as well.
   For example, the program pays for unlimited approved
hospitalization after a once-a-year deductible of $560 in 1989.
Previously, Medicare charged a deductible for each hospital stay
during a year and provided full payment of hospital bills for 59
days a year.
   The program was enacted with support from major senior citizen
groups such as AARP but drew swift and strong criticism from many
older Americans who were angry at the costs for mandatory coverage
that some said they neither wanted nor needed.
   Many elderly people said they already had duplicate coverage
from private insurers and that the new program doesn't address
their chief concern with the high cost of long-term care in nursing
homes. Higher-income retirees also objected to paying a high
proportion of the program's costs.
   The focal point of the opposition is a surtax levied on the 40
percent of retirees whose incomes are high enough that they pay
more than $150 in income tax. The surtax _ 15 percent of their
income tax liabilities _ this year is capped at $800 per Medicare
enrollee but rises in future years.
   ``A lot of people don't have that extra money in their
budgets,'' said Alicia Hasek, a Florida retiree who joined a
grassroots group called Seniors Opposed to the Surtax. ``The best
thing is to go back to point one and start over again.''
   The opposition has members of Congress on the run _ literally.
Democratic Rep. Dan Rostenkowski of Illinois, the 6-foot-4 chairman
of the powerful House Ways and Means Committee, was booed and
chased down a Chicago street by a group of senior citizens last
month after he refused to discuss the catastrophic package with
them.
   ``These people don't understand what the government is trying to
do for them,'' Rostenkowski said as he hurried to outpace his
critics.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater earlier this month said
the protests had reached ``tidal wave'' proportions but that the
Bush administration still hopes to see the program preserved.
   Many proponents of the package maintain that most seniors
support the catastrophic package and that it is a vocal and
affluent minority making much of the noise.
   Eric Shulman, legislative director of the National Council of
Senior Citizens, said that while the opposition has hit Washington
with ``blast furnace heat,'' legislators and seniors will come to
regret it if they repeal important health care benefits.
   ``Over time, seniors would look back and say, `We really could
have used that benefit,'' he predicted.
   House action on the catastrophic package is expected this week
as the chamber works through an omnibus budget bill laden with a
host of unrelated items. Legislators will have the chance to vote
on proposals both to repeal and scale back the program.
   As an alternative to repeal, Democratic House leaders are
pushing a plan that would eliminate the surtax and strip out new
hospital, doctor and nursing home benefits. The remaining benefits
would be financed by keeping the existing flat fee of $4 a month
paid by all but the poorest Medicare beneficiaries.
   Left intact would be new prescription drug benefits and modest
expansions of coverage for home health care, hospice benefits and
in-home respite care. Also kept would be a requirement that
Medicaid pay the Medicare deductibles, premiums and copayments for
the poorest seniors.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., is pushing a plan that would scrap
the surtax, retain the new hospitalization benefits, kill the drug
benefit and remove the cap on doctor payments. Other senators are
likely to push competing plans to repeal or revise the catastrophic
program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
