<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--DogExtortion     10-02 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Dog Extortion,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Hopeful Two Months After Dog's Disappearance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOPKINTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town council president remained
hopeful Monday that her golden retriever will be returned, two
months after it disappeared in a possible political extortion
attempt.
   The 7-year-old dog, Kelly, failed to return home July 31 from a
nightly romp on Sandra Johanson's 64-acre estate. Twelve hours
later, Mrs. Johanson received an anonymous telephone call from a
man who said: ``Get off the council and you'll get your dog.''
   Mrs. Johanson said she is confident the dog is alive. And she
vowed to remain in office.
   George Weeden, chief of the town's 10-member police force, said
Monday he has no new leads. Several people were interviewed, and at
least one was given a lie-detector test, but no arrests had been
made.
   Some residents of this rural town of 7,000 people, about 45
miles south of Providence, have speculated the dog's disappearance
could be related to the November firings of the town dump custodian
and the highway supervisor. The highway official was reinstated,
then resigned.
