<FIRST>r a AM-People     10-02 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0923</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 51-year absence from the stage in
Fort Worth only made Helen Hayes more charming to an enthralled
audience.
   The Academy Award-winning actress was joined briefly on stage by
her son, actor James MacArthur, for a Sunday benefit performance
attended by about 400 people at the Fort Worth theater.
   Ms. Hayes gave a lecture peppered with anecdotes from her eight
decades on the stage and performed a humorous James Thurber sketch
with her son.
   At the end of the 90-minute program, the audience sang ``Happy
Birthday'' with Van Cliburn accompanying on the piano. Ms. Hayes
will be 89 on Oct. 10.
   Ms. Hayes last appeared in Fort Worth in 1938, in the touring
version of ``Victoria Regina,'' playing Queen Victoria from youth
to old age.
   She said she has been inspired for more than 50 years by a line
from that play, in which a working-class Londoner shouts to the
aged Victoria: ``Go it, old girl! You done it good!''
   ``I think I want that on my tombstone,'' Ms. Hayes said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A planned barbecue was rained out, so rock
'n' roller Jerry Lee Lewis celebrated his 54th birthday with 400
relatives and friends at a golf club lodge on the outskirts of
Memphis.
   Friends say Lewis, who has been married six times and has
survived struggles with alcohol and drugs, has calmed down in
recent years, spending as much time as he can with his wife and
3-year-old son at their home in rural Mississippi near Memphis.
   Lewis played to those observations while performing an ad-libbed
rendition of ``Goodnight Irene.''
   ``Jerry Lee, you've stopped your ramblin' and you've stopped
your gamblin,'' he sang at Friday's party. ``You've got a nice home
down in Mississippi and you've got a beautiful, loving wife.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WILLCOX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willcox's favorite son, cowboy singer and
movie star Rex Allen, is going to have a place to hang his hat _
and his wardrobes, movie posters, silver saddle, record jackets,
comic books and other mementos.
   The Rex Allen Arizona Cowboy Museum will open during the 38th
annual Rex Allen Days, Saturday and Sunday.
   A fundraiser in Phoenix earlier this year raised some $100,000
and was attended by the likes of Allen, Gene Autry, Roy Rogers and
Glen Campbell.
   The museum is in a building that was a pre-Prohibition saloon.
Exhibits will touch on local history in addition to Allen's life _
from his youth spent in this southeastern Arizona town, through his
singing and movie days, and his numerous narrations for Disney
``World of Color'' specials.
   ``There's so much great history there,'' Allen, 68, said from
his home in Sonoita, southeast of Tucson. ``I think that's a lot
more important than doing something for some damn movie cowboy.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Alexandra, cousin of Queen Elizabeth II,
will fly out with a cargo of British government medical aid to
British Caribbean islands hit by Hurricane Hugo last month, her
office said Monday.
   The 52-year-old princess will leave Thursday and spend two days
in Montserrat and the British Virgin Islands.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Celebrities including Stevie Wonder, Paula
Abdul, Ally Sheedy, Cesar Romero, Valerie Harper, and Victoria
Principal turned out for a fund-raiser thrown by radio personality
Casey Kasem and his actress wife, Jean.
   The Kasems transformed their luxurious home into a huge lawn
circus Sunday to raise money for the homeless.
   Jugglers, mimes, sword swallowers, clowns, and fire eaters
performed for the more than 2,000 guests, said Karen Kukurin, a
spokeswoman for the couple.
   The fund-raiser also featured an auction of $3.5 million worth
of sculpture and oil paintings.
   It was not immediately known how much the auction had raised for
an Oct. 7 march on Washington, D.C., to draw attention to the
problem on homelessness, said Kukurin.
   Kasem's syndicated radio show is heard 450 stations each week.
His wife's acting credits include the television series ``Cheers''
and ``The Tortellis.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LANTANA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Cosby, who plays a wise father on his
hit series and wrote the best-seller ``Fatherhood'' about raising
his five children, says he and his wife refused to coddle a
daughter addicted to drugs and alcohol.
   ```Tough love' is the only way of dealing with this. We love her
and want her to get better, but we have to take a very firm, very
tough stand that forces her to realize that no one can fix things
for her,'' the star told the National Enquirer. ``She has to beat
this on her own.''
   Erinn Cosby, 23, who checked out of a drug rehabilitation center
Sept. 24, said she began using cocaine at age 19, but that her
parents had no idea she had a drug habit until she wrote them a
letter six months ago. She said she had kicked a $200-a-day cocaine
habit by then but was still hooked on marijuana and alcohol.
   ``People see Bill Cosby as a super dad. But I'm proof that drug
and alcohol tragedies can happen even in the most loving
families,'' said Erinn.
   The Enquirer piece was ``the only interview that he's been
willing to give on the matter,'' Cosby spokesman David Brokaw said
Monday. ``He has a relationship with them. He has found them to
treat him fairly.''
