<HEAD>Mother Teresa Develops Chest Pains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Mother Teresa developed
chest pains, but doctors attending her said Monday her condition
had stabilized.
   The 79-year-old Roman Catholic nun was admitted Sept. 5 to the
Woodlands Nursing Home hospital with a high fever and an irregular
heartbeat.
   Doctors said she developed chest pains Sunday, but ``She has
been comfortable since then,'' they said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   ``There is nothing to worry about ... she is now all right,''
the doctors said.
   Mother Teresa's condition twice become critical after she
suffered a heart attack while in the hospital's intensive care unit
Sept. 8.
   Despite her poor health in recent years, the Yugoslav-born nun
travels widely to offer care and comfort to the destitute. Her work
earned her a Nobel Peace Prize in 1979.
   Mother Teresa founded the Missionaries of Charity in 1950 to
care for the poor of this eastern Indian city's slums. The order,
which was formally recognized by the Vatican in 1965, expanded and
now has 3,000 nuns working for it in 87 countries.
