<FIRST>r a AM-CarnegieHall     10-02 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carnegie Hall,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archivist Looking for Carnegie Hall Memorabilia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A search for memorabilia to display for Carnegie
Hall's hundredth birthday turned up a Bennie Goodman clarinet and
the ribbon cut on opening night in 1891, the hall's archivist said
Monday.
   Archivist Gino Francesconi is looking for more souvenirs for
special exhibitions in 1990 and 1991.
   ``People have responded from all over the country. It's just
been fantastic,'' he said. ``But we're fighting the clock now.
We've given ourselves until March to look for material.''
   So far the search has turned up the silver trowel used by Andrew
Carnegie's wife, Louise, to lay the concert hall's cornerstone in
1890 and a ribbon that was cut on opening night in 1891.
   Bennie Goodman's daughter, Rachel Edelson, donated one of her
father's clarinets, and lots of photographs and recordings have
surfaced.
   ``We're desperately searching now for posters prior to 1960,''
Francesconi said. ``Most of those are just hanging on people's
walls. I can't believe that there aren't posters of Mark Twain,
Woodrow Wilson, Toscanini out there.''
   At the top of Francesconi's wish list: ``I would give anything
for a ticket from opening night, 1891. I know it's out there. ... I
was told by a collector that he had seen it five or six years ago.''
   Composers are being asked to write down a few measures of their
music that was performed at the hall, then sign it.
</TEXT>
