<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1836EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Runcie-Vatican     10-02 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Runcie-Vatican,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Runcie Ends Visit on High Note but With Little Visible Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglican leader Robert Runcie and Pope John
Paul II signed a document Monday committing their churches to
eventually heal their 450-year-old split but recognizing they still
had a long way to go.
   Runcie's first official visit to the Vatican yielded few other
visible signs of progress in relations between the world's two
largest groups of Christians.
   However, Runcie said he had built trust with Vatican officials
during four days of talks and that their commitment to seeking
unity was no mere ``academic exercise.''
   ``The way in which the conversations we have had together bear
fruit will come about gradually,'' he told a news conference.
   Among major points separating the churches is the doctrine of
papal infallibility, which applies to Roman Catholic beliefs such
as the Immaculate Conception of the Virgin Mary and her assumption
to heaven after death.
   Runcie is the fourth archbishop of Canterbury to visit the
Vatican since the late Geoffrey Fisher did so in 1960, ending four
centuries of estrangement that began when King Henry VIII formed
his own church after the pope refused to grant him an annulment of
his marriage.
   Talks have been under way since 1966 on a theological framework
for unifying the world's 850 million Roman Catholics and 70 million
Anglicans.
   The document signed Monday said: ``We here solemnly recommit
ourselves and those we represent to the restoration of visible
unity and full ecclesial communion.''
   But it noted the ordination of women in some of the Anglican
Communion's 27 self-governing provinces, such as the U.S. Episcopal
Church, ``prevents reconciliation between us even where there is
otherwise progress toward agreement.''
   Nonetheless, Cardinal Johannes Willebrands, president of the
Vatican's Council for Promoting Christian Unity, said ``obstacles
are there to be considered and overcome.''
   Runcie, the head of the state Church of England, repeatedly
emphasized one of the advances in Anglican-Catholic talks _ an
Anglican proposal to grant the pope a ``universal primacy'' over
Anglicans.
   Other advances in recent years have included a draft agreement
on how people's souls are saved.
   But many practical barriers to unity remain, including
differences on the Catholic ban on artificial birth control; some
Anglican churches' acceptance of abortion and divorce; the role of
lay people in the church; and the Anglican practice of allowing
married priests.
   Still, Anglican-Catholic talks are considered among the most
promising inter-faith discussions in which the Vatican is involved,
and Anglican officials say they expect some kind of unity in the
21st century.
   While both sides described the Anglican-Catholic meetings as
extremely friendly, Runcie's speeches expressed more eagerness
about unification than the pope's.
   Willebrands indicated the hesitancy of some Vatican officials
when he discussed a delay in the church's response to a 7-year-old
Anglican-Catholic report on possible theological agreements.
   ``We have often to consider in the church at large ... problems
of internal struggles or differences of opinion, etcetera, and it
is rather new to consider officially ecumenical documents,'' he
said.
   Runcie left the Vatican meetings with the promise Catholic
officials would respond soon to the 1982 report by the theological
commission.
   That report included agreements on the Eucharist and priesthood
and said Anglicans could recognize the pope as a universal primate,
but with somewhat reduced powers.
   Runcie's appeals for a leadership role for the pope drew fire
from the Rev. Ian Paisley, a Northern Ireland Protestant leader and
anti-pope activist, who charged at an impromptu news conference
that Runcie was trying to ``dethrone the queen and enthrone the
pope'' in England.
   But Runcie said he envisioned a spiritual rather than political
role for the pope, aimed at helping churches to promote religious
practice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1511EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru   10-02 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0626,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Opposition Figure Arrested For Advocating Government Boycott</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with Calderon, others reported
released; picks up 13th pvs: The Civic ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested an opposition leader and
eight supporters who were touring remote provinces urging people to
join a boycott of the military-controlled government, a fellow
opposition politician said.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, a former candidate for vice president,
was arrested with the others on Sunday in Veraguas province, 180
miles west of Panama City, according to Guillermo Cochez, a fellow
Christian Democraty Party leader.
   The Panamanian Defense Forces announced in a statement that the
opposition figures were freed today. Their released could not be
confirmed.
   The statement came shortly after the Christian Democratic party
said that Arias Calderon would go on a hunger strike.
   The opposition has engaged in a campaign of urging people to
delay paying taxis and utility bills as a way of increasing
economic pressure on the government led by military strongman Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The opposition also advocates a boycott of the lottery and
gambling casinos, which the government controls along with most of
the country's utilities.
   The Civic Democratic Opposition Alliance, which includes the
Christian Democrats, identified the other eight as party activists
Ivan Romero, his wife Mabel, Jose A. Sossa and his wife Gina,
Carlos Mantovani, Luis Eduardo Camacho, Temistocles de Obaldia and
Ramon Lima.
   Arias Calderon was one of two opposition vice presidential
candidates in May 7 national elections on a ticket led by Guillermo
Endara, who was in the 13th day of a hunger strike today as part of
the anti-Noriega campaign.
   The government annulled the May 7 election when returns showed
the opposition winning by a landslide.
   In a statement Sunday, Endara called Arias Calderon's arrest
``another symptom of despair by the dictatorship of Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega to repress the last vestiges of freedom and
democracy that remain in Panama.''
   The government, which depends heavily on revenues from the
lottery and casinos, has been short of funds since the United
States imposed trade and other economic sanctions on Panama soon
after federal courts in Florida indicted Noriega on
drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges in 1988.
   Endara, Arias Calderon, and his other running mate Guillermo
Ford want Noriega to respect the results of the May elections.
   The United States refuses to recognize the Noriega-dominated
government and considers Endara and his running mates Panama's
legitimate leaders.
   Noriega named his longtime friend, Francisco Rodriguez, as
provisional president on Sept. 1, the day Endara was to have been
sworn in.
</TEXT>
