<FIRST>r a AM-JailedLawmaker     10-02 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jailed Lawmaker,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Resigns After Four Months In Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA ZAGAROLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state legislator who spent the last four
months in jail for drunken driving resigned Monday amid pressure
from his colleagues, including threats by House Republicans to try
to expel him.
   State Rep. Dennis Dutko, an eight-term lawmaker from Warren, is
an acknowledged alcoholic with a history of drunken driving
incidents dating to 1973. During his time in jail, he has donated
his $42,670 salary to drug and alcohol treatment programs.
   Lawmakers had become increasingly concerned about the effect of
Dutko's jailing on the Legislature's integrity. But they were
reluctant to expel someone who was convicted of a misdemeanor
rather than a felony because it would be setting a precedent.
   The resignation came after last week's hint by House Minority
Leader Paul Hillegonds that he would call for an expulsion vote or
at least censure if the situation didn't change.
   Dutko twice said he'd resign, but backed down both times. He was
awaiting results of a floundering recall effort and his aides said
he still gets letters from constituents who don't think he should
step down.
   ``I am sure that many people will criticize me for not stepping
down sooner, but, in all honesty, I could not walk away from the
job and the people I love without a fight,'' Dutko said in his
resignation letter.
   He was jailed May 24, serving six-month and one-year sentences
concurrently. His scheduled release, counting time off for good
behavior, is Jan. 3.
</TEXT>
