<FIRST>r w AM-Officers'Club-Cost     10-02 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Officers' Club-Cost,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Spent $12.8 Million Renovating Officers' Club</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Renovation of an officers' club at the largest
U.S. Air Force base in Europe cost nearly three times the original
pricetag of $4.5 million, according to a Defense Department report
released Monday.
   The House Armed Services Committee had requested the review,
citing reports of construction and funding abuses.
   Work on the club at Ramstein Air Base in West Germany totaled
$12.8 million due to the use of incomplete and misleading data,
design changes that had to be made after construction began and
structural problems with the building, the report said.
   In fact, the facility was so structurally unsound contractors
were forced to raze all of the building except for the kitchen and
several small walls, said the review conducted by the Defense
Department's Inspector General.
   ``We had an officers' club that began as a Volkswagon and ended
as a Mack Truck rolling over anyone who got in its way,'' said Rep.
Marvin Leath, D-Texas, a member of the Armed Services subcommittee
on readiness.
   The report found that the original cost proposals for
construction of the club were based on inaccurate information.
After the work began, 130 design changes were made at a cost of
about $1.6 million.
   In addition, the review found that management ``had not operated
the club system efficiently, effectively or profitably from fiscal
1984 to fiscal 1987.''
   Leath, who released the report, said enlisted officers at the
base saw ``their financially sound clubs go into the hole several
million dollars. These operations lost $10,000 a day as management
was diverted to throw lavish parties for thousands of people.''
   ``This report reads like a base operations horror story,'' said
Rep. David O'B. Martin, R-N.Y., another member of the subcommittee.
   The Air Force, in comments included in the report, said the
service has begun follow-up audits and the Office of Special
Investigation is looking into whether civil or criminal charges are
warranted.
</TEXT>
