<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     10-02 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Discuss New Lebanon Charter, Disarming Militias</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese legislators meeting here
Monday put aside the problem of Syria's military presence in
Lebanon to discuss ways to disarm unruly militiamen and draft a
national charter to end the country's civil war.
   New tensions surfaced, however, over a surprise visit to Iran by
two key Moslem militia chieftains, Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt and
his Shiite Moslem civil war ally, Nabih Berri.
   Most of the 63 parliamentarians meeting here _ 33 Christians and
30 Moslems _ interpreted the trip as an Iranian attempt to
undermine the conference, under way since Saturday, conference
sources said.
   Berri heads the Shiite Moslem Amal militia and Jumblatt commands
the Progressive Socialist Party. Together, the two factions
comprise about 12,000 fighters.
   Tehran radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Berri as saying: ``We
are vehemently opposed to the plan submitted by the tripartite Arab
committee to solve the crisis in Lebanon.''
   The committee, composed of Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria,
has proposed a peace plan that includes a series of political
reforms designed to end the Christian domination of government,
Parliament, the army and the judiciary in Lebanon.
   The conference sources said the parliamentarians on Monday were
going over the proposed national reconciliation charter ``point by
point.''
   The charter would serve as an alternative to an unwritten
national covenant reached among the various sects in 1943, when
Lebanon gained independence from France.
   ``This plan does not conform with the wishes and aspirations of
the Moslems. This plan ... will result in the division of
Lebanon,'' Berri said.
   Berri and Jumblatt are Syria's main allies. Their support and
that of their rival Lebanese Forces coalition of Christian militias
is essential for implementing any agreement that may be reached in
Taif.
   Despite political problems, a cease-fire called by the Arab
mediators Sept. 22 to end six months of fierce artillery battles
between the Syrians and Christians was holding.
   The Christians' demand that a timetable for the withdrawal of
the Syrian army from Lebanon be workd out before political reforms
hampered progress during Saturday and Sunday.
   But Saudi Arabia's foreign minister, Prince Saud al-Faisal,
steered the deputies away from arguments, persuading them to
discuss instead the proposed political reforms.
   Faisal is sitting in on the Parliament debates along with his
Moroccan and Algerian counterparts, Abdel-Latif al-Filali and
Bouallam Belsayeh.
   The deputies also discussed how to disarm militia factions whose
military strength has eroded government authority.
   The sources said several suggestions were being examined for
disbanding the militias, including attaching some of them to
various military corps.
   They said most deputies appeared to favor a timetable, phasing
Syrian withdrawal from Moslem sectors of Beirut to the Bekaa Valley
in east Lebanon over two years while the country's constitutional
structure, virtually dismantled by the war, is rebuilt.
   But most of the Christian deputies, backed by some Moslems
allied with Iraq, Syria's rival in the Arab world, demanded an
immediate Syrian withdrawal.
   The Syrian army has 40,000 troops in Lebanon, controlling 70
percent of the country.
   The troops entered Lebanon in 1976, a year after the civil war
broke out, under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun, who is backed by Iraq, says
the Syrians abrogated their peacekeeping mandate by openly siding
with the Moslems.
</TEXT>
