<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru a0663 10-02 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Asks Legislature for Ban on Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads thruout to add details, background on strikes, parliamentary
debate. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev urged the
legislature on Monday to impose a 15-month ban on strikes that he
says are wrecking the Soviet economy and threatening development.
   Gorbachev spoke at the end of a stormy two-hour legislative
debate on a proposal of emergency economic measures put forward by
First Deputy Premier Lev Voronin, the Tass news agency said.
   Gorbachev urged legislators to discuss the strike ban overnight
and be ready to vote on it Tuesday.
   He referred to the possible ban on strikes as a ``necessary
measure ... which are called for to protect democratization from
anarchy and irresponsible management.''
   Plans for future economic development are ``under threat''
because of the strikes, he said.
   Emergency measures to bolster the rapidly faltering economy
overshadowed Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov's lengthy presentation of a
package of legislation covering the government's long-term
proposals on property, ownership and use of land, and taxes.
   Voronin told the legislature the Soviet economy had lost $6.15
billion in July and August alone due to strikes and that supplies
of fuel are low enough that the country might be unable to supply
enough heat to see Soviet citizens through the winter.
   The most damaging of a series of strikes to hit the Soviet Union
this year was a walkout in July by thousands of coal miners in the
far north, Siberia, and the Don Basin of the eastern Ukraine.
   That strike alone cost the country millions of rubles, and the
government agreed to a package of economic and social improvements
that officials say will cost about $3 billion.
   Strikes also have become a way of expressing ethnic discontent.
Such actions have idled the Nagorno-Karabakh region, the center of
a dispute between the neighboring Caucasus republics of Armenia and
Azerbaijan.
   In Moldavia and Estonia, Russian and other workers walked off
jobs at factories and offices during the summer to protest laws
that they said favored the majority Moldavians and Estonians.
   After legislators expressed contradictory viewpoints during a
debate, Gorbachev proposed they return Tuesday to vote on the
strike ban, and an overwhelming majority agreed, Tass said.
   The package of government proposals also calls for imposing a
``special form of administration'' on railroads in Armenia and
Azerbaijan, with the ministries of railroads, defense and interior
responsible for protecting the railroads and their workers.
   Armenian activists say Azerbaijani railroad workers recently
have blocked the trains that Armenia depends upon for 80 percent of
the goods brought in from other parts of the Soviet Union.
   Food stores have been emptied of many basic goods and there is
no fuel even for vehicles such as ambulances.
   Gorbachev said when the Supreme Soviet opened its fall session
Sept. 25 that decisive steps would have to be taken if rails to
Armenia were not cleared.
   Ryzhkov and radical deputies both named the law on property as
the most important of five key economic reforms presented to the
legislature, but they disagreed on what it should say.
   Ryzhkov said the central government must learn to refrain from
interfering in local economic affairs _ including its tendency to
claim all forms of property for itself.
   ``As long as about 90 percent of the basic means of production
belong in the framework of one owner _ the government _ all talk
about developing a market will remain empty words, and progress is
impossible,'' he said.
   But progressive Deputy Anatoly Sobchak of Leningrad said the
government's proposal still started from the point of view that the
state had priority of ownership, and individuals were last.
   He said it should be just the opposite.
   Ryzhkov said the government saw no reason to allow private
ownership of land but supported expanded rights for farmers who
lease land on long-term contracts from collective and state farms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
