<HEAD>Newspaper Says East German Leader Will Step Down After Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German leader Erich Honecker will
likely step down after upcoming celebrations marking the 40th
anniversary of his Communist nation, a newspaper reported Monday.
   The Bonn-based Die Welt said Honecker's doctors have determined
he is suffering from a ``total deterioration of his internal
organs.''
   The conservative newspaper said ``there are indications'' the
77-year-old Honecker will be replaced soon after the celebrations
this weekend.
   It did not name its sources.
   Die Welt said that in addition to suffering from gallbladder
ailments, Honecker is plagued by pancreatic disorders.
   West German news reports in August said Honecker was suffering
from cancer, but those reports were denied by East German officials.
   East German media have said only that Honecker is recovering
well from a gallbladder operation.
   Die Welt's report was to appear in its Tuesday edition. A
summary of its report was telexed to other news media in advance.
   The report came as East Germany copes with the exodus of
thousands of its citizens to the West. Hungary opened its Western
border Sept. 11, defying its Communist ally, and East Berlin has
agreed to free thousands who had holed themselves up in West German
embassies in Czechoslovakia and Poland.
