<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos-Hamilton     10-02 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos-Hamilton,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor George Hamilton Named in Marcos Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines-Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor George Hamilton, who once got a loan from
a company with reported ties to Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos, is one
of 61 unindicted co-conspirators named in the Marcos case,
according to court papers.
   Hamilton, Manhattan real estate developers Joseph and Ralph
Bernstein, and the Marcos' children, Irene, Imee and Ferdinand Jr.,
are among the unindicted co-conspirators named in documents filed
in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
   An unindicted co-conspirator may have done something to advance
an alleged criminal conspiracy, without necessarily knowing he or
she was doing it.
   An indictment last October charged that Mrs. Marcos and her late
husband, ousted Philippines President Ferdinand E. Marcos, stole
$168 million from the Philippine treasury. The trial is set to
begin in March.
   One of Mrs. Marcos' co-defendants, California Overseas Bank,
listed the unindicted co-conspirators in pretrial motion papers
asking for more information about evidence the government plans to
present.
   Hamilton bought a Beverly Hills estate once owned by Charlie
Chaplin for $1.2 million in 1981. The deal was financed by
Hamilton's own money, Wells Fargo Bank and the seller, said his
attorney, Michael Sherman.
   In late 1983, Hamilton used the increased value of the property
to get a five-year loan from Calno Holdings N.V. in the Netherlands
Antilles, which reportedly had ties with the Marcos family.
   Jeffrey Lane, a spokesman for Hamilton in Los Angeles, said the
actor could not comment until asking his attorneys to clarify the
ramifications, if any, of being an unindicted co-conspirator.
   The actor said through a spokesman in March 1986 that while he
had met Imelda Marcos, she had no financial interest in his home.
   Hamilton, who often has served as an escort for Elizabeth Taylor
and other celebrities, is known for his perpetual tan and his
portrayal of a vampire in the movie, ``Love at First Bite.'' He and
Mrs. Marcos have denied rumors linking them romantically; Mrs.
Marcos said they were just good friends.
   Two other unindicted co-conspirators, the Bernstein brothers,
told a congressional hearing that they managed the Marcoses' New
York real estate investments.
   The Bernsteins and Richard Hibey, a Washington attorney who
represents the Marcos family, did not immediately return calls to
their office for comment.
</TEXT>
