<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Crash     10-02 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Crash,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Killed as Train Crashes Into Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train carrying 125 passengers slammed
into a truck Monday after the truck driver apparently was blinded
by the sun and failed to see warning lights of a railway crossing.
Police said four people were killed.
   The crash threw four cars off the tracks and injured 26 people,
said police.
   The train from Hamburg, West Germany, was bound for Oslo,
Norway, when the accident occurred near Varobacka, 25 miles south
of Goteborg.
   Police spokesman Ove Bergman said most of the injured were from
Sweden and one was in critical condition. Six were reported
seriously hurt.
   ``I saw how he (the truck driver) pulled down his cap and
squinted against the sun before he accelerated to cross the tracks.
The warning lights were working,'' said a witness, Ake Strandberg,
who was quoted by the national news agency TT.
   The truck, loaded with asphalt, was ripped apart and chunks of
metal were thrown hundreds of yards.
   The truck driver and three people on the train died.
   The collision ripped a large hole in the side of the first
sleeping car where the passengers were killed.
   The train's engineer was quoted as saying he tried to catch the
driver's attention, then threw himself onto the floor an instant
before ramming the vehicle. He escaped with minor injuries.
   It was the worst train accident in Sweden since a head-on
collision in November 1987 killed nine people and injured 130.
   The national railway company, Statens Jarnvagar, had intended to
erect barriers later this month at the crossing.
</TEXT>
