<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2015EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RaleighTimes     10-02 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Raleigh Times,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raleigh Times to Cease Publication Nov. 30</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Raleigh Times, the capital city's
afternoon newspaper for 110 years, will publish its final edition
Nov. 30, the newspaper's publisher said Monday.
   Frank Daniels Jr., president of The News and Observer Publishing
Co., said an internal task force had recommended closing The
Raleigh Times as part of a plan to expand and improve The News and
Observer, Raleigh's morning newspaper.
   ``The recommendation to cease publication of The Raleigh Times
was one that was accepted reluctantly, but it was not unexpected,''
Daniels said. ``For several years, we have watched as afternoon
dailies in metropolitan areas closed. We cannot make the
improvements The News and Observer needs and still publish a
quality afternoon newspaper.''
   In recent years, afternoon newspapers in Winston-Salem,
Greensboro and Charlotte also have ceased publication.
   Daniels said no employee layoffs are expected. The news staffs
of The Times and The News and Observer were combined in 1987.
   The News and Observer will have five sections effective Dec. 1
to accommodate syndicated columns and features carried by The
Times, as well as expanded news coverage, Daniels said.
   The Times grew from the Raleigh Evening Visitor, founded in
1879. After merging with two competitors, the paper was renamed The
Raleigh Times in 1901. The Park family of Raleigh bought the Times
in 1911, with John A. Park serving as editor and publisher for 44
years.
   The Times was sold to The News and Observer Publishing Co. in
1955.
</TEXT>
