<DOCNO> AP891002-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1623EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Soviet-Psychiatry     10-02 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Psychiatry,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say They've Reformed Psychiatric Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet authorities have formed an independent
commission to monitor psychiatric abuses, an embassy spokesman
testified Monday, but U.S. experts said the reform was not adequate
to readmit the Soviets to the World Psychiatric Association.
   Seeking to bolster the Kremlin case, Georgi Markosov of the
Soviet Embassy appeared before a House panel to detail reforms his
government has taken to correct psychiatric abuses against
political and religious prisoners.
   The Soviet ``All-Union Scientific Society of Psychiatrists ...
is doing its utmost to implement and translate into reality the
needed reforms in the field of medical care and psychiatric
health,'' said Markosov, reading a statement prepared by the Soviet
society for the hearing.
   ``To prevent the use of psychiatry for non-medical purposes as
well as to assure maximum openness in specific cases of misuse of
psychiatry, an independent commission has been established, which
is composed of eight persons ... The commission is independent from
the Health Ministry or any (Communist) Party or state organs,''
Markosov said.
   Before this year, it was rare for Soviet officials to testify
before Congress, but since January, about a half dozen have done so.
   Markosov also listed other reforms, including:
   _New regulations that led to dropping 736,000 people from
so-called psychiatric registration lists. U.S. experts said the
lists contained 10.2 million names, and were used for job screening.
   _New rules that bar forcible commitment to a psychiatric
institution without the consent of patients or their relatives,
unless the patient poses a physical danger. ``Psychiatrists who
wrongly hospitalize mentally healthy persons may be sentenced to a
two-year prison term.''
   _Abolition in the Russian federation, the largest of the 15
Soviet republics, of two laws often used against dissidents.
   _A ban on the use of sulphazine, a drug made of pulverized
sulphur that has been injected into political dissidents, causing
extreme pain, fever and disorientation. Western experts say it has
no medical value.
   Most of the steps had been publicized previously, but the
existence of the commission was not known in the West, said another
witness, Peter Reddaway, a George Washington University professor
who has written two books on Soviet psychiatric abuses and was a
member of a U.S. delegation that visited Soviet psychiatric
institutions this year.
   ``It remains to be seen whether it is indeed vigorous and
independent,'' said Reddaway.
   The American Psychiatric Association, which supported the work
of the U.S. delegation, has voted to oppose readmission of the
Soviet group to the world body, which is scheduled to meet in
Athens, Greece, Oct. 11-16.
   ``It is my sincere hope as well as the hope of the American
Psychiatric Association, that there will be a time in the near
future when we can whole-heartedly welcome the All-Union Society of
Psychiatrists and Narcologists of the USSR into the World
Psychiatric Assocation,'' testified Ellen Mercer, head of
international programs for the U.S. organization.
   ``It is also our concern that, unfortunately, this time has not
yet arrived,'' said Mercer.
   Soviet health officials who in the past sent dissidents to
psychiatric institutions remain in senior government posts, said
Reddaway, and they could resume their abuses if there is a
conservative reaction along the lines of the crackdown in China
this summer.
   The officials he mentioned were Yevgeny Chazov, the health
minister, Nikolai Zharikov, last year appointed the head of the
Soviet Society of Psychiatrists and Narcologists, Georgy Morozov,
who for decades has headed the Serbsky Institute where many
political dissidents have been held in psychiatric care, Alexander
Churkin, chief psychiatrist of the ministry of health, and Marat
Vartanyan.
   These conservatives, said Reddaway, ``have a well justified fear
that if there is a genuine reform in Soviet psychiatry, they will
be swept out of office.''
   Senior Soviet psychiatric authorities want to be readmitted to
the World Psychiatric Association, said Reddaway, but ``the
reformers within Soviet psychology are opposed to it.''
   Denying the Soviets readmission to the world body, said
Reddaway, ``would delay genuine reform of Soviet psychiatry...''
   Soviet psychiatric abuses have been publicized for years by
Western experts, some of whom also testified Monday, and are now
being discussed more openly in the Soviet press.
   The U.S. Delegation to Assess Soviet Psychiatry, which visited
the Soviet Union this year, reported to Congress that ``while some
victims have been released, forced incarceration under the guise of
treatment for insanity, remains an institutional problem,'' said
Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., who presided over the hearing.
   ``Perhaps even worse, the perpetrators of these abuses remain in
key leadership positions in Soviet psychiatry,'' said Waxman,
chairman of the House Committee on Energy and Commerce Subcommittee
on Health and the Environment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1905EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SailboatStory     10-02 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sailboat Story,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Sailors Tell of Survival at Sea</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AUK2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four men whose 42-foot sailboat was
overturned in a storm say they drifted for nearly four months in
the South Pacific and survived by trapping rainwater, spearing fish
and eating seaweed.
   ``We needed a miracle, and we got one,'' New Zealand skipper
John Glennie said after the crewmen washed ashore Sunday and were
rescued on the Great Barrier Island. The four were all reported in
good condition.
   After wind pushed the overturned boat ashore, the survivors said
they spent their first night on land in 120 days, sheltered from
rain under a tree in the bush of the island, about 60 miles
northeast of Auckland.
   On Sunday, they walked through bush until breaking into an empty
cabin and finding warm clothes.
   Peter Speck, an island resident, first met the sailors at the
cabin.
   ``At first I thought these guys were nuts,'' Speck said. ``I
couldn't believe it.''
   The crew included owner and skipper Glennie, a sailor who
designed the craft for long-distance cruising; Phillip Hoffman and
Rick Hellriegel of New Zealand; and Jim Nalepka, 38, of
Minneapolis, Minn., who was in the second of two years as caterer
for the Outward Bound program in New Zealand.
   Nalepka's sister, Kathy Moynihan of New Brighton, Minn., said he
lost 25 pounds but was declared fit by doctors in Auckland after a
two-hour hospital visit.
   ``We never gave up hope. He kept hoping he was safe. ... This is
wonderful,'' she said. ``It's just an amazing story.''
   The sailors' trimaran Rose Noelle left Picton, on the northern
coast of the South Island of New Zealand, on June 1 for a
three-week Pacific Islands cruise that was to take them to Tonga.
   On the night of June 3, a strong wind grew to a 60-knot gale.
   ``About six o'clock in the morning there was a huge wave, and it
just flipped the boat upside down,'' Glennie said.
   The boat floated on its crossbeams and cabin top, with the cabin
top _ now the floor _ beneath a couple of feet of water, Glennie
said.
   The sailboat's light, buoyant bow rode high, so it always
pointed away from the wind, he said. The craft was stable and would
not sink unless it had broken apart.
   The men, jammed four abreast in its 54-inch width, cut a hole
through the hull of the yacht to gain dry access outside, without
having to swim through the now-watery tunnel of the hatch, Glennie
said.
   The yacht's two emergency locator beacons, designed to transmit
for 30 days, were switched on, but there was no sign from jets
overhead that their signals were detected.
   The boat was reported missing June 24 after it failed to arrive
in Tonga.
   For the first few weeks there were survival rations.
   ``We had plenty of soda stowed in the forward compartment,''
Glennie said. ``We had stacks of apples and kiwifruit and we got
plenty of moisture from those. But the drinks were rationed to a
few ounces every night.
   ``After about 40 days, when we had all come to terms with things
and began working as a team, we organized ourselves into making a
system to collect rainwater.''
   They split some plastic piping and placed the pieces together to
collect rainwater, which was drained into empty soft drink bottles,
Glennie said. They also ate seaweed and speared fish.
   ``We ate them raw, and we had plenty of vinegar on board to
marinate them in,'' he said.
   The sailors' families had given them up for dead, said Malcolm
Tomes, Glennie's brother-in-law.
   ``We were absolutely ecstatic to hear John's voice on the
phone,'' Tomes said. ``We were just so thrilled that he and the
rest of the crew are still alive after so many months ... The
celebrations are already under way.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
