<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Walton     10-02 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Walton,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arizona Death Row Inmate Wins U.S. Supreme Court Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arizona death row inmate who is challenging
the state's capital punishment law won a Supreme Court hearing
Monday.
   The court's eventual ruling in Jeffrey Alan Walton's appeal also
could affect death row inmates in Idaho and Montana, two states
that have death penalty laws similar to Arizona's.
   Walton was convicted of robbing and fatally shooting Thomas
Powell near Tucson in March 1986.
   Powell was robbed in a bar parking lot and then driven in his
own car to a secluded area where he was shot.
   A trial jury heard testimony that Walton fired the fatal shot.
Walton denied he killed Powell, swearing that a co-defendant was
the gunman.
   The jury did not specify whether it found Walton guilty of
premeditated murder or ``felony murder,'' the taking of a life
during commission of a felony.
   Walton's lawyers sought unsuccessfully during his sentencing
trial to introduce testimony indicating that the jury had been
undecided whether Walton killed Powell.
   The Arizona Supreme Court upheld Walton's conviction and death
sentence in a ruling that conflicts with a decision by the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The federal appeals court previously overturned a key provision
of Arizona's death penalty statute in the case of John Harvey
Adamson, convicted of murdering reporter Don Bolles. Bolles, who
had been investigating organized crime for The Arizona Republic in
Phoenix, died June 11, 1976, nine days after his car exploded.
   The 9th Circuit, setting aside Adamson's death sentence, said
Arizona's death penalty law unconstitutionally deprives defendants
of the right to a jury trial because the judge, not the jury,
decides whether an accused murderer is guilty of a crime warranting
capital punishment.
   The appeals court has jurisdiction in nine Western states,
including Arizona, Montana and Idaho.
   The case is Walton vs. Arizona, 88-7351.
</TEXT>
