<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Asks Legislature for Ban on Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: NEW throughout with strike background, editing; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev urged the
parliament Monday to impose a 15-month ban on strikes, which he
said are wrecking the economy and endangering development.
   He spoke at the end of a stormy two-hour debate on emergency
economic measures proposed by Lev Voronin, the first deputy
premier, the official news agency Tass reported.
   Gorbachev urged legislators to discuss the proposals and be
ready to vote on Tuesday.
   He referred to the possible ban on strikes as a ``necessary
measure ... called for to protect democratization from anarchy and
irresponsible management.''
   Plans for future economic development are ``under threat'' from
the strikes, he said.
   Voronin said the ailing economy lost $6.15 billion in July and
August because of strikes, and fuel shortages might mean inadequate
heat this winter.
   Proposals for the next 15 months include ``a prohibition on
conducting strikes ... in all branches of the economy,'' Tass said.
   The package also calls for a ``special form of administration''
for railroads in Armenia and Azerbaijan, with the ministries of
railroads, defense and interior responsible for protecting the
lines and their workers.
   Armenian activists say Azerbaijani railroad workers have blocked
the trains that carry 80 percent of Armenia's goods from other
parts of the Soviet Union. Food stores have been emptied of many
basic goods and even ambulances lack fuel.
   When the Supreme Soviet opened its fall session Sept. 25,
Gorbachev said decisive steps would be required if the rail lines
remained blocked.
   The neighboring republics in the Caucasus are in conflict over
Nagorno-Karabakh, a region that is part of Azerbaijan but has a
predominantly Armenian population.
   This year's most damaging strike was a walkout in July by
thousands of coal miners in the far north, Siberia, and the Don
Basin of the eastern Ukraine. It cost millions of dollars, and the
government agreed to economic and social reforms officials say will
cost about $3.08 billion.
   Strikes have become a common way of expressing ethnic
discontent. In addition to the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute, Russian
and other workers have struck factories in Moldavia and Estonia to
protest laws favoring native populations.
</TEXT>
