<HEAD>Administration Education Funding Policy Attacked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two administration officials caught the brunt
of criticisms Monday for President Bush's refusal at the education
summit to commit to an increase in federal funding for the nation's
schools.
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos irked a luncheon meeting of
black Republicans, telling them, ``Our role is not one of funding.''
   Across the street, Charles Kolb, a key Education Department
official who helped craft Bush's education budget, drew angry
responses from members of the Council of Urban Boards of Education
when he said the $353 billion estimated to be spent this year on
education by all levels of government is sufficient.
   Cavazos and Kolb were keeping to the line held by Bush at the
conclusion of the two-day summit last week with the nation's
governors who agreed jointly to develop national performance goals
by February.
   Milton Bins of the black GOP group, the Council of 100, sharply
questioned Cavazos on the administration's commitment to ensure
adequate funding to educate minority and disadvantaged youths.
   ``I am here to remind our nation that the problem (of equity
education) has not been solved,'' said Bins, noting that about 80
percent of most state legislators are from ``suburban or affluent
white communities.''
   ``There is no clear indication on the scene today that they are
going to take the advice from the governors,'' Bins added.
   Bins, deputy director of The Council of the Great City Schools,
was assured by Cavazos, the first Hispanic to head the Education
Department, that Bush continues to fight for equality. Cavazos
cited the president's support for funding specialized magnet
schools and for allowing parents to select the school their
children will attend.
   Kolb drew harsh criticism when he discussed Bush's stances on
funding and choice with the schools council, which is part of the
National School Boards Association.
   ``There was a general recognition that money wasn't the issue,''
said Kolb in summarizing the summit.
   ``The biggest challenge for all of us _ on the federal, state
and local levels _ is to find ways to deploy the resources'' that
are already available for education, Kolb said.
   Stephen Kafoury, a member of the Portland, Ore. school board,
said more money is needed for schools and stressed that to imply
otherwise would be ``disingenuous at best.''
   ``I thought this area had been declared a drug free zone and
here I am wondering what you've been smoking,'' said a sarcastic
Jonathan Wilson, of the Des Moines Independent Community School
District. ``You've got to look at what we're doing with the money.''
   Wilson's was greeted with cheers and applause when he compared
the amounts spent on the military and the savings and loan
associations bailout with federal spending on education.
   ``He bailed out the S&amp;Ls. The man didn't say he wanted to be the
S&amp;L president, he said he wanted to be the education president,''
said Wilson, referring to Bush's pledge during last year's
presidential campaign.
   ``What we need is more resources, not someone talking
platitudes. The real test is what are the resources and where are
they coming from.''
   NSBA President James Oglesby admitted the group ``beat up on
Kolb'' but said it was because many of the members are frustrated
volunteers.
