<HEAD>Bush Names Fleischman Acting SEC Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday named Securities and
Exchange Commissioner Edward H. Fleischman as acting head of the
panel while the Senate ponders his first choice, White House aide
Richard C. Breeden.
   The designation of Fleischman as chairman was an interim action
and does not represent a backing away from Breeden's nomination,
said deputy White House press secretary Alixe Glen.
   The previous chairman, David S. Ruder, left the job on Friday to
return to teaching at Northwestern University's law school.
   Bush nominated Breeden, assistant to the president for issue
analysis and the White House point man on the recent savings and
loan restructuring bill, last August.
   However, the Senate has yet to act on the nomination. A
committee vote is expected later this month.
   Fleischman, 57, a former New York lawyer, has been a member of
the SEC since 1986.
