<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-02 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten families are offering their table
scraps, raked-up leaves and old newspapers to development of a city
garbage profile.
   Susan Young, a regional environmental planner, said the city has
little information on what, or how much, Tulsa residents are
tossing away, so families were enlisted for special garbage pickup
and analysis.
   ``The biggest problem we have in doing any kind of planning on
solid waste management is we don't have any information about how
much is out there,'' Ms. Young said.
   The families began Sunday to separate their trash into
categories, including yard clippings, plastics and paper. They will
continue the effort for a year.
   Ms. Young said the project will provide valuable statistics. The
goal is to find new ways to encourage recycling.
   ``Any estimate, plus or minus 100 percent, is so much better
than what we have now, which is sitting down with a cocktail napkin
and saying, `Well, how much (trash) did you have last month?' ''
Ms. Young said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clare Crawford doesn't like to blow her own horn,
but making a musical instrument out of plumbing pipes helped the
16-year-old win a trip to the Nobel Prize ceremonies in Sweden.
   Ms. Crawford, a high school senior, beat out nine other
finalists in a contest sponsored by the Chicago Museum of Science
and Industry. She won $500 in addition to the free trip to
Stockholm for the Nobel ceremonies Dec. 10.
   ``It's pretty exciting. It's a great experience to be able to
see the Nobel Prize ceremony,'' said Ms. Crawford, who plans to
attend Harvard University and major in physics for a career in
research.
   Ms. Crawford, who plays piano and trumpet, was named the
museum's outstanding young scientist for 1989, with such projects
to her credit as a woodwind instrument she built out of plumbing
pipes to study pitch.

