<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0675 10-02 0877</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Lobbyist Says He `Played By Rules' to Get Favorable HUD Deals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 14th graf, bgng: In one xxx to UPDATE with
Manafort associates dealing with Dean; INSERTS one graf after 17th graf
pvs, bgng: Although he xxx to UPDATE with Lantos telling Manafort his actions
`questionable'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican lobbyist with former ties to the
White House told Congress Monday that he ``played by the rules'' in
obtaining lucrative federal housing subsidies. But the head of a
House panel charged he had reaped the benefits of ``a greased,
sweetheart deal.''
   Paul Manafort, a former campaign adviser to President Bush and
former President Reagan and a former business partner of Republican
National Chairman Lee Atwater, underwent hostile questioning from
disbelieving members of a House panel probing scandals at the
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   Manafort, who three months ago acknowledged to the same panel
that his work amounted to ``influence peddling,'' denied being
given an advance tip by insiders at HUD to the availability of HUD
subsidies for renovating low-income housing projects, which were
prized profit-makers for developers.
   He said his lobbying firm ``has worked within the existing
system at HUD.''
   ``We played by the rules,'' Manafort said. ``I understand that
the subcommittee views the process as fundamentally flawed. I am
not here to argue with the subcommittee about the process, or to
defend it ...''
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., took sharp issue with Manafort's
description of a New Jersey housing project in which Manafort was a
partner, and which benefited from more than $31 million in federal
subsidies for renovation and tax credits.
   ``This was a greased, sweetheart deal, where all the
participants knew what the final outcome would be,'' said Lantos,
chairman of the House Government Operations subcommittee on
employment and housing.
   Manafort contended that partners in the development faced normal
business risks, including the potential loss of a $450,000
downpayment, in buying the 326 units of dilapidated housing and
putting together a package of subsidies and financing.
   But Lantos said HUD documents showed Manafort's group was
assured of the HUD subsidies in contacts with top agency officials
before it invested the money. Lantos said Manafort and his partners
also benefitted from HUD specifications that were written to
exclude other developers. He said it was ``ludicrious'' for
Manafort to claim he faced any normal business risk.
   Lantos produced HUD documents which he said showed Deborah Gore
Dean, former executive assistant to HUD Secretary Sam Pierce, was
passing along copies of HUD project proposals to Manafort even
though he was not directly involved in them.
   ``There was no risk here. There was a prearranged deal which
went through as it was prearranged,'' Lantos said.
   ``There was a sweetheart deal with Deborah Dean,'' Lantos said.
``Deborah Dean promised them the units (of subsidy) and she
delivered on the units. Those are the facts.''
   Dean is one of four former top officials of HUD, including
Pierce, who have refused to testify before the panel by invoking
their constitutional rights against self-incrimination. Dean has
been at the focus of the panel's probe into political favoritism in
the awarding of HUD subsidies to developers.
   In one 1986 memo released by the panel, Dean had written another
HUD official should amass ``great wells of power and wield it on my
behalf.'' Manafort said he did not recall receiving the HUD
documents, but said they involved a partner, Victor Cruse, whom he
had introduced to Dean.
   Laurence Gay, an associate in Manafort's lobbying firm,
testified he met with Dean and discussed the New Jersey project.
Another associate in the firm, Richard Davis, was a former White
House liason to HUD who said he had been in contact with Dean daily
while in government.
   Manafort faced questions about his failure in his appearance
last June to recall all the HUD-related projects on which he had
served as a consultant or lobbyist.
   Manafort said he and his lobbying firm, Black, Manafort, Stone
and Kelly, had failed to fully check all their records but had now
produced a complete list. Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., said that
involved 21 separate clients.
   Although he faced contentious questioning, Manafort was offered
reassurance by one of the panel members. Rep. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., said, ``In no way have I ever seen anything related to
your activity that would suggest any illegalities.''
   Lantos, however, later told Manafort that ``your're trying to be
evasive,'' and that while his deal may not have broken laws `` ``it
certainly was highly questionable in terms of ethics.'' As a
result, Lantos said, money was denied to ``infintely more worthy
projects.''
   Lantos said subcommittee staff last week visited the Seabrook
project in Upper Deerfield, N.J., in which Manafort and Cruse are
partners. He described it as a ``slum'' with ``shocking''
conditions, including water-damaged apartments with no
refrigerators renting for more than $700 a month, including federal
subsidies.
   The panel questioned Cruse and Manafort at length about the
renovations and the failure so far to install gutters. Manafort
said that while 182 units are occupied, construction is still under
way and asserted, ``When we are finished with construction, we
believe the tenants will be happy.''
</TEXT>
