<SECOND>AM-US-Poland,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Tweaks Administration Over Aid To Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell again
goaded the Bush administration Monday on its ``timidity'' in U.S.
policy toward Poland and said the Democratic Congress will press
ahead with additional aid for the new non-communist government.
   Mitchell, who met with top Polish officials last week, said the
new government led by members of the Solidarity trade union is
``firmly committed'' to establishing a more Western-style economy.
``The only question is whether the West will make it possible for
this transformation to succeed,'' he said in a floor speech.
   He noted that Bush has voiced support for new loans to Poland
through the World Bank and International Monetary Fund. But he said
those moves alone will not meet the country's immediate needs.
   ``It appears the administration remains hesitant to move forward
until Poland's economic reforms already are fully in place,'' said
Mitchell, D-Maine. ``In light of our great stake in the success of
the new Polish government, I believe this response is excessively
timid.''
   The comments were Mitchell's fourth public attack on Bush's
Poland policy in two weeks.
   ``Congress will do its best to ensure that the United States
does in fact play a leading role in encouraging the success of
Poland's brave experiment,'' he said, pointing to a three-year $1.2
billion aid package passed by the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee that dwarfs Bush's three-year, $119 million program of
economic development aid.
   ``I call upon the administration to abandon its timidity and to
take advantage of this historic opportunity to provide the kind of
help that is necessary for democracy and open government to succeed
in Poland,'' he said.
