<FIRST>u w AM-Soviet-Jews     10-02 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>^AM-Soviet-Jews,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Emigration, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jewish Emigration From Soviet Union Sets Record for Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second straight month, Jewish
emigration from the Soviet Union reached an all-time high, a
spokesman for the National Conference on Soviet Jewry announced
Monday.
   In September, 8,442 Jews left the Soviet Union, up from the
previous monthly high set in August of 6,756 emigres. Before this
year, the previous high was set in October 1979, when 4,746
emigrated.
   At the current rate of emigration, ``we are within sight of
surpassing the benchmark year of 1979,'' when 51,320 Jews left the
Soviet Union, said Jerry Strober, a spokesman for the conference.
   The cumulative total this year is 41,886. Of last month's
emigres, 1,042 or 12.3 percent, went to Israel, the conference
announced.
   The group, which has been monitoring and lobbying for Jewish
emigration from the Soviet Union for two decades, repeated its call
for the Soviet parliament to pass legislation liberalizing
regulations for people seeking to leave.
</TEXT>
