<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     10-02 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>30 Percent of Voters Registered on First Day in Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first day of registration for
February's national election went smoothly and about 30 percent of
eligible voters signed up, a ranking international observer
reported Monday.
   Spokesmen for an opposition coalition, however, accused the
Sandinista government's electoral authorities of foot-dragging and
said about half its own representatives were not given credentials
to observe the registration.
   Joao Baena Soraes, secretary-general of the Organization of
American States, described the complaints as ``administrative'' and
said his organization's 52 observers throughout the country
reported about 570,000 of an estimated 1.9 million eligible voters
registered on Sunday, the first day.
   ``There was some (opposition) discussion of administrative
aspects, for example the delay in accrediting representatives and
the payment of the per diem, but ... everything proceeded
normally,'' he told reporters Monday. ``I did not verify any
obstacle or any complaint that could compromise the process.''
   Baena visited 35 registration centers Sunday in Managua, Leon,
Granada and in two villages.
   Voters are permitted to register at 4,394 centers on the first
four Sundays of October. General elections to be held Feb. 25 are
for a president and vice president, mayors and a 90-member National
Assembly.
   Publisher Violeta Barrios de Chamorro of the National Opposition
Union coalition is challenging President Daniel Ortega, who seeks
another term as candidate of the ruling leftist Sandinista party.
Eight other parties are contesting the presidential election.
   Ortega called early elections as part of regional accords with
the presidents of Honduras, Costa Rica, Guatemala and El Salvador
calling for demobilization of the Contras, U.S.-supported rebels
fighting the Sandinistas.
   Luis Sanchez, spokesman for the opposition alliance, told The
Associated Press registration was slow and about half the
opposition's representatives were not given credentials in time to
help supervising the process.
   He said the alliance would file a formal complaint with the
Supreme Electoral Council.
   Of seven Managua-area registration centers the AP visited
Sunday, the coalition was represented at only two. Other opposition
parties had observers at two of the remaining five and there were
no opposition observers at three.
   Observers from the Sandinista National Liberation Front were
present at all seven centers.
   An official said a registration center in Chontales province was
moved ``to a safer place'' five miles away because of armed men in
the area, presumably rebels. Ofiel Acuna, president of the regional
election council, said the center was in El Guarumo, 100 miles east
of Managua.
   There were no reports of Contra military activity on Sunday.
Most of the rebels are in jungle camps in Honduras, but a few
Contra groups remain in Nicaragua, including Chontales.
   A joint commission of the OAS and United Nations is charged with
supervising the demobilization and re-integration of the Contras
into civilian life.
   Baena said the necessary elements for fair elections appear to
be present. ``Generally, I believe that on Feb. 25 there will be
free and honest elections,'' he said.
   Thirty U.N. observers watched the registration Sunday but did
not comment.
</TEXT>
