<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1809EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-YonkersDeseg     10-02 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Yonkers Deseg,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices Hear Case of Defiant Yonkers Councilmen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Supreme Court Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge acted within his powers by
fining four Yonkers, N.Y., city councilmen for disobeying his
desegregation order, a lawyer for the federal government told the
Supreme Court on Monday.
   But an attorney for the councilmen argued that the judge could
have changed the city zoning ordinance, but chose instead to
violate the councilmen's common-law right of legislative immunity,
as well as their constitutionally protected freedom of speech.
   The case, argued before the high court Monday, is an outgrowth
of the bitter, nine-year battle to desegregate Yonkers. The
justices are expected to rule by July.
   The case centers around four city councilmen _ Nicholas V.
Longo, Edward J. Fagan Jr., Peter Chema and Vice Mayor Henry
Spallone _ who voted against a judge's order to pass a legislative
package designed to lure subsidized housing to the city's white
neighborhoods.
   Kenneth W. Starr, the federal government's solicitor general,
praised U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand for not employing more
stringent tactics to compel the councilmen to obey his July 26,
1988, order.
   In 1985, Sand found Yonkers that had for 40 years deliberately
concentrated virtually all its subsidized housing in the southwest
part of the city to keep blacks away from whites. Sand ordered the
city to build 200 units of public housing in white neighborhoods in
1988 and to plan for 600 more. The city appealed, lost and seemed
close to agreeing on a desegregation plan until Yonkers residents
raised loud objections. The council defied Sand's order by voting
4-3 against the desegregation plan.
   Sand then set fines of $500 a day and threatened to jail the
four unless they obeyed his order.
   ``They simply chose not to obey, and furthermore, they said, `We
don't have to obey,''' Starr told the justices.
   Sand had also set fines for the city _ starting at $100 a day
and doubling daily until they reached $1 million daily _ prompting
Councilmen Chema and Longo to change their votes as Yonkers faced
imminent bankruptcy.
   The councilmen ultimately paid $3,500 apiece in fines; none went
to jail. Yonkers paid a total of $819,000 in fines, which were
upheld by the Supreme Court.
   James D. Harmon Jr., the attorney representing the councilmen,
argued Monday that the district court used ``the most intrusive
means'' available to compel the four to change their votes,
violating their legislative immunity. Harmon also argued that to
vote is to exercise one's freedom of speech, which is protected by
the First Amendment.
   ``Is this like the court ordering somebody to say something they
don't want to say?'' Justice Byron White asked Harmon at one point.
``Courts are always doing that.''
   White gave the example of courts ordering employers to post
notices they'd rather quash, and suggested Harmon could make his
argument without invoking the Constitution.
   Harmon also argued that there are limits to judicial authority,
and that the councilmen were compelled to vote their consciences.
This prompted Justice Anthony Kennedy to ask whether the councilmen
had the right to force the city into bankruptcy.
   ``Yes, and to be held accountable for that at the ballot box,''
Harmon said.
   The cases are Spallone vs. U.S., 88-854; Chema vs. U.S., 88-856;
and Longo vs. U.S., 88-870.
</TEXT>
