<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Perkins     10-02 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Perkins,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Agrees To Consider Use Of Undercover Agents To Gain Confessions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to consider
allowing the use of police undercover agents to elicit confessions
from jailed criminal suspects.
   The justices announced they will use the the case of an Illinois
murder suspect to consider weakening its famous 1966 Miranda ruling
that requires police to warn suspects of their right to an attorney
and to remain silent.
   An Illinois appeals court ruled last November that police
violated the rights of Lloyd Perkins when they planted an
undercover agent in jail to question him about a murder.
   Perkins was charged with fatally shooting Richard Stephenson on
Nov. 8, 1984, in Fairview Heights.
   Police lacked a suspect in the murder in 1986 when Donald
Charlton, an inmate at Graham Correctional Facility in Hillsboro,
told authorities he had information about the homicide.
   Police then placed Charlton and undercover narcotics officer
John Parisi in the Montgomery County Jail on March 31, 1986.
Perkins was being held there awaiting trial on a charge of
aggravated battery unrelated to the murder.
   Parisi, using the alias Vito Bianco, wore motorcycle garb and
told Perkins he was interested in planning an escape. Parisi,
Charlton and Perkins arranged to meet in the cellbock after the
other inmates went to sleep.
   At that meeting Parisi asked Perkins whether he had ever ``done
someone,'' a phrase the appeals court said was intended to elicit
information about any killings in which Perkins took part.
   The appeals court said Perkins then recounted in detail the
killing of Stephenson.
   Perkins then was taken to the county courthouse, placed under
arrest for murder and given his Miranda warnings.
   A state judge in 1987 ruled that Perkins' jailhouse statements
to Charlton and Parisi about the Stephenson killing could not be
admitted as evidence.
   State officials, seeking to have the statements admitted, said
the Miranda ruling is designed to protect suspects against police
coercion.
   The officials said since Parisi and Charlton had engaged in
friendly conversation pretending to enlist Perkins in a jailbreak,
there could be no coercion.
   But the Illinois appeals court said the Miranda ruling applies
whenever a suspect is in custody, ``even when the purpose of the
custody is unrelated to the purpose of the interrogation.''
   The Supreme Court in 1980 ruled that law enforcement officials
cannot hire jailhouse informants to induce criminal defendants in
custody to make incriminating statements.
   The justices in that ruling relied on their own 1964 decision _
handed down two years before Miranda _ that barred government
agents from eliciting incriminating information from defendants
entitled to a lawyer's help during interrogation.
   Illinois officials said the 1980 high court ruling permits
Parisi's questioning of Perkins because no murder charges against
Perkins had been filed.
   Under such circumstances, the state said, ``there exists no
inherent danger that a suspect will believe he has no choice but to
submit to (police) will and to confess.''
   The case is Illinois vs. Perkins, 88-1972.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
