<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0655 10-02 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0655,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aides Say Shamir Will Not Alter Peace Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to include Jordanian quote and UPDATE casualties;
picks up 11th `Israeli soldiers...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir does not intend
to alter his Palestinian peace plan despite pressure from the
United States, Egypt and the rival Labor Party, his aides said
Monday.
   ``Only five months have passed'' since Shamir presented his plan
for elections as a first step toward negotiations and ``the prime
minister does not see any reason to change it,'' spokesman Yossi
Ahimeir said.
   Egyptian, Israeli and U.S. officials have been meeting in New
York and Israel's governing coalition _ Shamir's rightist Likud
bloc and the center-left Labor Party _ is preparing to debate
Mubarak's efforts to bring Palestinians and Israelis together in
preliminary talks.
   At the United Nations in New York, Foreign Minister Marwan Kasim
of Jordan urged the United States, Soviet Union and others to
persuade Israel to talk with the Palestine Liberation Organization
and move ``out of the circle of violence and oppression ... into a
state of security, stability and constructiveness.''
   The Cabinet leadership, including Likud and Labor ministers, is
to meet Thursday about Mubarak's ideas.
   Likud rejects a formula backed by Egypt and the United States
that involves trading occupied land for peace and including people
deported by Israel in a Palestinian negotiating delegation. Labor,
led by Finance Minister Shimon Peres, supports both ideas.
   Shamir's proposed elections would choose delegates to negotiate
with Israel about interim autonomy in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
occupied by Israel since the 1967 Middle East war.
   Mubarak raised the land-for-peace proposal after many
Palestinians dismissed Shamir's plan as an effort to end the
uprising against Israeli occupation that began Dec. 8, 1987.
   At Tammun village in the West Bank, Mahmud Hamed Bani Awde, 22,
was stabbed to death Monday for reasons not immediately clear.
   The Israeli army said the killing was a family matter and was
under police investigation, but the national news agency Itim and
Arab reporters said Awde belonged to the Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, a Marxist group, and the murder may have
been political.
   In the Gaza Strip, a soldier was slightly injured Monday by a
rock thrown by Palestinians in the Jabaliya refugee camp, the army
said.
   Elsewhere in the occupied lands, Arab hospital officials
reported 11 Palestinians wounded by army gunfire, including a
15-year-old boy hospitalized in Israel with a critical head wound.
   Shops in Nablus and Bethlehem closed Monday to protest the
shooting deaths of two Palestinians youths the previous day, Arab
reports said.
   Israeli soldiers or civilians have killed at least 581
Palestinians in the uprising, and 123 Palestinians have been slain
by fellow Arabs, most as suspected collaborators with Israel. Forty
Israelis have died in the violence.
   Mubarak telephoned Shamir on Friday to talk about his proposals.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III issued a veiled threat to
drop support for the election plan unless Israel moved toward the
proposals made by Egypt, the only Arab country to have made peace
with Egypt.
   Baker said last week the United States would ``have to go back
to the drawing board'' on plans for Middle East peace if Israel
rejected Mubarak's ideas.
   Avi Pazner, another Shamir aide, said Israel did not see Baker's
comment as a threat but added that the government would not bow to
U.S. pressure.
   ``Everybody knows you can't twist Israel's arm when you want to
get something,'' he told The Associated Press in a telephone
interview.
   Yossi Ben-Aharon, director of Shamir's office, said including
deported Palestinians in a negotiating team was a ploy to sneak the
Palestine Liberation Organization, which Israel defines as a
terrorist group, into the peace process.
   Peres, the Labor Party leader, noted that Mubarak did not
mention two Arab demands Israel has found most objectionable: a
direct role for the PLO and creation of a Palestinian state.
   He criticized what he called Shamir's effort to create ``a new
Palestinian people'' who agreed with Israel on all points.
   ``The opinions of the Palestinians, the sentiments of the
Palestinians ... must be known not only by every Israeli, but to
every Israeli politician,'' he said on television. ``We must
negotiate with people who do not agree with us.''
</TEXT>
