<FIRST>u a AM-FactoryMuseum     10-02 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Museum,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consultants Push Contemporary Art Museum to Bolster Milltown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH ADAMS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Converting an abandoned, 28-building
factory into a $77.5 million contemporary art museum could
revitalize this remote milltown, consultants said Monday.
   A commission is working on such a museum, but critics question
whether art lovers would drive to North Adams _ three hours
northwest of Boston, four hours from New York _ for the stark
enticements of contemporary art.
   Backers of the so-called Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary
Art want to use a plant complex abandoned in 1984 by the town's
largest employer, Sprague Electric. They want to convert the vast,
grimy plant into rooms of unique environmental works or sculptures.
   Sprague employed more than 1,000 people before relocating to
Connecticut. A draft of the consultants' feasibility study projects
the museum could employ 640 people in the town of 16,000 people
where unemployment is about 4 percent.
   Consultants hired by the commission project as many as 150,000
people would visit the museum in a year, pumping $22 million into
the region's economy.
   ``The sheer reality of marketing this museum will depend in a
certain extent to a creative approach,'' said Dennis Bidwell, one
of the consultants.
   The idea of turning the complex of 28 buildings into 350,000
square feet of gallery space was devised by Thomas Krens, former
director of the Williams College Art Museum in the Berkshires.
Shortly after launching the project, Krens was named director of
the Guggenheim Museum in New York.
   Plans for the museum call for an accompanying restaurant and
luxury condominiums selling at $160,000 to $250,000.
   ``The project will work,'' Don Bonz, another of the consultants,
told the commission Monday during review of the draft study.
   The commission is looking for $35 million from the state, spread
over four or five years. The remaining $44.5 million would come
from private donations.
   Members of the commission did not take final action on
feasibility of the project. They endorsed the draft study and
scheduled a presentation to the state Dec. 11.
</TEXT>
