<FIRST>r i AM-Kasparov-Chess     10-02 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kasparov-Chess,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kasparov Wins Dutch Tournament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TILBURG, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World chess champion Garri Kasparov
of the Soviet Union won the 13th annual Interpolis chess tournament
Monday with a record score of 12 points in 14 matches.
   Viktor Korchnoi, a Soviet exile who lives in Switzerland,
finished second.
   First prize in the $50,000 event was $12,000. Kasparov's
performance in this southern Dutch city also gave him to 2,795
points for the year on the World Chess Federation's international
ranking list, surpassing the record 2,785 earned by former champion
Bobby Fischer in 1972.
   The win at Tilburg, where the maximum possible score was 14,
extends an undefeated string for the 26-year-old Soviet grandmaster
that began in 1981. He does not plan to enter any more tournaments
this year.
   Korchnoi, 58, compiled 8{ points in the tournament and won
$8,000 for his second-place finish.
</TEXT>
