<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Labor 1stLd-Writethru a0696 10-02 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Labor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Socialists Abandon Non-Nuclear Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs with delegates supporing PLO and clarification
of block casting of millions of votes; picks up 6th pvs `Under the'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition Labor Party abandoned
its controversial policy of unilateral nuclear disarmament Monday,
overturning the vote-losing doctrine at its annual conference.
   It also approved a motion urging Israel to begin a dialogue with
the Palestine Liberation Organization and called the Palestinian
uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip a ``just
revolt.''
   Israel refuses to negotiate with the PLO, which it describes as
a terrorist group bent on destroying the Jewish state.
   The motion said that, since Israel seized the territories in the
1967 Middle East war, ``the Israeli military occupation has
prevented the Palestinians from living under their own chosen form
of government and enjoying civil and political rights.''
   Delegates reaffirmed previous party positions backing the right
of both Palestinians and Israelis to states with internationally
recognized borders and calling the PLO the only legitimate
representative of the Palestinians.
   It referred to the 21-month-old uprising in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip as ``the just revolt of the Palestinian people calling
for an end to the `iron fist' policy of the Israeli military ...
and a withdrawal from the occupied territories.''
   After sometimes heated debate, delegates voted for a policy that
commits a Labor Party government to give up Britain's nuclear
arsenal only as part of a negotiated arms deal.
   Dismayed left wingers hung peace symbols from balconies in the
conference hall as speakers warned that the socialist movement must
change or suffer a fourth successive election defeat by
Conservative Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   ``It puts us in a very strong position to argue for an effective
and realistic initiative and to get verifiable (nuclear arms)
agreements,'' party leader Neil Kinnock said after the vote on the
first full day of the weeklong conference.
   Delegates at the convention in this south England resort cast
votes totaling 3.6 million to 2.4 million to ditch unilateral
nuclear disarmament after leaders of big, moderate trade unions
swung behind Kinnock.
   There are 1,500 conference delegates but the votes are counted
in the millions because the leaders of trade union that control 90
percent of the voting power cast blocks of tens of thousands of
votes based on the memberships of their unions.
   In a victory for party leftists, the conference voted by a 4-2
margin for a Labor government to cut defense expenditures by
one-fourth, bringing it in line with the average in other West
European members of NATO.
   Under the new policy, a Labor government would retain Britain's
submarine-launched Polaris nuclear missiles. It would also stick to
Mrs. Thatcher's decision to replace them in the early 1990s with
U.S. Trident missiles, which are nine times more powerful than
Polaris missiles.
   Legislator Tony Benn, a former energy secretary and doyen of the
Labor left, accused the party of betraying ``the basis of our whole
policy.''
   ``Britain does not need nuclear weapons. There is no Soviet
nuclear threat. That is the challenge we cannot ignore,'' declared
Benn to cheers from sections of the conference hall.
   A succession of speakers cited strides in superpower arms
control negotiations since Soviet leader Mikhail s. Gorbachev took
office, and they said a new Labor policy suited the improved
East-West relations.
   But others argued simply that Labor must change to win.
   ``We know it is the policy which is at fault, not the
presentation,'' said delegate Sylvia Heal. ``The leadership has
been accused of betrayal. But the people who will be guilty of
betrayal are those who by their actions ensure Thatcher's return
for another term.''
   Labor adopted its policy on nuclear weapons in 1981 as the party
lurched left after losing power to Mrs. Thatcher two years
previously.
   Polls show the policy was a major factor in Labor's two
subsequent defeats by Mrs. Thatcher in 1983 and 1987. She must call
the next election by mid-1992.
   Dropping the non-nuclear doctrine was part of a major new policy
platform aimed at shifting the party toward the center. The
conference is to vote on the changes, the result of a two-year
review, through the week.
</TEXT>
