<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Stevens-Abortion     10-02 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Stevens-Abortion,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Stevens Removes Himself from Illinois Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice John Paul Stevens will
not take part in a key Illinois case over abortion rights to be
decided during the 1989-90 term, a court spokeswoman said Monday.
   Stevens had not disqualified himself when the justices agreed
last July 3 to review the case, one of three abortion disputes
before the high court this term.
   But a minor court order issued in the Illinois case Monday noted
that Stevens did not participate.
   Asked about that, court spokeswoman Toni House said the justice
had disqualified himself from the case for unstated reasons.
   Stevens was one of four dissenters from the court's decision
last July letting states make abortions harder to get. He has
provided a consistent vote in support of the 1973 court decision
that women have a constitutional right to abortion.
   The Illinois case focuses on a state law that would require
abortion clinics to add services and equipment now found only in
hospitals.
   The law could force many clinics to close down, and could add up
to $50 to the cost of an abortion performed in the first three
months of pregnancy.
   In invalidating the law, lower courts said it violated a portion
of the 1973 ruling in Roe vs. Wade that limited state regulation
over first-trimester abortions.
   Illinois officials are not asking the justices to use the
Illinois case to reverse Roe vs. Wade, but legal experts say the
court's ruling could chip away at the trimester-by-trimester
approach taken in the 1973 decision.
   The two other abortion cases under high court study this term
focus on parental notification requirements for unwed minors
seeking to end their pregnancies in Minnesota and Ohio. Stevens has
not disqualified himself from those cases.
   The Illinois case is Turnock vs. Ragsdale, 88-790.
</TEXT>
