<FIRST>u a AM-BakkerTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0701 10-02 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bakker Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bakker Testifies He Accepted $3.1 Million in Bonuses</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with both sides resting their
cases, testimony from PTL bankruptcy trustee, hotel supervisor; edits to
conform. Picks up 17th graf pvs: `Ms. Smith ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL founder Jim Bakker testified Monday
at his fraud trial that he and his wife, Tammy, accepted $3.1
million in bonuses while the ministry's finances foundered.
   Bakker said PTL board members granted the bonuses ``of their own
free will'' and often told him, ``I was worth much more than this,
and they would say that over and over again.''
   Bakker left the witness stand Monday, completing 10 hours of
testimony that began Friday. Both sides rested their cases Monday,
with closing arguments scheduled for Tuesday. The case could go to
the jury as early as Wednesday.
   The disgraced television evangelist testified that he raised
more than $425 million for PTL from 1984 to 1987, when he and his
wife received $3.1 million in bonuses.
   Bakker was asked by his lawyer, George Davis, what he did with
the $425 million.
   ``I put it to the work of Jesus Christ,'' he said.
   During defense questioning, Bakker summed up his defense: ``We
were a church, and people always wanted to run it like a business.
I had to keep telling them, this was a church, not a business.''
   As Bakker left court during a break, he was smiling, saying, ``I
feel fine.'' He turned to Davis and said, ``This is a nice place to
visit but I didn't plan to live here.''
   In other testimony, M.C. Benton, the trustee overseeing the
ministry's property since it filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection from creditors, testified PTL was $50 million in debt
and had $160 million in claims against it from ``lifetime
partners'' when Bakker resigned in March 1987.
   Bakker, 49, is charged with 15 counts of wire fraud, eight
counts of mail fraud and one count of conspiracy to commit wire and
mail fraud. Bakker is accused of diverting more than $3.7 million
in PTL money for his own benefit and of conspiring to defraud PTL
followers to support his lifestyle.
   If convicted, he faces up to 120 years in prison and more than
$5 million in fines.
   Richard Dortch, PTL's former executive vice president, was
sentenced Aug. 24 to eight years in prison and fined $200,000 under
a plea bargain. Dortch pleaded guilty to two counts of wire fraud
and one count each of mail fraud and conspiracy and testified
against Bakker.
   At the heart of the government's case is the charge that Bakker
failed to live up to his promises of providing lodging at PTL
facilities for nearly 153,000 ``partners,'' people who sent in
gifts of $1,000 or more.
   Bakker is accused of diverting money from $158 million in
contributions solicited to build lodging for donors. Bakker
testified Friday that based on his own calculations he could
accommodate more than 211,000 partners.
   ``Your long list (of available lodging) for the partners is
really a recent fabrication you prepared for this trial?'' special
prosecutor Deborah Smith asked Bakker.
   ``That's a lie,'' he responded.
   Christine Howe, a supervisor at PTL's Heritage Grand Hotel,
testified she had to turn away thousands of guests each month
because there was no room for them.
   Ms. Smith said Bakker failed to tell PTL board members about the
ministry's money problems.
   ``I don't know how the board members could not be aware of the
financial crisis at Heritage USA,'' Bakker testified. ``They knew
we had cash flow problems and they voted to borrow funds to pay for
them.''
   Ms. Smith asked Bakker if he was contradicting testimony from
six board members who said they didn't know about the ministry's
financial problems.
   ``I would tell them we were in great financial need. They were
always up to date on all the financial information,'' Bakker said.
``I gave them the information to the best of my ability.''
   But Bakker later acknowledged he may have painted a rosy picture
of PTL's finances to fellow board members.
   ``I was a minister,'' he said. ``I did my best to keep them
informed and I know I was positive in the face of turmoil at times.
I preached faith.''
</TEXT>
