<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Clouthier     10-02 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Clouthier,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends, Foes in Mexico Mourn Former Candidate's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TALLI NAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and foes of the conservative National
Action Party on Monday mourned the death in a traffic accident of
Manuel J. Clouthier, the party's presidential nominee in 1988
elections.
   The charismatic, 55-year-old Clouthier, who ran against
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, was killed on Sunday while
campaigning for local candidates in his home state of Sinaloa in
the northwest.
   He was considered an architect of pragmatic, business-oriented
politics within National Action.
   Salinas, in Washington on his first official visit to the United
States, called Clouthier's death ``very lamentable,'' describing
him as a Mexican ``who sought to promote the good of the country,''
the government news service Notimex said.
   Newspapers lauded Clouthier's efforts to increase democracy in
the country, which has been dominated by Salinas' Institutional
Revolutionary Party for 60 years.
   Salinas registered just over 50 percent of the vote to
Clouthier's 17 percent in an election Clouthier described as
``filthy.''
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who finished second to Salinas with 31
percent of the vote, on Monday sent his ``condolences for the
tragic death of a man who loved his country and set an example for
his party members.''
   Cardenas's coalition of followers formed a new leftist party
following the presidential contest in July 1988.
   Clouthier's death came two weeks after his party celebrated its
50th anniversary and three months after National Action won its
first victory in a governor's election in Baja California.
   Ernesto Ruffo, the first opposition governor-elect in 60 years,
left the Baja state capital of Mexicali for Sinaloa state as soon
as he heard of Clouthier's death.
   Javier Calvo Manriquez, National Action's president in Sinaloa,
was killed with Clouthier when their vehicle crossed a highway lane
divider and ran into a heavy truck transporting papayas and bananas.
   A thousand people lined the streets Monday outside the Church of
the Sacred Family in Culiacan, where Clouthier's body was taken.
Funeral services were scheduled for Tuesday.
   Clouthier is survived by his wife, Leticia Carrillo de
Clouthier, and 10 children.
</TEXT>
