<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru   10-02 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0670,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Stakes Hopes on `More Constructive Soviet Role' in Indochina</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 4-5 bgng: ``Vietnamese intransigence,'' with defense
of Vietnam policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior State Department official said Monday
more fighting might occur in Indochina but the United States hopes
``a more constructive Soviet role'' could help revive the stalled
Cambodian peace process and avert civil war.
   ``Unfortunately, there is a prospect of more fighting'' in the
Southeast Asian country,'' Deputy Assistant Secretary of State
David F. Lambertson told a Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee.
   But ``we hope it is not prolonged'' since the failed peace
conference at Paris in August ``was not the final chapter,''
Lambertson said.
   ``Vietnamese intransigence'' at that conference is one reason
the United States believes it is premature to normalize relations
with Vietnam and will try to maintain the diplomatic and economic
isolation of Vietnam, Lambertson said.
   ``In the current situation we plan to steadfastly maintain our
support for the diplomatic and economic isolation of Vietnam as a
reminder ... that attempts to manipulate international opinion will
not provide a real basis for improved relations with other
countries,'' Lambertson said.
   He testified as critics of U.S. Cambodian policy warned of a
``fourth Indochina War'' in the current dry season and attacked
U.S.-backed Prince Norodom Sihanouk's alliance with the communist
Khmer Rouge, blamed for more than 1 million Cambodian deaths during
the regime's 1975-78 rule over the country.
   Dith Pran, the Cambodian-born photographer whose escape from the
Khmer Rouge was portrayed in the motion picture ``The Killing
Fields,'' said the breakdown at Paris means that ``Cambodians are
being forced by their leaders to go to the killing fields again.''
   Pran said international pressure is needed to force the
Cambodian factions back to the negotiating table.
   At Paris, the Soviets were ``frankly, quite passive'' about
pressing for compromise on the part of their ally, Vietnam, and
Prime Minister Hun Sen's Vietnam-backed Cambodian government,
Lambertson said.
   But he said the United States is encouraged by subsequent
``useful discussions about Cambodia'' between Secretary of State
James A. Baker III and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
at their recent meetings in Wyoming and at the United Nations.
   The United States blames collapse of the Paris conference on the
refusal of Vietnam and Hun Sen to agree to share power with
Sihanouk in an interim Cambodian government.
   `We will continue to work on resolving the Cambodian conflict
with the Soviets in the context of the United Nations, the
continuing Paris conference process and on a bilateral basis,''
Lambertson said. ``We hope these discussions will result in a more
constructive Soviet role in this process.''
   He said the two superpowers have agreed on the need for a
political settlement ``and a continuation of the negotiating
process ... on the importance of averting both increased bloodshed
and the return of the Pol Pot (Khmer Rouge) regime to power, and
declared our readiness to announce, together with other states, a
moratorium on military assistance to all Cambodian factions as part
of a comprehensive settlement.''
   Lambertson said Vietnam appeared to have met its pledge to
withdraw its military forces from Cambodia late last month, ending
an 11-year occupation. While there was no evidence to back reports
of ``massive'' numbers remaining, the withdrawal should be verified
as part of an overall political settlement, he said.
   ``U.S. government assistance to the non-communist resistance has
been and continues to be non-lethal,'' Lambertson said, an apparent
reference to recent reports from the area about weapons assistance.
In the days ahead, he said, ``it is critical to maintain support
for Prince Sihanouk'' and the other non-communist Cambodians, he
said.
   But Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., chairman of the East Asian and
Pacific Affairs subcommittee, said the United States had pursued a
``morally bankrupt'' policy of backing Sihanouk's insistence on
including the Khmer Rouge in an interim Cambodian government, ``not
because we supported the Khmer Rouge, but because we supported
Prince Sihanouk.''
</TEXT>
