<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Salvador     10-02 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Salvador,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvador's President Asks Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alfredo Cristiani of El Salvador
on Monday proposed a cease-fire with leftist rebels who have fought
for 10 years to overthrow his country's government.
   He told the 44th General Assembly he will formally propose the
cease-fire at a meeting with the rebel Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front in San Jose, Costa Rica, on Oct. 16-17, ``because
the suffering must be brought to an end once and for all.''
   Cristiani invited all political factions in El Salvador to join
the current government. He said his administration would discuss
guarantees of security for the FMLN.
   After his speech, he told a news conference the rebels' interest
in political negotiations is partly due to Moscow's reluctance to
continued funding of guerrilla movements worldwide.
   About 70,000 people have died in the civil war.
   Cristiani's rightist ARENA party took office June 1 after
defeating the incumbent, centrist Christian Democrats in elections.
   The U.S.-backed government and the rebels held a first round of
preliminary peace talks in Mexico City in September. They decided
then to hold more meetings to seek a negotiated settlement of the
war.
   The rebels announced on Sept. 22 that they would not extend an
11-day truce that expired that day because the guerrillas felt the
government was not responding positively and was increasing
repression.
   The rebels last week launched a nationwide offensive that killed
or wounded 78 people.
</TEXT>
