<FIRST>u a AM-EastStLouisTeachers     10-02 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East St Louis Teachers,0274</SECOND>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,200 teachers and other
school workers went on strike Monday, canceling classes for 15,000
students in the state's fourth-largest district.
   The employees, represented by the East St. Louis Federation of
Teachers, walked out after rejecting the school board's proposal
for binding arbitration to settle disputes over wage increases and
insurance payments. A federal mediator had been trying to help the
sides reach an agreement.
   Negotiations resumed Monday afternoon. Thirty-three schools were
closed.
   The school board has offered employees a 2 percent pay raise for
the next year, but teachers would have to pay from $22 to $34 per
month for health insurance coverage for dependents. The district
currently pays for dependents' health insurance.
   The teachers' union is asking for a 5 percent pay raise with the
school district continuing to pay all health insurance bills .
   ``The district made every reasonable effort to avoid this
interruption of the educational process,'' school officials said in
a statement. There are ``certain undeniable economic facts which
some in the teaching ranks are apparently unwilling to accept.''
   The school district is trying to lower its $12.5 million debt.
   Union president Terry Turley said his members, who have been
working without a contract since the school year began, are
sensitive to the district's financial distress.
   ``As a matter of fact, last year we agreed to work with a wage
freeze with the promise that this year our concerns would be
addressed in some way,'' Turley said. ``As we began the strike
today, many of those concerns have not been addressed.''
</TEXT>
