<FIRST>u a AM-AgentIndicted     10-02 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Indicted,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agent, Businesswoman Plead Innocent in Conspiracy, Money-Laundering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal drug agent, his wife and the
owner of a construction company pleaded innocent Monday in an
indictment that alleges thousands of dollars were funneled into
real estate and coin collections.
   Drug Enforcement Administration agent Dennis Harker, his wife,
Mary Ann Harker, and Susan K. Terry, who owns SKT Construction, all
entered the pleas before U.S. Magistrate Celeste Bremer. Bremer set
a Dec. 4 trial.
   The charges against the three include tax violations, conspiracy
and structuring bank deposits to avoid a $10,000 limit over which
banks are required to report cash deposits.
   An indictment handed up by a grand jury last month details real
estate and bank transactions and charges the Harkers had hundreds
of thousands of dollars in transactions during years they reported
only a fraction of that income.
   In all, there are 11 counts in the indictment, with Harker
charged in eight of the counts, Ms. Terry in six and Mrs. Harker in
four.
   The indictment alleges that between 1986 and 1988 Harker and his
wife ``spent, invested and profited by cash transactions exceeding
$1 million.''
   The indictment did not elaborate further on the charges and did
not mention drugs.
   Harker is a DEA agent in Miami, but he earlier lived in West Des
Moines. Ms. Terry and the Harkers describe themselves as friends
since high school. Mrs. Terry also has been identified as a
business partner of Roxanne Conlin, a former U.S. Attorney and
Democratic candidate for governor.
   The indictment says Ms. Terry and Harker set up a company which
funneled cash to real estate investments and rare coin transactions.
   All three were free pending the trial. As part of the bail
requirements, all three must turn in their passports. Harker will
be forced to get rid of his extensive gun collection despite his
lawyer's arguments being a DEA agent means Harker lives under
serious threats.
   Harker could face up to 40 years in prison and $2 million in
fines if convicted on all the charges. The Harkers also could owe
taxes and penalties.
   Mrs. Harker, 40, faces up to 20 years in prison and $1 million
in fines if convicted. Ms. Terry, 38, faces up to 30 years in jail
and fines of up to $1.5 million.
</TEXT>
