<FIRST>u i AM-WorldChess 1stLd-Writethru a0640 10-02 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Chess, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0640,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Karpov Draws with Yusupov in Battle To Challenge World Chess Champion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with chess results, Kasparov earns
record rating. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former world champion Anatoly Karpov drew with
fellow Soviet Artur Yusupov in their first game Monday in a battle
among four top chess grandmasters to decide the challenger to
reigning champion Garri Kasparov.
   Jan Timman of the Netherlands and British grandmaster Jon
Speelman adjourned on the 60th move in the other game in the World
Championship Candidates' semifinal at Sadler's Wells ballet theater
in London.
   Timman was a pawn ahead in an endgame but most experts predicted
a draw when play resumes.
   Kasparov, in the 13th annual Interpolis chess tournament in
Tilburg, Holland, on Monday earned the highest rating record in the
history of the game, shattering U.S. player Bobby Fischer's 1972
record.
   The Soviet champion, by defeating Norway's Simen Agdestein in
the final round, won 12 points out of 14 matches, the best
tournament record ever. A win scores one point, and a draw half a
point.
   This entitled 26-year-old Kasparov to a total of 2,795 points on
the international ranking list of the World Chess Federation, known
by the French initials FIDE.
   Fischer's 1972 record was 2,785 points.
   Although the next rating list will not be officially published
before Jan. 1, Kasparov, who plans no further tournament
appearances this year, seems certain of his record.
   The second round in the semifinals in London will be played
Tuesday.
   The two winners of the semifinals contest will meet in the
Candidates' final scheduled for March in London.
   The winner will challenge Kasparov for his world title in a
24-game contest in October 1990.
   Playing with the disadvantage of the black pieces, Karpov
quickly neutralized Yusupov's opening advantage and exchanged both
pairs of rooks to reach an endgame where neither side could make
meaningful progress.
   After further exchanges, Yusupov forced a draw on the 44th move.
   Timman, playing white, gained an early opening initiative.
Speelman mistakes on the 17th and 21st moves let Timman reach an
endgame with an extra pawn and superior placed pieces.
   ``It's just one of those days when you miss everything,'' said
British grandmaster Nigel Short, the third ranked player in the
world, of Speelman's early play.
   But having gained a winning position, Timman failed to find
several promising continuations and Speelman put up the toughest of
defenses.
   In the adjourned position, each side has a rook. Timman has
three pawns and Speelman two.
   ``It looks like a draw now,'' said Short after Timman sealed his
61st move. ``Timman missed a lot of chances.''
   Karpov, 38, is heavily favored to knock out the 29-year-old
Yusupov. The outcome of the Timman-Speelman contest remains, in the
words of British Grandmaster Daniel King, ``completely unclear.''
   Karpov, ranked second in the world, held the world title for 10
years before losing to Kasparov in November 1985. Karpov is famous
for his so-called creeping style which analysts say squeezes the
play out of his opponent's position like a boa constrictor squeezes
the life from its prey. He has never lost to Yusupov.
   Yusupov, the world's 14th ranked player, rose to prominence in
1977 when he won the world under-20 championship at age 17.
   He will be hoping for a repeat of Karpov's astonishing collapse
at a June tournament in Rotterdam in the Netherlands. Over a
dramatic final three rounds, Karpov lost every game for the first
time in his long career.
   The winner of that tournament was Timman, a 37-year-old who is
ranked eighth in the world. By virtue of his formidable
performances, Timman was for many years the top Western grandmaster
and in 1987 a magnificent run of victories put him within striking
distance of Karpov.
   Speelman, who celebrated his 33rd birthday Monday, is ranked
13th in the world. He has a solid and tricky playing style,
punctuated with flashes of brilliance.
   Speelman, in the six-game quarter final, defeated Short by
3.5-1.5.
   Speelman said of the semifinals in his column in London's
newspaper The Sunday Correspondent: ``Before Karpov's collapse at
the end of Rotterdam I would have rated him the overwhelming
favorite against Artur Yusupov. Now I put him at about 70-30. I
rate Jan Timman favorite by about 55-45, but will strive mightily
to upset these odds.''
   The winner of each contest will receive $77,000, the loser
$46,000.
   If the matches are tied 4-4 after eight games, two more games
will be played. If it is still tied, the rules call for sudden
death games.
   The International Chess Federation has scheduled the 1990 title
final for Lyon, France, starting Oct. 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
