<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--TropicalDepression     10-02 0129</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Tropical Depression,0131</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tropical Depression Thirteen Forming in Atlantic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Atlantic hurricane season's thirteenth tropical
depression formed Monday evening, packing top winds of 35 mph and
showing signs of growing strength, the National Weather Service
said.
   Satellite pictures taken at 10:30 p.m. EDT Monday showed the
strong depression near latitude 14.8 north and longitude 48.6 west,
about 830 miles east of the Windward Islands.
   Forecasters said the depression would continue moving west
northwest at 12 mph and could carry tropical storm-force winds of
39 mph by Tuesday.
   Once a storm's maximum sustained winds reach 74 mph, it becomes
a hurricane. Hurricane Hugo was the eighth named storm and Iris was
the ninth of the Atlantic hurricane season, which runs from June 1
to Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
