<DOCNO> AP891002-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NoriegaCo-defendant     10-02 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noriega Co-defendant,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dedendant in Noriega Drug Indictment in Custody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian named as the co-conspirator with
Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega in a 1988 cocaine
trafficking indictment was ordered held without bond Monday by a
federal judge.
   Ramon Saldarriaga, 45, who was arrested Saturday south of Miami,
is only the second defendant of 16 named in the indictment to
appear in court.
   Saldarriaga is charged with conspiracy and two other counts in
the 12-count, 30-page indictment returned by a federal grand jury
in Miami on Feb. 4, 1988.
   The indictment accuses Saldarriaga of conspiracy to import
cocaine and aiding and abetting in cocaine trafficking linked to
the Medellin drug cartel. If convicted on all counts, he faces a
maximum prison sentence of 40 years.
   Saldarriaga's attorney, Steven Kreisberg, said his client has
lived in Florida since the early 1980s.
   Saldarriaga did not enter a plea, and Turnoff scheduled
arraignment for Oct. 13.
   Authorities at the hearing before U.S. District Court Judge
William Turnoff said Saldarriaga was caught in a routine traffic
case, but Saldarriaga's wife told The Associated Press that ``there
were at least seven police cars and there was a helicopter
overhead.''
   Bryan Davidow, the only U.S. citizen named in the Noriega
indictment, surrendered a few days after the indictment was issued
and has been released on bail. No date has been set for Davidow's
trial before U.S. District Court Judge William Hoveler.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
