<FIRST>r a AM-Exxon-President'sSpeech     10-02 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon-President's Speech,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon President Says `Chance' Was Oil Spill Factor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSEANNE PAGANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Exxon said Monday the
11 million-gallon Valdez oil spill has given him renewed respect
for ``what chance can do when it zeroes in on a target.''
   ``Valdez has made us appeciate all over again that plan as we
will, take care as best we can, we are all subject to chance,''
William D. Stevens told the state Chamber of Commerce. ``Especially
are we subject to human error.''
   Stevens, in only his third public appearance since the nation's
worst oil spill on March 24, said the oil giant was not trying to
avoid responsibility for the wreck of the Exxon Valdez.
   Instead, he said, ``a recognition that chance often has a say in
human affairs does allow a more dispassionate view of what
happened.''
   A breath analysis of former tanker Capt. Joseph Hazelwood taken
nine hours after the accident revealed his blood-alcohol level was
.06. The Coast Guard limit is .04. Investigators also are
questioning why a third mate was at the helm as the tanker was
navigated through glacial ice floes while Hazelwood apparently was
in his quarters.
   Stevens, whose speech was interrupted three times by hecklers,
said the oil spill had hurt his professional pride, but he said he
was satisfied with Exxon's billion-dollar cleanup was having
results.
   He said summerlong efforts to treat tarred Alaska beaches had
produced ``very remarkable progress.''
   ``Should we let chance events which could happen prevent us from
taking risk?'' he asked.
   Without accepting risk, he said, there could have been no
oilfields at Prudhoe Bay and no trans-Alaska Pipeline. Without
them, he said, Alaskans would have been denied a share in oil
development wealth.
   Stevens said managing risk was a related Valdez lesson. If great
undertakings are forfeited or delayed because of the risk of
accident, Stevens said, ``the country and all of us will be the
poorer.''
   ``We all have some stake in Alaska oil,'' he said, noting that
the state's oil meets 25 percent of U.S. demand. Stevens said
``soaring imports, unrest in the Mideast and few viable oil and gas
alternatives'' all remind him of conditions from the mid-1970s that
led to U.S. gasoline shortages.
   Development will continue to focus on Alaska, Stevens said,
since analysts have predicted as much as a third of the nation's
undiscovered oil is here.
   Stevens also said he was satisfied that Exxon policies regarding
tanker captain training and alcohol use on the job are adequate. He
said the oil spill was like ``a bad dream.'' He said it had
prompted a review of company policy, which Stevens said was
determined to be sound.
   ``I don't mean that to sound as if we are self-satisfied,''
Stevens told a crowd of about 600. ``Clearly, procedures weren't
followed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0242 </DOCNO>
