<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Angola 1stLd-Writethru a0733 10-02 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0733,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angola Indicates U.S. Support for UNITA Could Halt Cuban Pullout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 4-5 `However, U.S...' with 5 grafs CORRECTING that
Crocker is former assistant of state for African affairs and inserting
additional quotes from him. Pickup 6th graf `In an interview....' Adds
2 grafs with cease-fire and U.N. report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola's foreign minister indicated Monday
that if the United States continues aiding Jonas Savimbi's UNITA
rebels, the withdrawal of Cuban troops from his country might be
halted.
   Pedro de Castro van Dunem claimed U.S. officials repeatedly told
Angola that Washington would extend diplomatic recognition to
Angola and end aid to the rebels if Angola agreed to the Cuban
troop withdrawal.
   The United States and South Africa have linked the removal of an
estimated 50,000 Cuban soldiers in Angola by mid-1991 to South
Africa's agreement to cooperate with a U.N. plan to grant
independence to Namibia by April 1990.
   Chester Crocker, former U.S. assistant secretary of state for
African affairs, said in a telephone interview Monday the United
States did not promise to end aid to UNITA or to give diplomatic
recognition to Angola.
   He mediated the accords last year between South Africa, Angola
and Cuba on Namibia and the Cuban withdrawal.
   ``In 1988, we did not make any commitment, in principle or
otherwise, as the United States, to end aid to UNITA,'' Crocker
said. ``South Africa did,'' he said.
   Crocker said in December that Washington would not end its
support for UNITA while Angola received military aid from the
Soviet Union.
   In an interview at U.N. headquarters, van Dunem was asked if the
U.S. aid to UNITA might mean the Cuban troops would remain in
Angola. He said, ``We have not discussed this question, but it can
be a question.''
   In August, when six Cuban soldiers were killed in a rebel
ambush, Cuban President Fidel Castro said further attacks ``can
unfavorably influence compliance with the timetable for the Cuban
troops' withdrawal from the People's Republic of Angola.''
   Both Savimbi and Angolan officials are taking their case to
Washington.
   Van Dunem said he has requested a meeting with Secretary of
State James A. Baker III.
   Savimbi is in Washington seeking continued aid to the rebels'
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola _ UNITA.
   UNITA has been battling Angola's Marxist government since 1975
when the country gained its independence from Portugal and the
Soviet-backed Popular Liberation Movement of Angola won a brief
civil war.
   Cuba sent troops to Angola to help the government battle the
rebels.
   A change in the scheduled withdrawal of the Cubans could
jeopardize the planned independence for South African-ruled
Namibia, also known as South-West Africa.
   UNITA and Angola signed a peace accord June 22 and declared a
cease-fire effective two days later, but it broke down within weeks
amid charges of violations.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said recently
that U.N. military observers confirmed 15,927 Cuban personnel left
Angola by Aug. 1 and the rate of departure was ``fully consistent''
with a timetable calling for complete withdrawal by mid-1991.
</TEXT>
