<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0772 10-02 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0772,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS age in Tate obit to 77 sted 78.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Stanley Joseloff</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stanley S. Joseloff, a former radio
executive, advertising man, entrepreneur and songwriter whose song
``Dear Arabella'' was a World War II hit, died Sunday after a brief
illnes. He was 82.
   During World War II, Joseloff was chief of programs for the
Pacific Theater for the Office of War Information. His ``Dear
Arabella'' was recorded by the Glenn Miller orchestra.
   He was legal counsel to Broadway producers Lee and J.J. Shubert
and produced several radio shows, including ``The Eddie Cantor NBC
Radio Hour'' and ``The Life of Riley.''
   Joseloff, a member of the American Society of Composers, Authors
and Publishers, was also radio commercial writer and later program
and talent director for the Young and Rubicam advertising agency
and head of the radio department at the Brow advertising agency.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Huynh Tan Phat</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Huynh Tan Phat, a leading member of the
Viet Cong and later vice president of Vietnam's State Council, died
Saturday at age 76.
   A graduate in architecture from Hanoi University, Phat joined
the anti-French underground and was imprisoned by the colonial
government.
   Phat emerged as the chief theoretician of the National
Liberation Front, the key southern Communist-led movement whose
members were often called Viet Cong.
   After the Communist victory in Vietnam in 1975, Phat was one of
the few members of the Viet Cong to hold a leadership position in a
Hanoi government and Communist Party dominated by northern
Vietnamese.
   He served as vice chairman of the Council of State and chairman
of the Presidium of the Vietnam Fatherland Front, one of a number
of mass organizations under party and government control.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Virgil Thomson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Composer and music critic Virgil Thomson, who
wrote the only film score to win a Pulitzer Prize, died Saturday.
He was 92.
   Thomson had a long career as a composer of operas, ballets,
orchestral and choral works, as well as film scores and incidental
music for plays by authors from Shakespeare to Truman Capote.
   His 1949 Pulitzer came for the music for ``Louisiana Story,'' a
documentary film.
   In 1988, Thomson was one of 12 recipients of the National Medal
of Arts, an award created by Congress four years earlier at the
suggestion of then-President Reagan.
   Thomson was music critic for the New York Herald Tribune until
1954. His newspaper pieces, described as stylish, bright and
deliberately provocative, were collected into four anthologies.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Manuel Clouthier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manuel J. Clouthier, a leading conservative
politician and former presidential candidate, died Sunday in an
auto accident. He was 55.
   Clouthier, an agricultural engineer by profession, headed
leading business organizations for more than two decades.
   He entered politics in 1982 and ran for Sinaloa governor in 1986
but lost to the governing party candidate in balloting allegedly
marred by fraud.
   Clouthier finished third in Mexico's 1988 presidential election,
won by Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Willis Tate</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willis M. Tate, 77, who served as president of
Southern Methodist University for nearly 20 years, died Sunday of
an apparent heart attack.
   Tate served as the university's president from 1954 to 1971 and
again from July 1974 to October 1975. He retired as chancellor in
1976 and since then had served as president emeritus of SMU.
   His defense of academic freedom and campus expression of ideas
became a hallmark of his administration.
   In implementing the SMU Master Plan of 1963, Tate presided over
the establishment of SMU's School of the Arts and the launching of
doctorate programs on the campus.
</TEXT>
