<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv09   10-02 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv09,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Oct. 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, October 9, the 282nd day of 1989. There are 83
days left in the year. This is the Columbus Day holiday, as well as
Thanksgiving Day in Canada. This is also the Jewish Day of
Atonement, Yom Kippur.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Seventy years ago, on October 9, 1919, the Cincinnati Reds won
the World Series, five games to three in a best-of-nine contest, by
defeating the Chicago White Sox 10-5 at Comiskey Park. However, the
victory turned hollow amid charges that eight members of the White
Sox had accepted bribes from gamblers to throw the series in what
became known as ``The Black Sox Scandal.''
   On this date:
   In 1635, religious dissident Roger Williams was banished from
the Massachusetts Bay Colony.
   In 1701, the Collegiate School of Connecticut _ later Yale
University _ was chartered in New Haven.
   In 1776, a group of Spanish missionaries settled in present-day
San Francisco.
   In 1855, Joshua C. Stoddard of Worcester, Mass., received a
patent for the first calliope.
   In 1888, the public was first admitted to the Washington
Monument.
   In 1930, Laura Ingalls became the first woman to fly across the
United States as she completed a nine-stop journey from Roosevelt
Field, N.Y., to Glendale, Calif.
   In 1936, the first generator at Boulder (later Hoover) Dam began
transmitting electricity to Los Angeles.
   In 1958, Pope Pius XII died, nineteen years after he was
elevated to the papacy.
   In 1962, Uganda won autonomy from British rule.
   In 1967, Latin American guerrilla leader Che Guevara was
executed after being captured leading a guerrilla band in Bolivia.
   In 1975, Soviet scientist Andrei Sakharov won the Nobel Peace
Prize.
   In 1983, President Reagan's controversial Interior Secretary,
James G. Watt, resigned under fire.
   In 1983, a bomb explosion in Rangoon, Burma, blamed on North
Korean agents killed 17 visiting South Koreans, including four
cabinet ministers.
   In 1986, the Senate convicted U.S. District Judge Harry E.
Claiborne of ``high crimes and misdemeanors,'' making him the fifth
federal official to be removed from office through impeachment.
   Ten years ago: President Carter told a news conference he would
announce his plans for the 1980 presidential campaign in December,
but left little doubt he intended to run for re-election.
   Five years ago: One day after Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon
Duarte unexpectedly offered to hold peace talks with leftist
rebels, a coalition of guerrillas accepted the proposal.
   One year ago: Yugoslavian President Raif Dizdarevic warned
citizens in a national radio and television address that continued
nationalist and economic unrest could lead to a state of emergency.
   Today's Birthdays: Senator Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., is 49.
Singer Jackson Browne is 40. Football player Mike Singletary is 31.
   Thought for Today: ``The world is divided into people who think
they are right.'' _ Anonymous.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Use Monday, October 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
