<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1437EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Newfoundland'sWhales Adv15-2Takes   10-02 1029</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Newfoundland's Whales, Adv 15-2 Takes,1054</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w photos,
1 graphic. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Slowly, the largest animals ever to roam the
planet are returning to the craggy coves and lofty fiords of
Newfoundland, beckoning the curious from across America and Europe,
as well as scientists who want to study them. While the seasonal
arrivals of the whales are met with some trepidation by fishermen,
Newfoundlanders are learning that a live whale can be just as
valuable as a dead one.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRINITY, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring comes late and winter comes
early to these climes, governing the coming and going of exotic
seabirds, moose, caribou and seals. But the creatures that linger
most on the mind are the whales.
   In fact, a group of scientists will gather in Newfoundland in
February under the auspices of Memorial University in St. Johns to
tally the number of humpback whales left in the world by comparing
thousands of photographs taken over the years of humpback tails,
which have telltale fluke patterns.
   Situated off the food-rich Grand Banks, where codfish is king,
the seas around Newfoundland provide enough food, deep water and
isolation to satisfy the pickiest leviathan.
   ``This is the biggest restaurant in the world's oceans. It's got
a varied menu, everything you want and all you want, and it's
cheap,'' says whale researcher Peter Beamish, who conducts
whale-watching expeditions out of Trinity.
   The waters off Newfoundland have the highest concentration of
whales in the world, says Beamish, who holds a doctorate in marine
bioacoustics from the University of British Columbia and a master's
degree from Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Up to 25 species
of cetaceans _ whales, dolphins and porpoises _ migrate every
summer to the northwest Atlantic to feed.
   ``If a place like Alaska is a fish-and-chips joint that seats 25
people, then this is the entire city of Paris, which seats 5
million people all eating gourmet, 15-course meals,'' Beamish says.
   But the waters around Newfoundland have not always been
hospitable to whales, whose numbers have been decimated by 500
years of relentless pursuit and slaughter by whalers from several
continents.
   Since the time of Columbus, the coastlines of Newfoundland and
Labrador were littered with makeshift whale factories, which were
moved from one site to another after whales in an area were
depleted.
   Whales were deemed expendable. The rendering of their blubber
provided light for the streets of Europe and food for Asia.
Observations of their habits were limited to those who hunted them,
almost to extinction.
   Since the turn of the century, more than 2 million whales have
been reported killed for food, oil, cosmetics and other products.
   But after the 1960s, the decade of increasing environmental
awareness, and the 1970s, the decade of discovery about the
intelligence and gentleness of whales, the 1980s have been a decade
in which most nations banned whaling _ at least temporarily.
   While tourists spend thousands of dollars to travel here to view
whales, the fishermen who spend the most time in the company of the
gentle giants view them more like city pigeons than a national
treasure.
   ``My stepfather is a fisherman and I can't go home and speak of
what a great day I had,'' says Collette Churchill, 21, of Port
Rexton, Beamish's assistant on the whale-watching expeditions. ``To
him, the whales are a nuisance. They get in their traps and cost
them a lot of money.''
   Whales often wreak havoc with expensive fishing nets, and
toothed whales compete for the capelin, squid and cod that
contribute to Newfoundland's $700 million fishing industry.
   ``For fishermen, whales are marine rats. It's a pest, an
endangered pest, because it really does cost them money,'' says
John Lien, professor of ocean studies at Memorial University.
   The provincial government and whale researchers such as Beamish
and Lien have been working diligently over the past decade to
create goodwill between whales and the fishermen.
   Educational programs about whales have been presented in just
about every village and outport _ tiny settlements reachable only
by boat. And when a whale gets trapped in a net, a toll-free hot
line can put a fisherman in contact with a rescue team that will
try to free the animal and save the net.
   ``In Newfoundland as a whole, attitudes have changed,'' says
Lien. ``We've printed a half million whale posters, and I claim
they have replaced Sears catalogs in the outhouses. Now 90 percent
of the fishermen can identify a humpback, for instance. Before, it
was a very low figure.''
   Before hot lines and whale rescues, one in two whales trapped in
fishing nets would die, Lien says. This year, only three of 65
humpbacks that blundered into nets died.
   ``When I first came here, live whales cost Newfoundland
fishermen over $1 million a year from lost or damaged nets and
all,'' Beamish says. ``And now tourism probably brings in $1
million a year to the island.
   ``What I did and what I'm proud of is that I came to
Newfoundland hoping to make live whales more valuable to
Newfoundlanders than dead whales. And we did that.''
   A new generation of Newfoundlanders also is emerging, one much
more atuned to the special creatures in their midst.
   ``We surveyed 7,000 kids in Newfoundland and found that seal
pups and whales were their favorite animals. They were right up
there with puppies and kittens,'' says Lien. ``That's probably the
most important thing an animal can do for its survival _ get humans
attached to it.''
   There are two kinds of whales, toothed whales like the dolphin,
sperm and killer whales, and baleen whales like the blue, humpback
and right whales, which feed on krill, tiny shrimp-like plankton,
gulped by the thousands while the water is expelled through a mesh
of whalebone called baleen.
   Some whales, like the rare blue whale, the largest animal ever
to have lived, can be seen in winter feeding near the edge of ice
floes along the island's undulating, 5,500-mile-long coastline.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1438EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Newfoundland'sWhales Adv15-1stAdd   10-02 1035</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Newfoundland's Whales, Adv 15-1st Add,1058</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRINITY, Newfoundland: 5,500-mile-long coastline.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   But most of Newfoundland's whales, notably humpbacks, minkes and
fins, breed and calve in warm southern waters during the winter and
migrate north in summer to feed on the millions of tiny smelt-like
capelin that spawn on Newfoundland beaches.
   ``North to feed, south to breed,'' says Beamish.
   With little exaggeration, that's just about all that's known
about these warm-blooded, air-breathing mammals. What they do at
night, how deep they dive, where they go in the winter, how they
communicate, how some species feed, why certain whales beach
themselves, how long they live, how often they give birth, even
whether some species still exist, are all mysteries.
   ``Whales are really mysterious animals because they seem to
disappear. They'll go down and you don't see them ever again,''
says Beamish, who spent 10 years at the Bedford Institute of
Oceanography.
   ``We know a fraction about whales of what we do about other
animals on Earth because we can't study them at nighttime, we can't
study them when they're below the surface, we can't study them in
captivity and we can't study them in the winter very well.''
   Nevertheless centuries of hunting whales have yielded some of
their secrets. The sperm whale for instance feeds mostly on squid,
preferably the giant squid and octopus. That requires that it dive
to great depths, although like all whales it is an air breather.
   One sperm whale, a relative youngster at 45 feet long, was found
at a depth of 3,240 feet by the cable repair ship All America in
1932. It drowned apparently in mortal combat with the cable it
encountered while hunting squid. Almost 200 feet of cable was
twisted around its jaws and body.
   While most whales have a gentle reputation, the killer whales
are the most formidable. Thirty feet long and capable of swimming
at about 30 mph, they are unmatched in lethal potential. They are
voracious, some caught with the remains of more than 20 porpoises
and seals in their bellies.
   But no whale challenges the imagination as much as the great
blue, protected now but once hunted almost to extinction. Some 100
feet long and 150 tons, it is the largest creature on Earth, and
may have begun its evolutional history on dry land. There are
vestigial hipbones in the rear third of its body indicating that it
may have prowled the primordial land.
   It was a boon to the whalers. One blue whale could yield 45 tons
of meat and 40 tons of blubber. Its skeleton alone weighed 27 tons
and its internal organs 18 more.
   Beamish, who moved to Newfoundland from Nova Scotia 10 years ago
to study whales more closely, says he sometimes gets frustrated at
the very thing that makes them so mysterious _ their elusiveness.
   ``Sometimes I feel like switching to an easier animal,'' he says
wryly. ``I do this as well as anybody in the world, so I'm on the
edge of knowledge. But you'd like to work on an animal you can work
with more than just a few hours a day.''
   Nevertheless, there is something about whales that makes them
special in the marine kingdom and attractive to scientists.
   ``They are highly intelligent, and their brains are extremely
unusual and as complex as ours,'' says Jennifer Bates of the Whale
Center in Oakland, Calif. ``Not only that, they arrived at their
brain size at least 2 million years before we attained ours.''
   ``They are at the top of the evolutionary ladder among ocean
animals and man is at the top among land animals,'' Beamish says.
``So even though you get less data, the data might be more
meaningful.''
   The body of knowledge about whales, for the most part, is a
recent acquistion _ begun only in the latter half of this century.
   The reason may be found in a little clapboard museum in historic
Trinity dedicated to the town's fishing and whaling past. Curator
Calvert Goldsworthy, a former fish-plant worker, fingers the long,
sinewy fibers of a humpback's baleen.
   Looking out the window at Trinity Bay, a favorite haunt of
whales, the slight man of 63 years remembers when fish plants
smelling of salt cod covered the rocky coast and recalls stories of
the carcasses of dead whales hauled ashore for rendering a century
before.
   In many parts of the globe, the animals are still scarce. Some
species, like the bowhead and right whale (so called by the whalers
because it would float when killed, therefore ``right'') are highly
endangered, while others, like Longman's beaked and the
melon-headed whale, have not been seen for decades.
   Slowly, the largest animals ever to roam the planet have
returned to the craggy coves and lofty fiords of this verdant
island. And their arrival in the spring is met with both eagerness
and trepidation by the local inhabitants.
   ``It means spring is here, just like when my animals have young,
when the first lamb is born,'' says Goldsworthy. ``The first whale
is like the first robin. The ponds start to melt and you take your
rod and go out for a meal of trout.''
   ``You get this burst of energy,'' says Collette Churchill.
``Research doesn't go so well on the first day because I can't sit
down. I still feel like that every morning with our first humpback
sighting.''
   Sitting at a table in the small restaurant of Beamish's Village
Inn, Churchill relaxes before the start of another day of
note-taking on rough seas. After several days of rain and fog _ an
obvious deterrent to whale watching _ the clouds part and the sun
warms the small, clapboard houses built haphazardly along the steep
slopes.
   ``You can't describe the feeling that goes over you when you see
a whale for the first time or a humpback breach,'' Churchill says,
her face beaming. ``It doesn't matter who you are, where you're
from. I don't see how you can't feel that way, such a big animal,
so friendly. It's like they have this need to communicate.
   ``They want to and are trying, it's just that no one understands
them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1439EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--WhaleWatchers Adv15   10-02 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Whale Watchers, Adv 15,0840</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Newfoundland's Whales    </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRINITY, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like a roller coaster stuck on go,
the 60-mph Zodiac raft assaults mile after mile of 12-foot swells,
startling puffins into diving for safety, as tourists pursue an
elusive minke whale.
   ``Blow, 2 o'clock,'' yells a passenger, pointing into a
sun-washed horizon as the curved, black back of the minke appears
for a split-second breath of air.
   Minutes elapse before the whale watchers, all peering intently
into the vast expanse of ocean, spy the sickle-shaped dorsal fin
that appears as a minke spouts.
   ``Blow, 6 o'clock,'' yell two people at once as the Zodiac makes
a quick left turn and veers out toward open sea.
   After two days of rain and fog, the participants in a three-day
whale-watch expedition in Newfoundland are eager to see what they
paid thousands of dollars and traveled thousands of miles to see.
   Their patience is rewarded this sunny day in late summer.
Several minkes make appearances in coves at the base of high, rocky
cliffs, and the group of seven whale watchers establish brief
contact with a solitary humpback, an endangered whale known for its
melodious songs.
   ``I felt totally overwhelmed by it all,'' says Wendy Davidson,
35, an English native teaching in Norway. ``You really felt as if
the humpback was there with us. She came and rolled right beside
the boat as if to say, `Look, aren't I lovely?'''
   ``I think we were relieved, actually, that we had seen what we
came here to see,'' says Paul Collins, 33, a stage technician for
the Royal Shakespeare Theater in Stratford on Avon, England.
   Whale enthusiasts gravitate to this remote Canandian province at
the easternmost edge of North America because of the abundance and
variety of whales that migrate here every summer.
   What they find is sometimes more than they expected _ seals,
bald eagles, Arctic seabirds, and, inland, caribou, bear and moose.
   What they get in programs like those run by whale researcher
Peter Beamish in the historic village of Trinity is a chance to
participate in experiments in human-whale communication.
   ``Most people's expectations are just to see a whale, and as
soon as they walk in the door we tell them that we do a lot more
than that. We try to get them involved in a communication
experience, which is a lot more valuable,'' says Beamish, who has
operated his Ocean Contact program for 10 years.
   Beamish conducts three- and seven-day expeditions costing up to
$1,000. Air fare is not included.
   Participants are fed and housed at an old inn in Trinity, where
evenings consist of whale-related slide shows, movies and
discussions. Days are spent at sea looking for and, hopefully,
``talking'' to whales.
   The talking actually consists of electronic beeps sent through
the water several times at certain intervals. A ``conversation''
develops when a whale responds, either by spouting, breaching,
slapping his tail or lifting his head above water. Participants
help work the equipment and scan the horizon for the whale's
response.
   In his ``Whale Watcher's Handbook,'' author Erich Hoyt says,
``Sooner or later, the serious whale watcher finds himself in
Newfoundland.''
   But serious whale watchers also are finding there's more to this
ruggedly beautiful island than just whales.
   ``People come here to see whales. That's one of the things on
the list, but it's not the only thing,'' says Dan Collins, chief of
visitor activities at Terra Nova National Park near Trinity. ``They
are also interested in seeing icebergs and the wide-open spaces.''
   ``Newfoundland is kind of like the last outpost,'' says Terra
Nova superintendent John Fulton. ``The frontier ethic that existed
in the United States is still here. You still go out and cut your
wood, get your moose or caribou and your fish.''
   Greg Taylor, 40, an Englishman teaching in the Netherlands, said
the whales and the promise of pristine country are what attracted
him to Newfoundland and Beamish's program.
   ``When I asked the travel agent if she could get me a flight to
Newfoundland, she said: `Nobody ever goes there. Why do you want to
go there for?' I said, `Great, then that's where I want to be.'''
   New York City woodworker Cathy Zadoretzky, 39, says she felt
renewed by such close contact with animals that, to her, symbolize
``the things we are not'' in a land that is ``an idealization of
what I think of as peaceful, beautiful country.''
   ``Whales are superior beings who live in the ocean, and we are
supposedly the superior beings on land. They are a great force who
live peaceably under the sea, but we are a destructive force, and
we are beginning to realize that it might cost us.
   ``They're our salvation. If we can save them, we are starting to
save ourselves.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
