<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ShipyardDown Adv15-2Takes   10-02 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Shipyard Down, Adv 15-2 Takes,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w photos.)
   </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   It was once called the ``American Clyde,'' after
the Clyde River in Scotland, then a major shipbuilding center in
Europe. Now the Delaware River is losing the last of its once-proud
shipbuilding yards, partially because of a general slump in the
industry brought on by new government policies.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHESTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the unfinished hulls of two Navy ships
leave the yard of Pennsylvania Shipbuilding Co., the Delaware River
will be without a shipbuilding business for the first time in more
than 300 years.
   Since William West built the Amity in 1682, the year William
Penn came from England, companies putting together seagoing ships
have been a part of the Delaware River landscape. At one time or
another, there were 38 shipyards along the river and its
tributaries.
   It has been in decline here for decades, but spokesmen say a
national slump in shipbuilding, aggravated by new government
policies, really finished off a once-proud industry that was a
national leader.
   For example, John Fitch advertised steamboat trips along the
Delaware River 17 years before Robert Fulton ran his Clermont along
the Hudson. Some of the Civil War-era ironclad ``monitors'' were
built here.
   Delaware Valley shipyards built boats to defend the America's
Cup. In Wilmington, Del., the Pusey &amp; Jones shipyard built them for
trade on the Amazon River.
   In 1915, with war under way in Europe, American International
Shipbuilding Corp. built what was then the world's largest shipyard
_ 50 shipways employing 34,000 workers. It turned out 122 cargo
ships and troop transports in two years.
   The river was nicknamed the ``American Clyde,'' after the Clyde
in Scotland, then the center of European iron shipbuilding.
   The proud tradition continued down to 1960, when the huge
aircraft carrier Kitty Hawk was launched from the New York
Shipbuilding Corp. yard in Camden, N.J., right across the river
from the Philadelphia waterfront. That yard closed soon after and
is now being demolished.
   The Kitty Hawk is being modernized now in Philadelphia at the
U.S. Navy Yard, which does ship repair work but hasn't built a ship
from the keel up since 1971.
   The two ships the Navy ordered from Pennsylvania Shipbuilding
sit at the river's edge, one tied up in a slip and the other braced
in a dry dock and minus the bow, stern and deckhouse. A mortgage
agreement filed in the Delaware County Recorder of Deeds Office
gives the Navy title to four parcels of land owned by Penn Ship if
the company fails to pay for the costs of finding another company
to finish the work.
   Pennsylvania Shipbuilding was known as Sun Shipbuilding &amp;
Drydock when Sun Oil opened it in 1916 to guarantee a supply of
tankers. Over the years it built 674 oceangoing ships.
   Sun got out of the shipbuilding business in 1982 and sold the
yard to a Texas company that renamed it. It was later sold to three
Mobile, Ala., real estate developers.
   In May 1985, Penn Ship won a $222.4 million contract to build
two fleet oilers for the Navy, vessels that refuel combat ships at
sea.
   The Navy planned to buy 18 of the 677{-foot, T-AO-187 class
tankers eventually, and Penn Ship stood to gain a good share of
that business if it completed the contract successfully.
   It didn't. The Navy renegotiated the contract to $331.4 million,
but Penn Ship announced in February that it didn't have enough
money to finish the ships with the cost overrun factored in.
   Work stopped on the ships and Penn Ship laid off 1,200 workers.
Rumors have said the hulls, one 90 percent finished and the other
70 percent done, will be towed to either Tampa, Fla., or New
Orleans to be finished.
   William Gallagher, the yard's general manager, couldn't say what
would become of the unfinished ships.
   ``The contract has been terminated,'' he said. ``We are not
involved with where they will go. I have no idea when they will
leave.''
   What went wrong? Why couldn't the yard finish a couple of
tankers, basically like ships that were built here for years?
   ``There were a lot of circumstances contributing,'' Gallagher
said. ``We bid in a time frame when labor rates were low. There was
also an expectation of follow-up work. Our costs turned out to be
much higher than we expected, and there was no follow-up work to
spread them over.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1441EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ShipyardDown Adv15-1stAdd   10-02 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Shipyard Down, Adv 15-1st Add,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHESTER, Pa.: them over.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nationwide, Gallagher said, shipbuilding is in trouble.
   ``There's no business,'' he said. ``The only new construction in
this country for the past couple of years has been for the
government.''
   Why?
   ``Aging facilities, and other countries' yards are subsidized,''
he said. ``It's impossible to compete in the world market the way
we're having to compete.''
   The U.S. maritime administration once subsidized the
construction of new vessels, but those subsidies have been
terminated, Gallagher said.
   In Washington, John Stoker of the Shipbuilders Council of
America agreed in part.
   ``For purposes of discussion, it's fairly accurate,'' he said.
``You can just watch the downward trend.''
   In 1982, the council counted 110 shipbuilding companies in the
United States, employing 112,000 workers. This year it's down to 69
companies employing 72,000.
   ``We lost 41 shipyards and 41,000 people,'' Stoker said.
   Shipbuilding in the Seattle area has been devastated in recent
years, Stoker said. Other areas that were hit hard were south
Texas, Baltimore and the San Francisco area.
   The Reagan administration terminated shipbuilding subsidies,
Stoker said, arguing that the government shouldn't be interfering
in the private sector, propping up the industry.
   ``But that was looking at the world through naive and myopic
lenses,'' he said. ``It doesn't recognize that if we are not
subsidized and the rest of the world is, we are doomed.''
   What saved American shipbuilding through the '80s, Stoker said,
was rebuilding the Navy. With that almost complete, American
shipyards face tough times again.
   Rather than asking the government to return to subsidies, the
council wants the major shipbuilding nations _ South Korea, Japan,
West Germany and Norway _ to drop government intervention in the
business.
   The council filed a complaint in June with the Office of the
United States Trade Representative against the four. It agreed to
withhold the petition while the United States tried to negotiate an
agreement on shipbuilding subsidies.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills agreed to seek agreements
with U.S. trading partners both through the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development and through the Uruguay Round
negotiations of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   ``I have received assurances from representatives of all these
countries that they will negotiate seriously on this matter,'' she
said.
   Ms. Hills set a deadline of March 31, 1990, which Stoker called
``fairly aggressive.''
   ``But we can't really allow the process to drag on,'' Stoker
said. ``A number of our companies are potentially in trouble.''
   Stoker agreed it will not be easy to persuade other governments
to stop subsidizing shipbuilding.
   ``It depends on how you define a subsidy,'' he said. ``They tend
to think of a subsidy as a direct payment from the government to a
business. But when they make export credit available to a shipyard,
they don't think they're subsidizing it.''
   Gallagher is pessimistic.
   ``Those countries have decided they want to maintain a
shipbuilding industry,'' he said. ``In this country, we've
apparently made the decision not to have one.''
   Stoker is more optimistic. The nation still has areas where
employment is high in ship construction and repair _ the Gulf
Coast, San Diego and the area around Hampton Roads in Virginia.
Other big yards are in Connecticut, Rhode Island and Maine.
   U.S. trade negotiators have started talks with Japan and South
Korea, and Stoker said the major talks are expected in mid-October.
   ``We are hoping the U.S. negotiating position can be hammered
out later this month,'' he said. ``We frankly think some attitudes
about the shipbuilding industry in the nation have changed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
