<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1442EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--LastShipyard Adv15   10-02 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Last Shipyard, Adv 15,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Shipyard Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHESTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last working commercial shipyard in
Pennsylvania was started by an oil executive making sure his
company had enough tankers. It went out of business trying to
finish a pair of military fuel ships.
   Sun Oil Co. incorporated Sun Shipbuilding &amp; Drydock Co. in 1916,
a year after company President J. Howard Pew had taken a business
trip to Germany and been impressed with that country's naval
strength.
   Sun Ship's first vessel, the SS Chester Sun, slid down the ways
in October 1917. By the end of World War I the yard had built six
tankers plus three minesweepers for the Navy.
   Over the years Sun Ship emerged as one of the nation's largest
privately owned shipyards. Its Sun Doxford diesel engine eventually
made it the biggest American manufacturer of large marine diesel.
It also launched the first all-welded tanker, the SS White Flash,
in 1931.
   But its glory years were during World War II, when an average of
a ship a week rolled down its 28 ways. On one day, the yard
launched three ships.
   By the end of the war, Sun Ship had produced more than 250 ships
_ 40 percent of all U.S. tankers built. It converted, armed and
repaired 1,000 more. The yard employed 33,500 people.
   But the end of the war brought a sharp decline in ship
construction. The other yards on the Delaware River began closing
and by 1975 only Sun Ship was left. By the end of 1980, the parent
Sun Co. estimated it had lost more than $200 million keeping the
shipyard alive.
   Sun announced it was getting out of the shipbuilding business in
January 1981. A company official estimated the shipyard would be
sold for $30 million to $40 million.
   In February 1982 the yard and its assets were sold for a
reported $8 million to Levingston Industries Inc., a Texas company
that renamed the yard Pennsylvania Shipbuilding. Levingston sold
control two years later to three real estate developers from
Mobile, Ala.
   But shipbuilding hasn't been very successful for Penn Ship. In
May 1985, when the Navy awarded the contract for two 677{-foot
fleet oilers, it was hailed as a deal that would keep the yard
alive.
   Later, Penn Ship would argue that it had to submit an
unreasonably low bid to get the contract and the Navy renegotiated
the deal to $331.4 million. In February, Penn Ship said that wasn't
enough either, and it suspended work with an eye to hiring another
yard to finish the job.
   Finally the Navy decided to find a new contractor itself.
   William Gallagher, the yard's general manager, said Penn Ship
made its bid when labor was plentiful and rates were low but soon
had trouble finding qualified employees in a booming economy.
   How could a shipyard that built tankers for years lose a
contract to build a couple of Navy fuel vessels? Michael Shaffer,
business agent for Local 802 of the Boilermakers Union, says the
company made a mistake by hiring Japanese consultants to introduce
``modular'' construction techniques.
   In traditional shipbuilding, workers build the hull and install
mechanical and electrical equipment inside the cramped confines.
The new technique has workers completely build entire sections and
then weld or bolt them together.
   ``That's one thing we're bitter about,'' Shaffer said. ``We've
been building 50-ton units and lifting them into place for years.
The Japanese didn't show us anything we didn't know already. But
the company treated them like gods while they treated their own
employees like dirt.''
   Gallagher disagrees.
   ``The modular techniques helped,'' he said, insisting that the
shipyard's troubles would have been even worse without them.
Absenteeism wasn't especially a problem, Gallagher said, but hiring
skilled workers was.
   ``That's really true throughout the country,'' he said. ``The
shipbuilding industry used to have a lot of skilled people. Most
shipyards used to have apprentice programs, and they were major
employers. Those people have left and found work in other areas.
   ``These are people in the skilled trades _ electricians, sheet
metal workers, machinists and so on _ and they don't have any
trouble finding new jobs. If you have to build up again, you have
to start over.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
