<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1443EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--FrenchDrugs Adv15-2Takes   10-02 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--French Drugs, Adv 15-2 Takes,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 graphic.)
   </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lifesaving drugs are often available in France
long before they are on the market in the United States. The reason
is a difference in the bureaucracies of the two countries. While
some argue that the U.S. Food and Drug Administration should speed
up its drug approval process, others warn that it's risky to be
hasty.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1985, a desperately ill Rock Hudson was one of
many AIDS patients who fled to France for a drug they couldn't get
in the United States.
   The drug didn't work. But at the time it was the only hope, and
American doctors couldn't prescribe it.
   Last year, French doctors began prescribing the so-called
abortion pill to terminate pregnancies. American women may not get
it for years.
   These are two examples among many in which the French became the
first to receive the potential benefits of new drugs.
   It happens because the French drug approval system is simpler
and faster than that of the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
Advocates of the French system say it has elements that could be
adopted in the United States, cutting the time that Americans must
wait for new drugs.
   The issue has become increasingly important as the FDA faces
growing pressure to speed the approval of experimental cancer and
AIDS drugs that might help patients who would otherwise be unlikely
to survive.
   The FDA has, in fact, responded to that pressure by speeding the
approval of the AIDS drug AZT. And on Sept. 28, it announced that
it was making a newer AIDS drug, called DDI, widely available while
tests of its safety and effectiveness are still continuing.
   Defenders of the FDA argue the French system has certain
drawbacks that would make it unworkable in the United States.
   The French system is faster ``because it's very different,''
says Jerome Halperin, former deputy director of drugs at the FDA.
In the United States, the drug approval process is subject to
enormous oversight by Congress and consumer groups, says Halperin,
who is now with the U.S. Pharmacopeial Convention, a private
organization that sets standards for drug quality, purity and
strength.
   Some public interest groups are calling for a speed-up in drug
approval, Halperin notes, at the same time that others are arguing
that the agency takes unnecessary risks by sometimes being too
hasty.
   The classic example of a drug being approved too quickly is
thalidomide, which caused severe birth defects after it was
approved in Europe in the late 1950s and early 1960s. The drug was
never approved in the United States.
   Oversight from Congress and the public interest groups
inevitably puts pressure on reviewers and slows down the
drug-approval process, Halperin says. Similar government and public
oversight does not exist in France.
   ``There is hardly ever anybody from the AP or The New York Times
looking over their shoulders,'' says Dr. Michael Weintraub, a
clinical pharmacologist at the University of Rochester School of
Medicine in Rochester, N.Y., who spent the 1980-81 academic year in
France studying its pharmaceutical approval process. ``Our system
is much more political.''
   Most Americans see that public scrutiny as important, even
though it might slow new drug approvals, Halperin says.
   Nevertheless, he says, there are examples of drugs that get
approved here before they get approved in other countries,
including some AIDS drugs.
   ``I think the FDA has gone remarkably far in making experimental
AIDS drugs available with as little administrative encumbrance as
possible,'' Halperin says.
   The principal difference between the French and American systems
is that while the FDA relies on an in-house staff of drug
reviewers, the French rely on an outside committee of expert
volunteers, says Dr. Yves Juillet, director of scientific affairs
for the French National Pharmaceutical Industry Association.
   Some of the volunteers are drawn from the drug industry itself.
That works well in France, Juillet says, but the use of drug
company scientists to review drugs in the United States would
likely draw allegations of conflict of interest.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1444EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--FrenchDrugs Adv15-1stAdd   10-02 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--French Drugs, Adv 15-1st Add,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>PARIS: of interest.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The French expert committee meets every other Friday morning to
review pending new drug applications. Individual committee members
present written technical reviews of each application and then the
committee makes its decisions.
   In cases in which unusual speed is needed, or in which research
results are especially complicated, the health ministry simply
invites additional experts to join the committee for a time.
   ``It doesn't cost a lot because people are not paid for that,''
Juillet said in an interview at Broussais Hospital in Paris, where
he practices medicine.
   A decision is generally rendered within a few months after a
company sends in its research reports. The health minister
rubber-stamps it.
   ``When I was there, the limit was four months, and I almost
never saw anything over four months,'' Weintraub says.
   In contrast, at the FDA ``some drugs are quicker than others but
by and large it's about 18 months'' for approval after a final
application has been submitted, Weintraub says.
   ``In the French system, everything is reviewed within an hour or
an hour-and-a-half in one day at one presentation,'' Weintraub says.
   The FDA also places great emphasis on certain studies considered
pivotal in demonstrating the safety and effectiveness of new drugs.
The most important thing the FDA could learn from the French would
be ``not focusing on the so-called pivotal studies, but looking at
all the studies and all the data,'' Weintraub says.
   One of the drawbacks of the French system, according to
Weintraub, is that the health ministry does little until research
is complete and the company is ready to ask for approval.
   The FDA requires a review of laboratory findings before it will
allow a new drug to be tested on humans. The French don't. Drug
companies simply inform the health ministry that human trials are
about to begin, and the ministry rarely intervenes.
   ``They can't guide you,'' Weintraub says. The FDA meets
regularly with drug companies testing new drugs to advise the
companies on what further research is needed for approval.
   In France, ``there are no contacts between the committee and the
companies until the file is through,'' Juillet says.
   When the file of research data is complete, Juillet, acting as
the industry representative, makes the company's case before the
committee. ``My mission is to be a witness and defend the companies
and give them information if there is a problem,'' he says.
   French drug companies have a much closer relationship with the
health ministry than American companies do with the FDA, Weintraub
says, ``because the reviewers don't work for the government; it's
not a `them-and-us' thing.''
   In contrast, FDA reviewers and drug companies often deeply
distrust each other. Company officials charge the FDA with dragging
its feet, while the FDA often blames delays on the inadequacy of
the companies' research.
   Juillet suggests the FDA should rely more on outside reviewers.
``I think the open system is a good thing, working with people on
the outside,'' he says.
   Dr. Charles Leighton, a senior vice-president at Merck Sharpe &amp;
Dohme Research Laboratories in Blue Bell, Pa., says one reason
French drug approvals are often faster is that the French have
decided that the benefits of speeding new drug approval outweigh
the risks.
   ``They realize there might be a risk,'' he says. ``If you're the
first country to approve a drug, you might be the first to see a
problem.''
   Weintraub says history shows, however, that the French have not
in fact been subject to more problems with drug side-effects than
have Americans. ``We aren't saved from every problem drug, nor are
they exposed to every problem drug,'' he says.
   Although he believes the FDA has much to learn from the French,
Weintraub praises the expertise of the FDA's reviewers. ``Everybody
respects those people. They're smart, hard-working. ... A lot of
countries will allow marketing of the drug once the FDA does.
   ``We are the benchmark, for good or ill.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1510EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--HimalayanBattleground Adv15-2Takes   10-02 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Himalayan Battleground, Adv 15-2 Takes,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo,
1 graphic.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The startling boom of heavy artillery
reverberates through the world's highest mountains where for five
years India and Pakistan have been fighting for control of an icy
wasteland. While neither side will say how many casualities they
have suffered, they estimate only one in three resulted from combat.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIACHEN GLACIER, Kashmir (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Top of the World is the
battleground in a largely unknown and undeclared war raging between
India and Pakistan, a war in which wind, snow and ice often take a
greater toll than the enemy.
   At stake is national prestige and possession of the Siachen, a
Himalayan wasteland wedged between Pakistan-occupied Kashmir and
territory controlled by China.
   After more than five years of fighting and artillery duels over
what would appear to be a minor issue, India and Pakistan are
trying to end the costly war.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India and Pakistani Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto, confident they can do business, are
pushing to bury ancient animosities and move their countries into a
friendlier era.
   But while they talk of peace, huge artillery guns continue to
boom, each startling blast echoing through the stillness of the
cathedral-like mountains.
   Fifteen years ago few thought it possible to fight, let alone
hold ground, for years in the higher reaches of the Karakoram
mountain range, where lie the Siachen and more than half of the
world's 20 tallest peaks.
   Never had battles been fought for any length of time at heights
of up to 4 miles, breathing air that contains less than half the
oxygen at sea level and at temperatures that frequently drop to 50
degrees below zero.
   ``Climb a 21,000-foot mountain anywhere else in the world and
you get an award,'' Brig. Gen. V.R. Raghavan, commander of the
Indian troops, told foreign journalists flown to the base camp at
the mouth of the Siachen and then taken by helicopter up the
45-mile-long, 6-mile-wide glacier.
   The number of casualties on both sides remains a military
secret, although Raghavan estimated only one-third are actually due
to combat.
   ``There are natural limits to this conflict _ the weather and
the terrain,'' he said. ``Here one has to fight constantly and even
more doggedly to survive. So much depends on so few and death can
be just one false move away.''
   The conflict's roots can be traced to the 1947 partition of
Moslem Pakistan and India, which is predominantly Hindu.
   Both countries have coveted the 85,000 square miles of
Jammu-Kashmir, a predominantly Moslem state that acceded to India.
   The dispute led Pakistan to grab about one-third of the
territory. In 1949, the two countries signed an agreement that drew
a cease-fire line that stopped at the southern foot of the Saltoro
range running along the glacier's western edge toward the Chinese
border.
   Negotiators did not extend the line because there was no
fighting in the region and glaciers were difficult to demarcate.
Although there were minor adjustments following the 1965 and 1971
India-Pakistan wars, the question of Siachen was left unresolved.
   Almost from the beginning, India has said it is entitled to
control all of Kashmir. Pakistan, however, says it has controlled
the Siachen all along, citing mountaineering expeditions that for
years sought its permission to enter and atlases published in the
United States and Britain in the early 1980s that showed the area
under its control.
   India first deployed troops to the Siachen in April 1984, a move
it said was merely to pre-empt a planned Pakistani strike.
Islamabad denied the charge.
   The conflict slowly escalated, with each side deploying
thousands of soldiers, erecting outposts and setting up bigger,
more powerful artillery.
   In the winter of 1987, Indian troops abandoned a 20,000-foot
outpost on Bilaford, one of three key passes. When they returned in
the spring and found the Pakistanis had moved in, a fierce six-day
battle ensued, with both sides pounding the other with artillery.
   Pakistan retaliated three months later with its biggest strike
of the war, capturing one post and closing in on a second before
the Indians unleashed an artillery barrage.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1511EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--HimalayanBattleground Adv15-1stAdd   10-02 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Himalayan Battleground, Adv 15-1st Add,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>SIACHEN GLACIER: artillery barrage.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The secret to this conflict is to control the high ground, and
we do. Pakistan is on the lower slopes, and we can punish them
whenever necessary,'' Raghavan said as 130mm artillery guns fired,
reverberating through the canyons.
   ``We have just given them our reply for firing at one of our
posts.''
   Indian soldiers posted on the peaks and ridges keep watch day
and night for the other side's supply and patrols columns.
   It is a lonely existence for the soldiers, most of whom come
from the palm-fringed beaches of southern Kerala state or the
desert of western Rajasthan or the jungles of eastern Assam and
have never lived _ much less fought in _ a snowbound environment.
   ``This is the hardest place on Earth,'' said Modhival Iqbal, a
weary 23-year-old soldier who just completed four months of duty at
a 19,000-foot outpost.
   From the base camp, soldiers armed with ice picks, skis,
shovels, ropes and 65-pound backpacks trudge across the black
moraine, through knee-deep snow and over 200-foot crevasses and up
the walls of ice to their posts.
   But before leaving, each visits the cave-like enclave where
there are hung images of the Hindu gods Rama, Shiva and Ganesha, as
well as a portrait of Jesus Christ.
   ``Everybody who goes to the glacier comes here first and says
his prayers. It doesn't matter if he's Hindu or Moslem or
Christian,'' Raghavan said.
   The trek takes six to eight days, with brief rest stops at posts
along the way, before reaching the small outposts where the
soldiers live for months in bunkers dug deep in the snow.
   ``Every day up there is important because every day you survive
means you're one day closer to leaving,'' Iqbal said. ``It's not
just the Pakistanis. It's the blizzards, the howling winds, the
blinding glare of the sun off the snow. It's the avalanches and the
isolation.
   ``We have plenty of food and supplies, but not much else. Maybe
someday somebody will organize a society for the prevention of
cruelty to soldiers.''
   A month-long clash erupted in April when Pakistan allegedly
tried to establish a new post within easy firing range of the
Indians and both sides dispatched soldiers to an icy 21,300-foot
peak. Pakistan, however, said it had only discovered an old
observation post.
   Accounts of what happened differ, but the Indians apparently
requested a meeting between the two opposition commanders. After
three sessions both sides agreed to pull back and the Indians
agreed to accept the post the Pakistanis had said was there all
along.
   With India commanding most of the heights along the Saltoro, it
now wants that boundary to serve as the northern extension of the
line that divides most of Kashmir between India and Pakistan.
   Since January 1986, the two governments have met five times to
discuss withdrawing their troops from the glacier and to consider
declaring the region a demilitarized zone.
   Pakistan officials believe the eventual withdrawal of Indiain
troops would be a major victory for Ms. Bhutto and a vindication of
their position that India started the conflict by sending troops
into an undemarcated area.
   Both Pakistani and Indian officials say the rapport between
Gandhi and Ms. Bhutto is helping but it still may be difficult for
either to yield. Gandhi is only months away from facing a national
election. Ms. Bhutto is in an even stickier situation, facing
criticism at home from opposition leaders who accuse her of
submission to India.
   While their leaders struggle to find a political solution, both
sides contend they can hold out indefinitely.
   ``Whether there is a settlement is a matter between state and
state,'' Raghavan said. ``Until then, we have a job to do. That
doesn't mean we want to stay here forever. Who would? But we can
stay here as long as we have to.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
