<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1516EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--IconPainting Adv15   10-02 1146</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Icon Painting, Adv 15,1185</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The painting of religious icons is an art form
inspired by the Eastern Orthodox Church and now practiced by less
than 100 artists across the United States and Canada. But there are
two schools that teach icon painting in this country, one in a
mountain community in western Pennsylvania.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIGONIER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Zimmerman paints mystical ``windows
to heaven,'' he says, haunting religious icons used as vehicles of
prayer.
   ``Icons are a very important part of the church,'' Zimmerman
says. ``They are a spiritual and physical depiction of some sacred
image _ of Christ or the Virgin Mary, a saint or some other
liturgical happening.''
   Icons, popular in the Eastern Orthodox Church, are painted in
rich, luminous colors. Faces are depicted with prayerful
expressions, and religious figures usually are crowned with halos
of real gold, not gold paint.
   Perpective and scale are distorted to give the religious scenes
a supernatural feel.
   Some regard icons simply as products of religious devotion or
art inspired by the Eastern Orthodox Church, which began the
tradition centuries ago.
   The religious regard icons as ``windows to heaven'' or
``theology made visible'' and believe focusing on them deepens
prayer and meditation, Zimmerman says.
   Zimmerman, 36, of nearby Johnstown, has been teaching two-week
classes in icon painting since last summer at Antiochian Village,
an Orthodox cultural center outside this mountain community about
60 miles east of Pittsburgh.
   The village, and the School of Sacred Arts in New York City, are
the only schools in the United States offering classes in icon
painting. Zimmerman says there are about 90 iconographers in the
United States and Canada.
   Students must learn to create within the strict conventions of
the art. They eventually develop their own styles while absorbing
hundreds of details on symbolism used in icons.
   For instance, halos _ blazing disks of golden light _ are
applied in gold leaf around the heads of divine figures to depict
emanations of radiant light.
   ``They are auras of spiritual holiness. Icons depict not just a
person's earthly image, but a spritual-type image as well,''
Zimmerman says. ``There is no light source like in other art. The
light source comes from within the figure.''
   Anatomical details such as facial features, fingers and body
shapes are stylized to give figures an additional aura of the
supernatural. Scenes are painted in two dimensions and no shadows
are cast.
   ``That's why in iconography, the icons do not look like real
people,'' Zimmerman says. ``We're not trying to make them look like
real people. It's a symbolic representation of a person.''
   Certain colors are associated with some religious figures.
Christ, for example, usually is depicted in blue and red.
   ``You usually never depict Christ in green,'' Zimmerman says.
``It's not traditional.''
   Iconographers say they technically do not paint icons, but
``write'' them. Artists are taught to create their works with
thousands of tiny caligraphic strokes.
   ``What they are are scriptural pictures _ pictures of the
scriptures,'' Zimmerman says. ``When you write the icon, you're
writing scriptures just the same as when you are using words.''
   Although the mechanics of the art are important, theology
debates often erupt during class sessions.
   ``It's very, very, very theological,'' Zimmerman says. ``There's
a lot of rules attached to this _ not a lot of painting rules, but
a whole lot of rules on what's proper, what's liturgical, what's
not liturgical.''
   Interest in icon painting has increased dramatically in recent
years, and not just among the religious.
   ``People here in the West are just beginning to discover the art
of the Orthodox church,'' Zimmerman says. ``It's not just something
Grandma brought over from Czechoslovakia.''
   ``I think the whole interest in religion is coming back,'' says
Steven Glazer, an official of the School of Sacred Arts.
   ``For a long time people were looking to Eastern religions and
Eastern mysticism. While that's still popular, people are returning
to their own traditions now.''
   Iconographer Vladislav Andreyev, who was born in the Soviet
Union, offers a 14-week class at the New York school, which also
offers classes on the art traditions of other religions.
   ``It's pretty international and we sell out every time. We
usually limit classes to 10 students,'' he says. ``Many of the arts
we teach are not available elsewhere.''
   Classes offered in the subject are short-term, but it often
takes years to develop competence, says Nicholas Papas, 30, an
iconographer from nearby Indiana.
   ``When I first started I was very timid and self-conscious,'' he
says. ``I was pretentious, boxed in and stiff. I feel that it took
me years to even begin to break out of that. I feel like I'm still
breaking out of that.''
   Papas began painting icons in 1979 and started full-time work as
an iconographer in 1982.
   Papas sells notebook-size icons of a favorite subject, such as
portraits of Christ, for as little as $175, but bigger and more
complicated works can be worth thousands of dollars.
   ``Every iconographer has his own idea of what he should get for
an icon,'' he says.
   Papas' icons usually are sold to churches or people who display
them in their homes. A giant mural of his is displayed 30 feet
above the ground in the dome of St. Mary's Byzantine Catholic
Church in nearby Homer City.
   A 70- by 12-foot mural Papas currently is working on, ``The
Communion of the Apostles,'' will attempt to depict what heaven
looks like.
   The idea of selling icons to people who admire them only as
works of art is a sticky ethical problem for some iconographers who
fear the buyer would be misusing a holy object.
   ``I would feel uncomfortable, but I would do it,'' says Papas,
who was born to an Eastern Orthodox family. ``Even if a person
asked me for an icon for the wrong reason, there's a possibility
that the icon could be a good influence on them.''
   Zimmerman began painting icons 18 years ago, while studying to
be an art teacher at Indiana University of Pennsylvania.
   An iconographer who served as the choir director of one local
Orthodox church recruited him and several of his college friends to
help him with his work.
   ``We made his job a little easier by filling in colors and stuff
like that,'' Zimmerman says.
   Also during college, Zimmerman decided to leave the Protestant
United Church of Christ to become an Eastern Orthodox Christian.
   ``I was always interested in religion, always interested in
exploring other religions as well,'' he says. ``I felt the Orthodox
Church was very satisfying. I felt this church has so much to offer
liturgically, spiritually, musically, artistically _ everything.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv15   10-02 0892</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 15,0912</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)
   </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Savage didn't set out to become an
actor, but now that he's become quite successful at the age of 13
he'd like to stick to it.
   Fred, who was nominated for an Emmy for his lead role in ABC's
hit comedy series ``The Wonder Years'' but didn't win, is a video
game hustler in the upcoming December release ``The Wizard.''
   ``I never really wanted to get into the business,'' he says.
``It was never a goal. It just happened.''
   It happened when he began doing commercials at the age of 6 in
his hometown of Chicago, where he lives with his family when he's
not working. He made his film debut at 8 in the movie ``The Boy Who
Could Fly.''
   ``I really enjoy acting,'' Fred says, now that he is a veteran
performer. ``I'd like to continue it for a while. I do want to go
to high school and college. I'd like to direct. On the set they
call me `Little Opie,' because Ron Howard started as a child actor
and grew up to direct. He could be a role model for me. I'm always
looking through the camera and checking angles. I want to learn all
I can.''
   ``The Wonder Years'' is the kind of show that will grow with
Fred. It made its debut in March 1988, and it has already changed
to reflect that Fred, as Kevin Arnold, is maturing and facing
different problems and challenges.
   ``The beauty of the show is that when my voice changes I can
still do the show,'' he says. ``Even if I get zits.''
   The beauty is also that virtually everyone can identify with the
adolescent traumas of Kevin, Paul, Winnie and their friends. The
time period this season has advanced to 1969, but its stories and
characters transcend time and place.
   ``I see Kevin as just a typical kid growing up in the late
1960s,'' he says. ``He's very shy. He has a non-stop fear of the
men in his family. His older brother's always beating up on him and
everyone's afraid of his dad.
   ``He's sort of insecure, especially around girls. But I think
he's a cool kid. He's a normal kid in 1969. This year he moves into
the eighth grade and has trouble with algebra and the algebra
teacher. This year his older brother learns to drive.''
   His favorite episode is the one in which Kevin accompanies his
father to his office.
   ``It's so true,'' he says. ``The exact thing didn't happen to me
but I went to my dad's office. I was so impressed watching him
work. I'd bring books to the office and copy the whole book on the
copy machine.''
   Fred, accompanied by his mother, is late for an interview. He
explains he had to complete work with his tutor for the public
school he attends in Chicago. He also explains that his father,
who's an industrial real estate broker, is back in Chicago.
   ``But they're not divorced,'' he quickly adds. They're merely
temporarily apart because of the requirements of his role on ``The
Wonder Years.''
   Fred has a younger sister, Kala, and a brother, Ben, who
appeared with him in his latest movie, ``Little Monsters.''
   In ``The Wizard,'' he and his younger brother head for a video
game championship. ``They're heading from Utah to the game in Los
Angeles,'' Fred says. ``They make money hustling other kids to play
video games. Their father's looking for them and their mother hires
a kind of bounty hunter.''
   The movie also stars Luke Edwards, Beau Bridges, Christian
Slater and Jenny Lewis.
   Fred first got into acting when notices in his Chicago
neighborhood asked for small children to audition for a television
commercial.
   ``The auditions were near our house and it sounded like fun,''
he says. ``So Mom and I went over. I didn't get it and six months
later the same director held another audition. I didn't get it
again. Six months later the director called and I was cast in a Pac
Man vitamins commercial.
   ``I did commercials for about two years, then I got into movies.
I did quite a few and I was in a TV series called `Morning Star,
Evening Star.' It only lasted six weeks.
   ``I was called in to read for `The Wonder Years' because the
producers had seen me in the movie `Vice Versa.' I flew to L.A. and
read for the network. I guess they approved because I got the part.
They ran the pilot after the Super Bowl in 1988 and we went on the
air in March.''
   The show won the Emmy last year as best comedy series after just
half of a season on the air. Fred never saw the Emmy telecast
because he was asleep when the show came on. He was in North
Carolina making the movie ``Little Monsters.'' His mother wouldn't
let him stay up.
   This year he was not only nominated as best lead actor in a
comedy, making him the youngest person ever nominated in a lead
role, but he was an award presenter with Carl Reiner.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
