<DOCNO> AP891002-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1526EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv15   10-02 1100</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 15,1127</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before he returned to Broadway for the first
time in 25 years, Tony Randall wondered whether audiences would
forget television's Felix Unger long enough to accept him as the
tormented protagonist of ``M. Butterfly.''
   After all, Randall was Felix, the fussy, fastidious half of
``The Odd Couple,'' for five years on prime time television as well
as in nine stage productions with four different Oscar Madisons,
including his TV co-star, Jack Klugman.
   ``That question came up a million times,'' Randall recalled the
other day. ``Would they want to laugh instead?''
   He need not have worried.
   ``There's not a moment of rejection and having to win them
over,'' he says now, talking about his performance as Rene
Gallimard, the French diplomat who has an affair with a Chinese
opera singer. And theatergoers go along willingly with the more
bizarre plot developments in David Henry Hwang's Tony award-winning
play. Gallimard is seduced by the singer who turns out to be a man
masquerading as a woman.
   ``But then director John Dexter has set up the play so that when
the first voice comes out of this miasma of light and movement and
music, the audience is already captivated,'' the actor says. ``He's
the only director I ever worked with in my life who I thought was a
genius.''
   Randall is one of those actors who's not afraid of opinions.
   Asked why it has been more than 25 years since he has appeared
on Broadway, he says, ``No one's asked me.
   ``I've frequently had a year off or more and have noised it
around town that I was available. The fact that a man is a Broadway
producer doesn't make him any more intelligent than a network
executive.''
   Not that he hasn't been on stage during this time. Last year,
there was a Ray Cooney farce done at the Paper Mill Playhouse in
New Jersey, and he has worked for John Neville's theater company in
Nova Scotia as well as in all those tours of ``The Odd Couple.''
   ```The Odd Couple' is a masterpiece,'' he states
matter-of-factly. ``The laughs just roll in. But you have to play
it as if it's `Hamlet' _ very, very seriously.
   ``Any play that is good has some ideological basis behind it. In
`The Odd Couple,' it's male bonding. The play is very chauvinistic
and anti-feminist. The only women in it are two dingbats, and the
men hate their wives. The only happiness these men have is when
they are away from their wives.''
   Randall has worked in just about every medium except burlesque.
Last year when he was honored at the Museum of Broadcasting, four
videocassette machines simultaneously unspooled ``The Odd Couple,''
``The Tony Randall Show,'' ``Love, Sidney'' and ``Mr. Peepers,''
the four television series he has done.
   ``There was my life on the screen,'' he recalls. ``You could
watch me go bald.''
   Bits and pieces of Randall's story also are told in ``Which
Reminds Me,'' a collection of show business anecdotes he has
gathered during his more than 40 years as an actor. Randall, who
says he's ``cursed with almost total recall,'' wrote the book in
collaboration with and at the urging of a good friend, Michael
Mindlin, an advertising executive and movie publicity man. It
arrives in bookstores in November from Delacorte Press.
   Randall, fresh out of Tulsa, Olka., and one year at Northwestern
University, came to New York in the early 1940s. His first Broadway
show was Thorton Wilder's ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' in 1942. Well,
almost. He was drafted into the Army the second day of rehearsals.
   Four years later, Randall returned to New York, where he found a
lot of work on radio and a few small parts in the theater. But he
didn't _ and still doesn't _ think much of radio work.
   ``It was nothing,'' Randall recalls. ``Standing there reading a
script. What was that? And the script, for the most part, was
dreck. It probably had been written that morning. How could you
act? You had one rehearsal and you were on the air.''
   Randall had better luck _ and better parts _ on television,
beginning in 1952, when he appeared as English teacher Harvey
Weskitt in ``Mr. Peepers,'' one of the best of the early TV sitcoms.
   His big break on Broadway came in 1955 in ``Inherit the Wind,''
a retelling of the Scopes trial in which he played a reporter
modeled after H.L. Mencken.
   The play propelled him to Hollywood for scores of movies,
including three Doris Day-Rock Hudson classics, ``Pillow Talk,''
``Lover Come Back'' and ``Send Me No Flowers,'' as well as other
films like ``Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter?'' and ``The Seven
Faces of Dr. Lao.''
   The 69-year-old Randall admits he was a little frightened about
returning to Broadway in a play as physically demanding as ``M.
Butterfly.''
   ``That's what I thought would kill me,'' he says. ``Moving
around like that and the knowledge that my predecessor (John
Rubinstein) had lost 25 pounds. And he was a young guy. They had to
get new costumes for him.
   ``But I was at the doctor's this morning with my wife and I've
gained weight.''
   Memorizing was an easy part of the job, Randall says. He had
four weeks of rehearsal before going on in ``M. Butterfly,'' and
director Dexter came back for a week to work with him.
   ``A replacement doesn't have that much option really,'' Randall
says. ``The first three weeks of rehearsal, he just works with the
stage manager who takes him through the established staging. If he
wants to change anything he can, but it's foolish. The stage is
lighted. Everything is set. If you want to move here instead of
there, that means they have to change the lights. It's not worth
it.''
   Actually, he adds, playing in ``The Odd Couple'' was more tiring
than ``M. Butterfly.'' ``But the role of Oscar is harder than
Felix. Oscar is a killer,'' he says of other half of ``The Odd
Couple.''
   ``I don't think I could play Oscar too well. Although when I
went into this play, a half dozen people asked me what part I'm
playing,'' Randall laughs. ``I don't see myself as the young
Chinese girl.
   ``I think it's `The Seven Faces of Dr. Lao.' They know I played
an Oriental in that movie.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
