<FIRST>s i BC-Taiwan-40Years Adv08-2Takes   10-02 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Taiwan-40 Years, Adv 08-2 Takes,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>After 40 Years, Taiwan Is Rich and Democracy Makes Inroads</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>By ANNIE HUANG</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Forty years after Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek
and his Nationalist Chinese arrived in defeat from the mainland,
Taiwan is prosperous _ the world's 13th largest trading nation _
and democracy is beginning to take hold.
   But in 1949, with Mao Tse-tung' Communists in control of
mainland China, the outlook for the Chinese Nationalists on Taiwan
was bleak.
   Not only had they been routed from their homeland, they faced a
restive Taiwanese population that viewed Chiang and his 2 million
or so followers as an occupying force.
   The Nationalists prevailed, nevertheless, by dint of
authoritarian rule and clinging to their contention, supported by
the United States and other Western nations, that they were the
legitimate rulers of China.
   In the years since, firmly guided economic policies have
transformed Taiwan into the economic success it is now as the
island approaches its national day Oct. 10 _ Double Ten, for the
tenth day of the tenth month.
   With prosperity at its peak and people demanding greater
freedoms, the Nationalists have begun to loosen their authoritarian
grip, slowly bringing democracy to the island of 20 million and
permitting contacts with the rival Communist Chinese for the first
time since the civil war on the mainland.
   ``Many people used to be disappointed with the government and
tried to emigrate whenever they had the chance,'' said Lu Ya-li,
political science professor of National Taiwan University. ``They
now feel there is some hope and have begun to care and criticize.''
   An agrarian economy based on rice and sugar production has given
way to the manufacturing of textiles, electronic products and
machinery.
   The formula was capitalism mixed with government policies
designed to stimulate selected industries. While the Nationalists
controlled major monopolies, many of the light-industry factories
were family-run operations that helped spread the wealth around the
island.
   Annual per capita income rose from $50 in 1949 to $5,512 last
year. Gross national product soared from $1.2 billion 40 years ago
to $119 billion in 1988.
   Exports led the way, with foreign trade jumping from $300
million in 1952 to $110 billion last year. So much foreign exchange
has poured in that the island's coffers bulge with $74 billion in
reserves.
   Prosperity is everywhere on the streets of Taipei. Porsche and
BMW automobiles snake through the congested streets, fancy
restaurants are on almost every block and the latest electronic
gadgets fill store windows.
   Indeed, Taipei, the island's capital, seems to lack nothing.
   Except foreign embassies.
   While the island advanced on economic successes, it faced bitter
diplomatic defeats as the world recognized the Communist Chinese
government in Beijing.
   Only 24 countries, mostly tiny island nations and Latin American
countries, still recognize Taiwan diplomatically, down from 50 in
1949. The Communist Chinese government has formal ties with 135
countries.
   The toughest blow came in 1978, when Taiwan's major ally, the
United States, announced it was cutting diplomatic links and
setting up formal relations with Beijing.
   The United States dismantled its military bases on Taiwan and
said military aid would not increase in quantity or quality.
   But the U.S. market did not close to Taiwan and that helped
assure its economic health.
   Chiang Peng-chien, a leading opposition politician, blamed
Taiwan's diplomatic isolation on the ``dream of a reunified China''
ruled by a Nationalist government.
   The Nationalists also used that dream in their efforts to
justify their monopoly on political power and the harsh quelling of
dissent.
   The Nationalists placed Taiwan under martial law and refused to
allow rival political parties or an opposition press. Critics who
traveled overseas often were not allowed back; many of those who
stayed in Taiwan were thrown in jail.
   By claiming to be the rightful ruler of all China, the
Nationalists insisted that native Taiwanese, who comprise about 80
percent of the population, could not replace any of the members of
the Legislature and electoral college who had been elected in
mainland China before the civil war defeat.
   But as the Taiwanese prospered economically they demanded more
political rights. It was Chiang Kai-shek's son, the late President
Chiang Ching-kuo, who finally launched the political liberalization
the Nationalists needed if they were to maintain popular support.
   In 1987, Chiang Ching-kuo lifted martial law, which paved the
way for the formation of opposition political parties. Some media
restrictions were erased, leading to a more critical press. Taiwan
residents were allowed to visit relatives on the Chinese mainland,
bringing a more relaxed attitude toward the Communists.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Taiwan-40Years Adv08-1stAdd   10-02 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Taiwan-40 Years, Adv 08-1st Add,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>TAIPEI: the Communists.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrations became an almost daily occurrence, with Taiwanese
taking to the streets to protest everything from prostitution to
pollution.
   By the following year, it became apparent that the gradual
liberalizing trend would not easily be reversed.
   When Chiang Ching-kuo died in January 1988, he was succeeded by
Vice President Lee Teng-hui, the first native Taiwanese to lead the
Nationalist government and a supporter of democratic reform.
   Six months later, Lee was named chairman of the Nationalist
Party and some, but not all, aging hardliners from the mainland
retired from top party posts.
   The Nationalist leadership under Lee has proposed a gradual
increase in the percentage of the Legislature that is elected on
Taiwan. Still, only less than half the seats will be contested in
Dec. 2 elections, making it impossible for the opposition to wrest
any real political power from the Nationalists.
   ``We are fully committed to democratization,'' government
spokesman Shaw Yu-ming said in a recent interview. ``We are moving
slowly but surely to meet the demands of the time.''
   But Taiwan still has problems:
   _Rising wages and an appreciating currency: These have made
Taiwan less competitive in low-cost exports and the government is
seeking a new economic formula to deal with the problem. ``We must
actively push forward the research of top-notch industrial
technologies,'' Premier Lee Huan recently told the Legislature.
``The service sector should also grow quicker to become the center
of our future economic development.''
   _Pollution caused by years of rapid development: Taipei's air is
foul and the island's rivers are filthy. Some villagers have
protested the construction of new factories they fear will ruin the
local environment.
   _Gambling and speculation: Gambling is illegal but rampant, and
speculating in the stock market has become the national pastime.
The Taiwan stock exchange is second only to Tokyo's in trading
volume, and some analysts believe it is a speculative bubble
waiting to burst. Some see the obsession as a temporary phenomenon
following the easing of foreign exchange controls in 1987. Others
argue that industrialists are more interested in quick profit than
in longterm investment, such as automating factories and developing
more sophisticated products.
   Perhaps the greatest challenge facing Taiwan is its policy
toward mainland China.
   Official policy remains the ``three no's'' _ no contact, no
negotiations, no compromise with the Communists. But that policy
today is a shambles.
   The government allows trade with the mainland if conducted
through a third party such as Hong Kong, and Taiwanese businessmen
have begun investing in the mainland to take advantage of low labor
costs.
   Finance Minister Shirley Kuo traveled to Beijing in May to
attend an Asian Development Bank meeting and met privately with
Communist officials.
   The future of such contacts is somewhat clouded because of the
Communists' violent suppression of the democracy movement this past
spring. But the old Nationalist dream of returning to rule the
mainland seems shattered.
   When the Chinese Communist government seemed in disarray during
the spring democracy movement, the Nationalists were forced to
acknowledge there was not much they could do but watch.
   ``We must have the courage to face the fact that at this moment
we are unable to effectively exercise the right to govern the
mainland,'' President Lee told a meeting of Nationalist leaders on
June 3.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 8</NOTE>
