<FIRST>s i BC-Afghanistan-Islam Adv08   10-02 1183</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Afghanistan-Islam, Adv 08,1225</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Differences Over Islam Are at Root of Afghanistan's Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFAQUAHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Differences over what is and what is
not Islam lies at the heart of Afghanistan's 10-year war.
   President Najib has been attempting to deflate his foes' main
rallying cry _ that his Marxist-based People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan is a pack of godless Soviet stooges _ by transplanting
the party's ideology into the country's Islamic heritage.
   But many Afghans hold deep suspicions that the party is rooted
in the Soviet Union next door. The assault on Islam by Najib's
predecessors has not been forgotten.
   Islam is the one link the violently competitive Afghan tribes
all share. Being recognized as a good Moslem is an ironclad form of
acceptance.
   Doubt in the leaders' faith is strongest among the Shiite Moslem
minority known as the Hazara. They make up about 17 percent of the
16 million Afghans, 99 percent of whom are Moslems. The Sunni sect
is the overwhelming majority.
   Hundreds of thousands of Hazara live in Kabul, but most inhabit
the mountains at the country's center, an area known as Hazarajat.
   The government has little control there, but the Hazara rejected
a government offer of formal autonomy earlier this year.
   ``The Hazara want to be part of the government, but not their
(People's Democratic Party) government,'' said one 52-year-old
professional interviewed at the Chendawul mosque. ``It is a
communist government.''
   The group was officially discriminated against for years, kept
out of the army and their rituals banned in public.
   The Hazara now have religious freedom, but they contend the
government ignores their development needs.
   ``If you go to Hazarajat, there are no houses, there are no
schools, there are no hospitals,'' said a mullah, or prayer leader,
at the Chendawul mosque.
   The Hazara spoke in interviews only on condition of anonymity,
saying that many who publicly denounced the government in the past
were sent to prison.
   They said the government's wooing them is in part motivated by
the desire to improve relations with neighboring Iran.
   The Islamic Republic of Iran, founded by the late Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, is run by Shiite Moslem clergymen and supports
the Shiite branches of the Moslem rebels, the mujahedeen, seeking
to overthrow the government in Kabul.
   The Hazara say they respect Khomeini as a religious figure but
do not look to his revolution to solve their problems.
   Many Hazara reject fellow Shiites who have joined the
government, such as Prime Minister Sultan Ali Kishtmand.
   ``The people in the party, it makes no difference from what
place, what religion they are, we still think they are communist,''
said the mullah.
   Najmuddin Kawyani, secretary of the party's Central Committeee,
says, ``Our party is not a communist party, our ideology is not a
communist one.''
   Government officials say development will come in time. They
point out that President Najib, who uses just one name, went to the
Chendawul mosque in August and pledged 10 million afghans, about
$180,000, for reconstruction.
   Suspicions about the religious faith of the government also are
held by other Afghan Moslems, including Maulavi Abdul Rauf at the
upscale Wazir Akbar Khan mosque, which is surrounded by a rose
garden in Kabul's diplomatic quarter.
   ``Our people are Moslem,'' he said. ``We don't know about the
government.'' The Sunni Maulavi, who is roughly the equivalent of a
bishop, spent five months in prison after he assailed Soviet
influence in Afghanistan at a sermon the president had attended.
   He also opposes the government's practice of writing sermons in
support of its policies for the 20,000 mullahs on its payroll.
   ``Religion should be free,'' Rauf said.
   The role of the government is ``to build more mosques, persuade
people to pray more, to establish the conditions so people will
want to pray,'' he said.
   The lack of trust in the party stems from alleged atrocities
that followed the April 1978 Marxist revolution.
   Independent studies put the number of Afghans killed in those
early days of the revolution at 50,000 to 100,000, with Hazara and
clergymen a particular target. Hazara claim 13,000 of their
tribesman disappeared from Kabul in one day.
   The government's land redistribution program was seen as an
attempt to rewrite Moslem inheritance laws and a heavy-handed
literacy campaign as an attack on the clergy as teachers. Even the
study of Islamic art was banned.
   These measures helped spark the rebellion against the government
and all have been reversed since the Soviet intervention in
December 1979, after which a more tolerant wing of the party was
given power.
   ``The culture of the people must be taken into considertion,''
said Abdul Ghafoor Bahir, minister of Islamic guidance. ``When the
revolution came there were some mistakes.''
   Islam was enshrined as the state religion in the constitution
adopted in 1987, which also stipulates that the president be a
Moslem. New laws cannot contradict Islamic law.
   Najib has won praise for establishing the University of Islamic
Studies and Research in Kabul. The Soviet withdrawel in February
gave a major boost to combating his un-Islamic image.
   The research center publishes books about Islamic history in
Afghanistan, such as a chronicle of the holy place in Kandahar.
   It is also a religious cheering section for the party, however.
Its walls are plastered with stickers of Koranic quotations used by
President Najib.
   ``He who destroys the house of one Moslem, he is in truth
destroying his own house,'' said one quotation. It is a pointed
reference to the destruction wrought by rockets of the mujahedeen,
whose name means holy warriors.
   Mohammad Siddiq Sailani, the university's president, Kabul said
that its aim is to educate students and that the religious
squabbling impedes progress.
   ``Some traditional customs that exist among the people are
un-Islamic,'' he said. ``We want to replace them with the real
Islam.''
   Among the customs he listed as un-Islamic was what he described
as the lack of equal treatment for women.
   ``A woman is not a toy,'' he said. ``Islam establishes many
rights for women and the rights should never be threatened by men.''
   The government viewpoint on this and other issues clashes
sharply with that of Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, leader of the
fundamentalist Hezb-e-Islami faction of the Pakistani-based
mujahedeen.
   He has a reputation for having all the bars in Kabul bombed
because Islam forbids the consumption of alcohol. His group also is
believed responsible for killing two women bus drivers by blowing
up their buses when the government briefly experimented with women
drivers several years ago.
   The government also highlights what it calls the atrocities
committed in the name of Islam by the Saudi Arabian-financed
Wahhabi mercenaries fighting for the mujahedeen. Reports of their
mutilating victims and selling women into slavery are widespread.
   ``In our opinion, it is because of lack of knowledge of the
Koran that makes people act like this,'' said Gholam Sarwar Manzur,
president of the state-run Council of Clergy.
   Afghans in general say they basically want Islam respected by
the government.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 8</NOTE>
