<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2252EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   10-02 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Look Who's Talking''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Film opens nationwide Oct. 13.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Remember the ``Bachelor Mother'' kind of movie in which Ginger
Rogers seeks a husband so her baby will have a father?
   ``Look Who's Talking'' is a 1989 replay with all the old
gimmicks intact (``I don't like to fly,'' she insists. Next scene,
she's flying in his plane). The only innovation: the baby talks.
Not only that, the voice is that of Bruce Willis. The title, get it?
   It's a pleasant sitcom with amiable performances, especially by
the four infants who play Mikey. The scenes under the titles will
no doubt arouse controversy. A large round object floats amid
translucent, undulating folds of matter, bouncing gently at the
bottom of a pit. A flock of flittering, chattering polliwogs enters
the space, and one of them joyfully discovers the round object and
climbs inside. A new kind of sex education.
   Throughout the film, the voice of Willis makes comments,
enjoying his nine-month swim, complaining about his abrupt
emergence, conversing with other infants and generally observing
the human comedy. The one-liners wear thin, but some of it is funny
stuff.
   Mikey's mother is Kirstie Alley, a thirtysomething accountant
who has been impregnated by her client, a lecherous, charmless
fast-food entrepreneur (George Segal). When she goes into labor,
she hails a New York cab driven by John Travolta, who races her to
the hospital, then dons a mask and gown and witnesses the delivery.
   As you can guess, he falls for Kirstie and her baby, but she
considers him a loser. He becomes the sitter while she prowls for
prospective fathers, not realizing that Travolta is really a
struggling flight instructor. To illustrate his compassion, there
is a subplot about his concern for his senile grandfather (Abe
Vigoda).
   Amy Heckerling (``Fast Times at Ridgemont High'') directed her
own script, a loose affair that allows the actors to ad lib
aimlessly. The veracity of the film was not helped by filming it in
Canada. The producers saved money, but there's no way that
Vancouver can double for Manhattan.
   Kirstie Alley manages an endearing portrait of the beleaguered
mother; she's as appealing on the big screen as she is in
``Cheers.'' Travolta is so laid back that he seems invisible at
times, but it's good to see him back. Olympia Dukakis has some
bright moments as the worrying grandmother.
   ``Look Who's Talking'' is a Tri-Star release produced by
Jonathan D. Krane. The rating is PG-13, mostly for adult
situations. Running time: 103 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
