<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2258EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Salonen Adv13-15   10-02 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Salonen, Adv 13-15,0978</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 13-15, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Symphony Star Started Career Late, at Age Nine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finnish conducter Esa-Pekka Salonen is a
star in the symphony orchestra world, and his only lament is that
his career in classical music started late _ at age 9.
   ``In this business people start at age 4 or 5,'' said the
31-year-old Salonen, named in August as musical director of the Los
Angeles Philharmonic.
   ``I realized young that this would have to be my life. I had no
other hobbies.''
   Salonen, in Oslo recently as a guest conducter, said he looks
forward to settling down with the Los Angeles orchestra after years
of nomadic conducting. He begins with the 1992-93 season.
   He succeeds Andre Previn in Los Angeles. `When I got the offer
from L.A., I did a hell of a lot of thinking ... finally, after
some time, I decided it made a lot of sense,'' Salonen said.
   ``With the L.A. Philharmonic I have an instrument that is
capable of anything. I have no other plans beyond it. It is
definitely one of the world's most important symphonies and the
possibilities are unlimited.''
   Between bites of an apple during an interview in a hotel lobby,
the boyishly handsome Salonen said, ``Frankly I'm fed up with
hotels and guest conducting.''
   He currently conducts the Swedish Radio Symphony and is
principal guest conducter of the London Philharmonia and the Oslo
Philharmonic.
   These and other engagements keep him on the road up to 44 weeks
a year. He speaks five languages, but countries often blur and,
``in the morning it doesn't matter what I say, its always in the
wrong language.''
   Salonen, in jeans and a blazer, said his weariness goes deeper
than jet lag.
   ``Guest conducting is almost doomed to be superficial unless you
know the orchestra very well. You work with one orchestra and then
a week later you go to another place,'' he said.
   ``What really excites me ... is getting beneath the skin of an
orchestra, which is not possible as a guest conducter. It takes a
long time to build up trust. You have to establish certain musical
habits in an orchestra to be able to express yourself.''
   So he will take a ``semi-sabbatical'' in 1991. ``I will lay down
in my hammock and remain there until I feel the urge to do
something.''
   But he will remain open about guest conducting in Oslo and
elsewhere and about renewing his Swedish contract, which overlaps
with his Los Angeles contract for the 1992-93 season.
   Salonen drew international attention in 1983 when he conducted,
with one week's notice, a London Philharmonia performance of Gustav
Mahler's Third Symphony.
   It was followed by a U.S. debut with the Los Angeles
Philharmonic and concerts in West Berlin, New York, Chicago,
Boston, Philidelphia, Paris, Montreal, Minneapolis and Washington.
   ``I always have so much work to do that I haven't really had
time to think about such concepts as success,'' he said.
   Salonen was raised in Helsinki. His classical music training
began at age 9. He studied composition and conducted at Sibelius
Academy. He eventually began to give concerts in Scandinavia.
   ``I happened to be part of a stimulating group and we had a
music society,'' he said of his childhood experience. ``I loved the
instant feedback. It was fun.'' He still joins young Finns who
compose and play their own music in a group called Avanti!
   A a composer, french horn player and pianist, Salonen began
conducting to make a living, and ``because I needed a conducter who
was sympathetic to my music, and that was me.
   ``Now I would rather see someone else conduct my music ... I get
very nervous about conducting my own music.''
   He is known as a champion of contempory music and avant-garde
experimentation. A philharmonic has a dual function, he said: as a
guardian of traditional music and as a forum for new ideas.
   ``Contemperary music allows you to understand old musical
phenomena in new ways,'' he said.
   A conductor's frustration is having to depend on others, he
said. ``You never make your own sound. You depend on the orchestra.
The chemistry ... is essential.
   ``It's hard to describe what I will do in Los Angeles. It must
be something organic, something that emerges by itself from the
collaboration between the orchestra and me.''
   Salonen got to know the orchestra as a regular guest since 1984.
His youth and small-country origins will be no problem, he said. In
Finland, talent finds encouragement.
   ``I never felt the age question as a problem in the States. The
society favors youth ... and age doesn't help if you can't
deliver,'' he said.
   Being a hot property presents other problems.
   ``You know three or four years in advance exactly where you will
be on any given date. It creates a claustrophobic feeling, like
your life is being taken away from you. You talk and think about
things that are five years in the future, but by that time you will
be five years older,'' he said.
   Salonen still has few hobbies. An avid reader and movie buff, he
occasionally listens to pop music so he can know what's going on,
and he cannot relax with classical music.
   ``If I listen to classical music when I'm relaxing I immediately
go to work, thinking about how I would do it,'' he said. ``I relax
to enthic music, Indian and Japanese, because I can just listen.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 13-15</NOTE>
</DOC>
