<DOCNO> AP891002-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--TamHouse Adv05   10-02 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Tam House, Adv 05,0875</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Oct. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Unusual Home For Seniors Provides Alternative To Nursing Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANSELMO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maggie Wiel is 80, nearly blind and
can't live on her own. Yet she bristles at talk of a nursing home.
   But Wiel lives at Tam House, a communal home on a tree-lined
street in the shadow of Mount Tamalpais, with seven other women and
two men. Its directors call Tam House an idea whose time has come;
residents are simply thankful it exists.
   ``It's perfect for someone like me. I needed to be around people
but I needed to be independent and on my own,'' said Dorothy
Wright, 70, who moved in 18 months ago after separating from her
husband of 46 years.
   Now Wright spends her time gardening, playing bingo, visiting
nearby senior centers and hiking six miles a day. ``It's great to
be able to walk to a good trout fishing lake from your home,'' she
said.
   Charlotte Mulford, 79, came to Tam House after staying with a
cousin on his houseboat in Sausalito. Now she wouldn't feel
comfortable going back. ``If I didn't live here, I couldn't afford
to live anywhere else,'' she said.
   The 7-year-old, private, non-profit home owned and operated by
the Ross Valley Ecumenical Housing Association, offers more
independence than a board-and-care home, while fostering
companionship and support. Although there is a waiting list, there
hasn't always been. Communal living isn't for everyone.
   It took more than a year to fill the six-bedroom main house and
four-bedroom annex, said Norma Dougherty, RVEHA executive director.
``It was a new idea. Shared living was not a real popular idea with
seniors.''
   Many wanted their own apartment and were reluctant to squeeze a
lifetime's belongings into a bedroom, Dougherty said. And for many,
Tam House also is the first time they've lived with a group since
they were youngsters.
   Tam House is the product of a group of local church members who
started meeting in 1975 to discuss senior housing. In 1980, they
found the house, which was bought and renovated with federal
development funds.
   Residents must be at least 55 and able to live independently
when they move in. Rents range from $400 to $425 a month, including
dinner and food for do-it-yourself breakfasts. Operating costs were
$78,780 in 1988, Dougherty said.
   Advocates for the elderly expect shared group housing to become
increasingly common among seniors. ``It's very common among young
people, it's just not been an acceptable mode of living among old
people until recently,'' said Ellen Caulfield, director of the
Marin County Agency on Aging. ``I think it is an extraordinarily
viable concept but it takes the right mix of people.''
   This year, for the first time, California expanded its senior
housing program to include funds for such shared group residences.
For those who don't mind paring down, group housing offers a
balance of privacy and company.
   Mulford's tidy room disguises the fact that she has boxes and
crates under the bed, jammed in the closet and covered with afghans
in the corner. Little things can rankle, she admitted, laughing at
her own annoyance when others forget to refill the ice cube tray or
replace a roll of toilet paper.
   But the good outweighs the bad, she said. Tam House is within
walking distance of shopping, restaurants, entertainment and public
transit.
   Although residents must be independent, Tam House is small
enough to accommodate changes. Wiel's glaucoma has reduced her
vision since she moved in so ``that they wouldn't take me this way
now.'' But residents help her with chores, and all agree she is
coping remarkably well with her handicap.
   Otto Springer, 81, is a senior member of the house, having moved
in in 1983. Boxes of files create a maze-like pattern on his floor,
and books and more files practically spill off the bookshelves. A
portable computer hums in the corner. Springer is writing his
memoirs.
   He is a survivor of German concentration camps and was a spy for
the British Secret Service who worked to rescue Jews during World
War II. He was imprisoned for refusing to divorce his Jewish wife,
who escaped. Family photos hang on the wall beside framed
commendations from Israel and California.
   Although his two daughters have each offered to share their
homes, Springer will never accept. ``I would have the feeling that
I am burdening someone. We have a wonderful relationship but I
wouldn't want to encroach on their privacy. Even if you have a big
house, it's a problem to have old people around.''
   Although only one person, who had a drinking problem, has been
evicted, Tam House residents are sensitive to the ruptures that
conflicts can cause.
   Springer said he is sometimes bothered by noise but uses
earplugs rather than complain because ``it would establish a
certain tension.''
   ``This is 10 crotchety old people,'' said Teddy McDonald, 81.
``We're all set in our ways before we get here. It's simply amazing
how we all get along.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 5</NOTE>
