<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--ChickenDinnerNews Adv05   10-02 0812</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Chicken Dinner News, Adv 05,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Oct. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Patriarch of Journalism Still Going Strong at 93</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. IGNACE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalism careers begin humbly under
Wesley Maurer, a 93-year-old patriarch of the profession who starts
the process by having bright young students restock newspaper
vending machines.
   Maurer teaches an old school of journalism, the small-town kind
known unkindly in big-city newsrooms as ``chicken dinner news.''
It's the toughest journalism there is, and the most important, he
believes.
   Maurer bought the Mackinac Island Town Crier for his students
and the St. Ignace News for himself. At both weeklies, reporters
and interns write about ice cream socials and summer parades. They
sell ads, take subscriptions, paste up the paper and collect
quarters from the stands.
   They also probe social issues and pry truth from rumor. And they
listen for the beat of the community heart.
   ``The idea to know about journalism is to know the whole
thing,'' Maurer says. That means living with the people you write
about and to whom you sell the stories and the ads. Shed your
cynicism and tell readers of their own decency, grace and
commonweal, Maurer says.
   You might not expect to learn such high ideals selling ads for
an obstinate man who can hardly hear, who sits dwarfed in his dim
office beneath a wall of books, ripping into newspaper stories.
Here is a man who advocates such old-school and now taboo ideas as
doctoring quotes to improve their clarity.
   Some of Maurer's students start their summers on Mackinac Island
thinking they're entering a museum. The necessity for reporters to
cover their beats by riding bicycles on the motorless island
doesn't help.
   ``I think they look at him, in a way, just as an old man. I hate
to see it but I know where it's coming from,'' said one of Maurer's
disciples, Richard Hayden, a publisher who came out of retirement
to be advertising manager.
   ``I know they respect him but they wonder with his age that he
might be out of touch with reality. ... They look at him as a
stodgy old professor.
   ``Then, all of a sudden, it's a rude awakening. Here's this man
tearing into their copy and they're not prima donnas anymore.''
   There is more to Wesley Maurer than this.
   He works every day of every week and always wears a suit with a
University of Michigan pin _ he joined the faculty in 1928 and was
journalism chairman for two decades starting in 1947 _ and a tie
with a perfect Windsor knot, even when weeding his beloved roses.
Sunday mornings, he gathers his interns for three-hour lectures on
topics ranging from the Cold War to why papers didn't sell.
   ``He called me back into his office once and I thought there was
something wrong with one of my stories,'' said former St. Ignace
reporter Mark Esper, now at the Ironwood Daily Globe. ``Instead, he
leans back in his chair and says `Light can illuminate but it can
also blind.'''
   Vintage Maurer.
   The reporters he has coached, encouraged and tormented have gone
on to become correspondents, editors and publishers around the
world.
   ``He is a terrific teacher, a very stimulating fellow. He makes
you think,'' said Earl Gottschalk, one of Maurer's first island
interns, now senior writer for the Los Angeles bureau of the Wall
Street Journal.
   Maurer's students tell of a relentless teacher and
perfectionist. The idiosyncrasies are tolerated. The ideologies are
cherished.
   ``I feel every moment I can spend with him is worthwhile. He is
forever the teacher,'' says senior intern Sean Reavie. ``I know new
students see this 90-year-old man waddling around and they say,
`What can he do for us?' But they genuinely love the man at the end
of the summer.''
   And how Maurer loves them. ``I get always connected with young
people. It's a delight. I find them interesting.''
   Age now is wedging itself between Maurer and the business he
loves. Bypass surgery last fall knocked him off his feet. ``Despite
doctors' orders, he would come down here and be on his feet to
check the paper,'' Hayden said. ``He was just obstinate. I know he
had said to me at one time when he was recovering, that he thought
it could be the beginning of the end.
   ``I had never seen that attitude in him.''
   Maurer has, however, turned over more of the daily newspaper
work to his son, Wesley Maurer Jr., and to Hayden. Neither man has
a journalism degree, but both are lifelong students of Maurer's
community news.
   ``I'm an old man who doesn't know when to retire,'' Maurer says.
``As long as I can, I will do some kind of work, because I think
that keeps you alive.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 5</NOTE>
