<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Briefs Adv05   10-02 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Briefs, Adv 05,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Oct. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Blind Volunteers Sought in Program to Help Blind Elderly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blind Americans aged 60 and over will be
recruited as volunteers to help other visually handicapped elderly
people under a project being launched as part of the government's
Senior Companion Program.
   SCP announced Sept. 15 that it had awarded a $220,000 grant to
the American Foundation for the Blind, which will help find and
train visually impaired senior volunteers and locate other blind
seniors who need help.
   The Senior Companion Program uses low-income citizens 60 and
older to provide care and companionship to other adults to help
them live independently. The program is sponsored by ACTION, the
federal domestic volunteer agency.
   Acting ACTION Director Jane A. Kenny said the new program
targeting the blind is designed ``to focus attention on the
abilities of the disabled.''
   Under the grant, the American Foundation for the Blind will
assist four local Senior Companion Programs in developing two-year
demonstration projects, which have not been selected.
   The foundation will help develop training materials, evaluate
the projects and offer information to other SCP groups interested
in using blind volunteers or serving more visually impaired elderly
people. The New York-based, non-profit foundation is contributing
12 percent in matching dollars toward the cost of the demonstration
project.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Screening, Brochure Available on Leg Pains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 3 million Americans ignore leg ache,
pain or cramps during walking or exercise as simply signs of aging,
but they could have an easily diagnosed and treated disease that
could be incapacitating.
   Peripheral arterial disease is a narrowing or blockage of
arteries, generally in the lower abdomen or extremities and
especially in the legs. The most common cause is atherosclerosis,
or hardening of the arteries.
   P.A.D. most often afflicts people over 50 and has most commonly
hit men, though women also are at increased risk because more women
are smoking. Other risk factors include diabetes, hypertension and
high fat levels in the blood.
   ``P.A.D. is easily treated if detected in its early stages,''
said Dr. Charles Kilo of Washington University School of Medicine.
   LEG ALERT, a 3-year-old program established by the National
Council on the Aging Inc., and Hoechst-Roussel Pharmaceuticals
Inc., has screened over 34,000 people. The NCOA and
Hoechst-Roussel, which makes a drug that increases blood flow, also
have prepared a booklet describing P.A.D. and what to do about it.
   For a copy of ``Step Lively,'' send a stamped, self-addressed,
business-size envelope to CMC-PK, Department PAD, P.O. Box 830,
Andover, N.J. 07821.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Outreach Program Aims to Increase Access to Government Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advocacy group for older Americans is
expanding its outreach program to help more elderly and disabled
poor people get the government benefits to which they are eligible.
   The American Association of Retired Persons said it will help
people in 30 communities nationwide learn about and apply for
Medicaid, food stamps, low-income home energy assistance and
Supplemental Security Income benefits.
   The outreach program earlier had been planned for 10 cities and
was focused on helping eligible people obtain SSI benefits, which
provide a minimal income floor for the nation's blind, aged and
disabled.
   A pilot SSI outreach program in 1988 in Oklahoma City,
Pittsburgh and El Paso, Texas, resulted in a 97 percent increase in
SSI applications and a 58 percent jump in SSI awards, AARP said.
   Training, community presentations and publicity are among the
methods used to reach people who may be eligible for benefits, the
group said.
   AARP's expanded outreach program, scheduled to run through 1990,
is being financed with help from The Commonwealth Fund Commission
on Elderly People Living Alone. Cities to be included in the
project will be selected after local organizations apply to assist
in the outreach program.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Organizations interested in the outreach program
can get more information by writing to: Public Benefits Outreach
Project, AARP Consumer Affairs, 1909 K St. N.W., Washington D.C.
20049. The deadline for applications is Oct. 16.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 5</NOTE>
