<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-LandPrices     10-02 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Land Prices,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Land Prices in Tokyo Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Land prices in Tokyo's residential areas have
fallen for the first time since the government began keeping
records in 1975, but real estate costs have been rising elsewhere
in Japan, a report released Monday said.
   The National Land Agency said residential land prices in Tokyo
were down 4.4 percent as of July 1 from 1988, when they rose 8.1
percent.
   The highest residential land price in Japan was $88,000 a square
meter, or 10.76 square feet, in the Tokyo area, said an agency
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The official declined to say who lives there, but Kyodo News
Service said Prime Minister Toshiko Kaifu lives in an apartment
house in that area, and owns his apartment.
   Last year's highest price was $79,000 a square meter.
   Japan's most expensive commercial land was $254,000 a square
meter at the site of a building of Meidi-Ya Co., a trading firm, in
the Ginza, Tokyo's leading shopping district. That area also was
most expensive last year, at $242,000, the official said.
   He said the report was based on a survey of land prices
conducted on July 1 at 25,216 spots throughout the nation.
   The official said the nation's average land price went up by 6.8
percent from a year earlier in residential areas and 7.5 percent in
commercial areas, compared with 7.4 percent for residential land
and 8.0 percent for commercial land last year.
   In Osaka and neighboring areas in western Japan, residential
land prices rose 37.3 percent from a year earlier, compared with an
increase of 26.9 percent last year.
   In Sanrizuka, land prices went up 96 percent, the highest in
Japan this year, to $317 a square meter from $162.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
