<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 0934EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Phones     10-02 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Phones,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Competition Bringing Down International Phone Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company that held a monopoly on Japan's
international telephone service will cut its rates by 14 percent
next month to compete with two new rivals, officials said Monday.
   Kokusai Denshin Denwa Co. Ltd. began receiving telephone service
competition Sunday from the new International Telecom Japan and
International Digital Communications.
   The new companies started with service to the United States and
Hong Kong, the two places called most frequently from Japan,
company officials said.
   IDC plans to extend its services to Britain and Singapore later
this year, and to Taiwan next year, company spokesman Koyo Taura
said.
   ITJ said it also would be serving Singapore, Britain and France
by November, and such places as South Korea, Taiwan, Australia and
West Germany next year.
   Government officials said they hoped the new competition would
help the international telephone business grow in Japan.
   While domestic phone calls produce about $33.7 billion a year in
profit, the international phone business in Japan has been worth
only $1.44 billion in annual profit, said Takaharu Yamamoto,
spokesman for the Post and Telecommunication Ministry.
   Two years ago, the average Japanese called overseas only once a
year, he said.
   The two newcomers' normal daytime rates for three-minute calls
to the United States are $4.86, lower than KDD's current $6.35,
Taura said.
   The Post and Telecommunication Ministry's recent approval for
KDD's percent rate cut starting Nov. 1, to $5.20, would narrow the
price gap, making competition keener, he added.
   KDD has reduced its rates nine times since 1979, said KDD
spokesman Shinichiro Terada. The largest reduction was last year's
21 percent cut, said the post ministry's Yamamoto.
   Japan long has been criticized for expensive international phone
call rates.
   ``It used to be almost twice as expensive to call from Japan to
America, we admit that,'' Yamamoto said.
   But the gap has been narrowing, and will narrow further with
healthy competition in Japan, Yamamoto added.
   Currrently, AT&amp;T Co., America's largest long distance carrier,
charges $6.02 for a three-minute daytime call to Japan. U.S. Sprint
Communications Co., a competitor, charges $5.67, Yamamoto said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
