   The stock market declined slightly today,
getting off to a sluggish start on the last quarter of 1989.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 4.37 to 2,688.45
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 371 up, 548 down and
474 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 16.07 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said prices backtracked a bit in the absence of the
end-of-quarter buying by investing institutions that helped support
the market last week.
   They said the atmosphere was characterized more by an absence of
demand than by any pickup in selling pressure.
   The results of a monthly survey of corporate purchasing
executives, released this morning, showed continued softness in the
manufacturing sector of the economy during September.
   But brokers noted that the report contained few surprises for
investors, and actually indicated a modest improvement from August.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines rose ] to 109|; General Electric gained \ to 56};
McDonald's dropped \ to 29{, and Eastman Kodak was down \ at 46[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.26 to 193.71. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .20 at 388.56.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 2.09 to
2,692.82, reducing its gain for the week to 11.21 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 8 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 892 up, 560 down and 503 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 155.30 million shares, against 164.24
million in the previous session.
