<FIRST>r f PM-CoalStrike 2ndLd-Writethru f0040 10-02 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0040,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittston-Related Strike Affects Scattered Mines In Two States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with walkouts in West Virginia.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, About 1,700 ... A version moving on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIKEVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 350 United Mine Workers members
walked off their jobs in two states today in a strike against coal
mines the union claims are filling orders for the Pittston Coal
Group, subject of a months-long strike.
   UMW President Richard Trumka ordered selective strikes at Sunglo
Coal Co. and Rob Fork Mining Co. in Kentucky to begin at midnight
Sunday, said Dean Bentley, UMW International representative.
Bentley and company officials today confirmed that the mines, with
about 250 union workers total, had been shut down.
   In West Virginia, about 120 UMW members went on strike today at
five coal companies, a spokesman there said.
   ``The union found them doing business with Pittston, they found
them aligning themselves with them and supporting them,'' said
Danny Wells, executive board member at UMW District 17 in West
Virginia. He said ``there's no way to tell'' how long it will last.
   Kentucky State Police and company officials reported no problems
on the picket lines, and Wells said the situation was also peaceful
in West Virginia.
   Members of the union's international committee met Sunday with
UMW Local 1468, representing about 200 Sunglo miners, and Local
1812, representing about 50 workers at Rob Fork Mining, formerly
known as Beth Energy. Both mines are in southern Pike County in
eastern Kentucky.
   ``They said they had solid proof (the mines) were selling coal
to Pittston and that's the reason the local is being called out on
selective strike,'' said Charles Spartman, an officer of Local 1468.
   The companies affected in West Virginia, all in Logan County,
are the M&amp;H Coal Co.; War Eagle Construction Co.; Gar Coal Co.;
Auger Resources, and Can Run Coal Co., Well said.
   About 1,700 UMW members went on strike against Pittston in
Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky in April after working more
than a year without a contract. Among the issues the union has been
unable to resolve with Pittston include insurance and pension
benefits, and hiring non-union labor.
   Wildcat strikes related to the Pittston dispute affected tens of
thousands of union miners at other companies in June and July.
   Phil Lucas, superintendent of Rob Fork Mine 29 and processing
plant, said he didn't know if the company was filling Pittston's
orders. He said the company has salesmen who handle coal shipments
but could not provide their names or any other details.
   There was no comment from Sunglo mine manager I.C. Spotte.
People who answered the telephone at one Sunglow mine said Spotte
was at another mine, where there was no answer.
   Leonard Fleming, co-administrator for UMW District 30 in
Pikeville, said Spotte has denied to the union that the company was
helping Pittston, but he was ``confident w can prove our case in
any court of law that they are filling Pittston's order.''
   UMW spokesman Joe Corcoran said the union is looking at other
unspecified companies in the three states to see if they also are
assisting Pittston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
