<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-02 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rumored Soviet Demand Fuels Crop Futures Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose sharply in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid signs the
Soviet Union has returned in a big way to the U.S. agricultural
markets.
   Corn futures soared the permitted daily limit of 10 cents a
pound shortly after the opening on rumors the Soviets had bought
1.5 million to 2 million metric tons of U.S. corn over the weekend.
   Rumors of an impending Soviet corn purchase had simmered through
the markets last week despite statements last month by the Soviet
Union's grain-buying agency that the country would purchase no more
grain this year.
   Further buying of grain futures was prompted by a news service's
report that an agricultural aide to President Bush had said an
``unprecedented'' sale of U.S. farm goods to the Soviets would be
announced soon.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1{ cents to 4{ cents higher
wiith the contract for delivery in December at $4.11} a bushel;
corn futures were 9 cents to 10 cents higher with December at $2.43
a bushel; oats were 4\ cents to 5 cents higher with December at
$1.48\ a bushel; soybeans were 8} cents to 18 cents higher with
November at $5.86 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .35 cent higher with October at
71.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .13 cent lower
with October at 82.82 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to .78
cent higher with October at 44 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .40 cent to .78 cent higher with February at 48.77 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Friday.
</TEXT>
