<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-USX-OilReserves     10-02 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USX-Oil Reserves,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>USX Puts Oil Reserves on Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. said today it is offering to sell
the oil and natural gas reserves of its Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corp.
subsidiary.
   The oil and steel giant said it has retained the investment
banking firm First Boston Corp. to handle the sale. The reserves
are mainly located in Texas, Oklahoma, Arkansas, Louisiana,
Colorado and Kansas.
   USX, based in Pittsburgh, issued 133 million shares of stock in
1986 to acquire Texas Oil &amp; Gas in a deal valued at around $3
billion. USX has been disappointed by the company's earnings ever
since. The parent has pinned its hopes for a turnaround at Texas
Oil &amp; Gas on the prospect of natural gas prices surging.
   A sale is anticipated by year's end, said USX spokesman William
E. Keslar, who declined to say what value USX places on the
reserves.
   Texas Oil &amp; Gas has 1.2 trillion cubic feet of gas in reserve,
about a quarter of the 3.5 trillion cubic feet held by the other
USX subsidiary, Marathon Oil Co. Texas Oil &amp; Gas has 28 million
barrels of oil, or 3 percent of Marathon's 766 million barrels.
   The bulk of Texas Oil &amp; Gas' business is natural gas gathering,
which would not be affected by the sale. The subsidiary also would
retain its contract drilling business.
</TEXT>
