<HEAD>Crop Futures Surge on Rumored USSR Corn Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures prices soared Monday on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid rumblings of a major Soviet purchase of U.S.
corn, and the other grain and soybean markets went along for the
ride.
   Rumors that the Soviet Union had bought as much as 3 million
metric tons of corn over the weekend sent futures prices for the
commodity up the permitted dily limit of 10 cents a bushel shortly
after the opening.
   The other markets rose in sympathy with corn, but prices
retreated from their highs across the board in afternooon trading
when ``the biggest thing was profit-taking,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Rumors of an impending Soviet corn purchase had simmered through
the markets last week, despite statements last month by Russia's
grain-buying agency that the Soviet Union would purchase no more
grain this year.
   At the close, wheat futures were \ cent to 4\ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.07{ a bushel; corn was
5{ cents to 8\ cents higher with December at $2.41\ a bushel; oats
were 2} cents to 4\ cents higher with December at $1.46} a bushel;
soybeans were 3} cents to 11 cents higher with November at $5.76 a
bushel.
