<FIRST>r f AM-Coke-Columbia     10-02 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coke-Columbia,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coke Board Approves Columbia Sale to Sony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co.'s board of directors on Monday
approved the sale of its stock in Columbia Pictures Entertainment
Inc. to Sony Corp. and said it would use the money _ $1.45 billion
_ for its soft drink operations and buying back some of its own
stock.
   The Coca-Cola board gave its formal OK to the sale of the
company's 53.8 million shares of Columbia Pictures to Sony USA
Inc., a subsidiary of the Sony Corp. The board also authorized the
purchase of up to 20 million shares of Coca-Cola stock through 1991.
   The deal will bring Coke an after-tax gain of some $530 million,
or $1.53 per share, this year, the company said.
   Sony reached an agreement to buy Columbia last week, with Sony
paying $27 a share, for a total cost of $3.4 billion. At that
price, Coke's take comes to $1.45 billion.
   Coke entered the movie business in 1982, when it bought a
predecessor of Columbia.
   ``Our investment in the entertainment business has provided
substantial value and outstanding returns to our shareholders,''
Coca-Cola Chairman Roberto C. Goizueta said in a statement. ``We
see excellent opportunities to continue to build ... through growth
of and further investments in our worldwide soft drink business,
and by instituting a new share repurchase program.''
</TEXT>
