<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2041EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-USX-TXO     10-02 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX-TXO,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>USX Puts Texas Oil &amp; Gas Reserves on Block</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. Monday offered to sell the natural
gas and oil reserves of its Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corp. subsidiary in
what is being viewed on Wall Street as a concession to shareholders.
   Texas Oil &amp; Gas has been a disappointment to USX since it was
acquired in 1986 in a $3 billion stock swap.
   ``I think shareholders have just lost their patience,'' said
David N. Fleischer of Prudential Bache Securities.
   USX is showing a willingness to part with assets that probably
will appreciate if held long enough but could enhance the stock's
value now by being sold, he said.
   ``This is a very strong statement that they're committed to
shareholders,'' Fleischer said.
   Chief among the shareholders who stand to benefit is corporate
raider Carl Icahn, who is holding an 11 percent stake in USX.
   Fleischer and analyst Frank Bracken of Fidelity Investments of
Boston said they valued the reserves at around $1.5 billion. A sale
is anticipated by year's end, said USX spokesman William E. Keslar,
who declined to say how USX values the reserves.
   The Pittsburgh-based oil and steel giant said it has retained
the investment banking firm First Boston Corp. to handle the sale.
The reserves are principally located in Texas, Oklahoma, Arkansas,
Louisiana, Colorado and Kansas.
   After racking up impressive operating income of $547 million and
$377 million in 1984 and 1985 respectively, Texas Oil &amp; Gas
reported an operating loss of $21 million the year USX acquired it,
then broke about even with $2 million the next year and lost $31
million last year.
   ``I estimate that TXO's producing properties are losing $30 to
$40 million per year on an operating basis,'' said Fleischer.
   The sale, besides boosting Texas Oil &amp; Gas's earnings, will help
with USX's goal of reducing debt and may lead to the repurchase of
stock or raise the dividend, he said.
   USX had been pinning its hopes for a turnaround at Texas Oil &amp;
Gas on the prospect that natural gas prices will surge.
   Texas Oil &amp; Gas has 1.2 trillion cubic feet of natural gas in
reserve, about a quarter of the 3.5 trillion cubic feet held by the
other USX subsidiary, Marathon Oil Co. Texas Oil &amp; Gas has 28
million barrels of oil, or 3 percent of Marathon's 766 million.
   The sale would not affect gas gathering, the bulk of Texas Oil &amp;
Gas's business, or contract drilling, USX said.
   Gas gathering accounted for $538 million of Texas Oil &amp; Gas's
$937 million in total sales last year. Drilling and other activites
had sales totaling $41 million.
   The remainder, or $358 million, came from petroleum sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
