<DOCNO> AP891002-0328 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1722EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Nissan     10-02 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nissan,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan Executive Predicts '90 Vehicle Sales Will Drop</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT7 of Oct. 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Corp. car sales should drop
in 1990 although it expects its truck sales to increase, led by its
new four-door Pathfinder sport-utility vehicle, a Nissan executive
said Monday.
   Overall, sales throughout the industry in 1990 will drop to
about 14 million cars and trucks from nearly 15 million in 1989,
said Bob Thomas, general manager of the Nissan Division of Nissan
Motor Corp. in U.S.A., the Japanese company's U.S. marketing arm.
   Thomas said Nissan's share of that market should be about
660,000 vehicles in each year. Nissan's car sales in 1990 should
drop by about 0.8 percent but truck sales should rise by 2.5
percent.
   Thomas estimated the four-door Pathfinder would make up 90
percent of the vehicle's U.S. sales of about 31,000 vehicles. About
24,000 two-door Pathfinders were sold in the United States during
the 1989 model year, but Thomas said that number would drop
drastically because of price increases needed to recover tariff
costs effective on the 1990 models.
   The Treasury Department, under rules announced earlier this
year, classified the four-door version of the imported Pathfinder
as a car, making it subject to a 2.5 percent tariff.
   Nissan officials had worried that the four-door Pathfinder would
be classified as a truck, making it subject to a 25 percent import
duty.
   Nissan now makes pickup trucks and Sentra automobiles at its
Smyrna, Tenn., plant. Thomas projected that Sentra sales will fall
to about 180,000 cars in the 1990 model year, down 21.1 percent
from the 228,000 the company expects to sell in the 1989 model
year. Sales of U.S. built pickup trucks should increase slightly,
he said.
   When asked if a larger car would be made at the Smyrna plant,
Thomas said only that it would be two to three model years away.
However, he later said a redesigned Stanza would be offered at
about the same time, and with design work done in California, ``at
that time it could be an all-American vehicle.''
   He predicted the newly redesigned 1990 Stanza would more than
double U.S. sales for the nameplate during the 1990 model year. He
also forecast that sales of the 300ZX sports car would rise in
1990, with sales of other cars flat or lower.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
