<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1744EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TexasAir-Lawsuit 1stLd-Writethru   10-02 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Air-Lawsuit, 1st Ld-Writethru,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions File Racketeering Countersuit Against Texas Air, Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with attorney's confirmation that countersuit
filed; picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, The action, ...; NEW grafs 7-10 to
UPDATE with judge enjoining union suit against Eastern leasing planes from
Continental, edit to conform; picks up 8th graf pvs bg'ng, The lawsuit
...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Eastern Airlines pilots and Machinists
unions said Monday they filed a civil racketeering lawsuit against
Texas Air Corp., company chairman Frank Lorenzo and two subsidiary
airlines.
   The lawsuit seeks relief for damages to employees and
shareholders from a pattern of ``fraudulent empire-building,
misrepresentation, extortion, asset-stripping and criminal activity
against Eastern Airlines unions,'' the Air Line Pilots Association
said.
   A spokesman for the clerk's office at the federal court in Miami
was unable to confirm receipt of the documents on Monday afternoon,
but ALPA attorney Michael Harwood confirmed that he had filed the
papers.
   The action, a counterclaim to an earlier lawsuit filed by
Eastern, charges violations of the federal Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organizations Act by the company.
   ALPA spokesman Ron Cole said many of the allegations have been
made to the bankruptcy court in New York, but the racketeering
complaint was filed because the progress of the bankruptcy case has
been slow.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Robin Mattell said the lawsuit was
without merit.
   In a separate action Monday, a federal bankruptcy judge in New
York granted an injunction to Eastern blocking another union
lawsuit from being tried in the Miami district court. That suit,
filed by ALPA alone on Sept. 1, challenges Eastern's recent
practice of leasing DC-9 jets and flight crews from sister carrier
Continental Airlines.
   In a hearing before U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland,
ALPA attorney Bruce Simon contended that Eastern violated its
collective bargaining agreement with the pilots union by leasing
the planes and crews from Houston-based Continental. Bruce
Zirinsky, a lawyer for Eastern, insisted that the leasing
arrangement didn't violate any labor agreements and was vital to
Eastern's rebuilding effort.
   Lifland agreed, saying that the loss of the leasing arrangement
_ now involving 16 jets and crews _ could cause ``irreparable
harm'' to Eastern.
   In the corruption countersuit, the unions alleged a pattern of
racketeering activity in violation of the securities laws, mail and
wire fraud statutes and other federal laws. In addition to Texas
Air, Lorenzo and Eastern, the lawsuit names subsidiary Continental
and Lorenzo's Jet Capital Corp.
   The lawsuit seeks multimillion-dollar damages and relief to be
determined by the court. The civil RICO statute allows juries to
award triple damages.
   Because Eastern is in bankruptcy proceedings in New York, the
unions said they will ask for a release from the bankruptcy court
to press the claims against Eastern.
   Texas Air filed a civil RICO lawsuit against ALPA and the
International Association of Machinists in May 1988 accusing
Eastern unions of trying to wreck the airline in order to force its
sale at a loss.
   Eastern's Machinists, pilots and flight attendants walked off
the job last March 4 and Eastern filed for bankruptcy protection
from creditors five days later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
