<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-02 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Higher In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in quiet trading Monday,
resisting continued intervention by central banks to weaken the
U.S. currency.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   ``Trading was dominated by profit-taking with central bank
intervention less effective,'' said Ronald Holzer, currency broker
with Harris Trust &amp; Savings Bank.
   The U.S. Federal Reserve and foreign central banks continued for
the second consecutive week to sell dollars in a concerted effort
to push the dollar lower.
   Last week the U.S. currency lost more than 4 percent of its
value against the West German mark and Japanese yen. The action has
followed a recent agreement by the Group of Seven industrialized
democracies that the dollar's recent rise was ``inconsistent with
longer run economic fundamentals.''
   The seven nations in the group are the United States, Britain,
Japan, France, West Germany, Italy and Canada.
   Currency analysts said many traders remained bullish and
repeatedly challenged the intervention.
   ``The underlying pro-dollar sentiment was coming back out of the
closet, and every time it came out the Fed came in and intervened
along with other central banks,'' said Robert A. Feldman, vice
president of Salomon Brothers Inc.
   In Tokyo, the dollar ended slightly lower at 139.30 Japanese yen
compared with 139.35 at Friday's close. In late London trading, the
dollar was at 139.25 yen. In New York, the dollar traded at 139.70
yen, up from 139.05.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6175, firmer than Friday's
closing at $1.6150. In New York, the pound fell to $1.6135 compared
with $1.6195.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1,8795 West German marks, up from 1.8720; 1.6285
Swiss francs, up from 1.6220; 1.1782 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1770; 6.3745 French francs, up from 6.3500; and 1,3740 Italian
lire, up from 1,365.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Friday's rates,
included: 1.8750 West German marks, up from 1.8715; 1.6240 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6225; 6.3595 French francs, up from 6.3535;
2.1140 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1090; 1,366.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,363.825; and 1.1772 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1783.
   In London, gold traded at $366.50 bid per troy ounce late
Monday, down from $367.00 late Friday. In Zurich, gold traded at
$366.40 bid per troy ounce compared to $366.50 bid late Friday.
   Gold closed at $367.25 bid in Hong Kong, down from $367.40 at
Saturday's close.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $367.60 an ounce, up from $367.20 on Friday.
Later Republic National bank of New York said gold was bid at
$366.10 an ounce, down from $366.25 on Friday.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $5.23 bid a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Friday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.22 from $5.226 on Friday.
</TEXT>
