<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-02 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Touch 16-Year Low On Ivory Coast Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices plunged to a 16-year low Monday on New
York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange on indications that more
cocoa from the Ivory Coast may be headed for an already
overburdened world market.
   On other commodity markets Monday, cotton futures rallied
strongly, grains and soybeans were sharply higher, most energy
futures fell, livestock and meat futures were mixed, and precious
metals were mixed.
   Cocoa settled $25 to $34 lower with the contract for delivery in
December at $1,008 per metric ton. The December contract traded as
low as $995 during the session, marking cocoa's first dip below
$1,000 since 1973. The close was also the lowest since 1973.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds.
   Analysts attributed much of the market's weakness to
confirmation that the Ivory Coast, the world's largest cocoa
producer, had slashed by 50 percent the support price it pays to
cocoa farmers.
   Arthur Stevenson, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., said the price-support cut had been urged by international
lending agencies and could signal a more aggressive selling posture
on the part of the Ivory Coast.
   Meanwhile, rumors resurfaced that a 500,000-ton Ivorian cocoa
deal involving two trade houses had collapsed.
   ``It just means there is that much more cocoa to be sold,''
Stevenson said.
   Cotton futures soared on New York's Cotton Exchange, largely
reflecting bullish chart signals. Further buying was linked to
speculation that India's cotton crop may be smaller than forecast
and to position-evening by traders in a market that has fluctuated
wildly in recent weeks.
   ``A lot of people have been whipsawed by this market,'' said
analyst Judy Ganes of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Corn futures prices soared on the Chicago Board of Trade amid
rumblings of a major Soviet purchase of U.S. corn, and the other
grain and soybean markets went along for the ride.
   Rumors that the Soviet Union had bought as much as 3 million
metric tons of corn over the weekend sent futures prices for corn
up the permitted daily limit of 10 cents a bushel shortly after the
opening.
   The other markets rose in sympathy with corn, but prices
retreated from their highs across the board in afternooon
profit-taking.
   Wheat futures settled unchanged to 4} cents higher with December
at $4.07\ a bushel; corn was 6 cents to 8{ cents higher with
December at $2.41{ a bushel; oats were 2} cents to 4\ cents higher
with December at $1.46} a bushel; soybeans were 4{ cents to 9 cents
higher with November at $5.77 a bushel.
   Energy futures finished mostly lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, led by a drop in near-term heating oil contracts that was
viewed as a technical correction following five days of steady
gains.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 12 cents
lower with November at $20.01 a barrel; heating oil was .30 cent to
.45 cent lower with November at 59.58 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1.42 cent lower to .05 cent lower with November at
56.80 cents a gallon.
   Live cattle futures dropped sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange amid worries that cash prices would not follow through on
expectations for higher levels.
   Pork futures advanced moderately following Friday's quarterly
Agriculture Department hogs-and-pigs report, which showed
lower-than-expected hog-breeding intentions.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent to .90 cent lower with October at
71.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .60 cent lower
with October at 82.60 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent lower to
.65 cent higher with October at 44.17 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .03 cent to .33 cent higher with February at 48.55
cents a pound.
   Precious metals finished nearly unchanged on New York's
Commodity Exchange.
   Gold was 20 cents lower to 40 cents higher with October at
$367.60 a troy ounce; silver was 0.6 cent to 1 cent lower with
December at $5.303 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
