<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-02 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices fell Monday as a recent rally
inspired by a new OPEC production agreement ran out of steam.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, slipped 12 cents to close at $20.01 per
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. The contract
had gained 27 cents on Friday.
   Friday's advance was sparked by an agreement among the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries that raised the
ceiling on the cartel's overall output to 20.5 million barrels of
oil a day from the previous limit of 19.5 million barrels.
   Oil investors were encouraged by the group's ability to reach an
agreement to limit production.
   On Monday, though, many traders sold futures contracts to cash
in their profits and halted the rally, analysts said.
   ``There was a feeling the market was overbought'' on Friday,
said Mary Haskins, a vice president of energy futures trading at
Drexel Burham Lambert Inc.
   Home heating oil futures traded on the mercantile exchange also
declined. The November contract for heating oil, in its first day
of trading, fell 0.38 cent a gallon to close at 59.58 cents and
subsequent months also retreated.
   The November contract for gasoline, also in its initial trading
day, dropped 1.42 cents a gallon to 56.80 cents. Most subsequent
months also fell.
</TEXT>
