<SECOND>AM-Motorola Cuts, 1st Ld-Writethru,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motorola to Cut Workforce by 2,500</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: to UPDATE with company comment on possibility voluntary severance
will not bring sufficient workforce reductions, INSERTS one new graf after
3rd graf; pickup 4th graf pvs: The company. SUBS 8th graf pvs to ADD Fort
Worth, Texas, to list of cities where severance offer expected; Pickup
last graf: Motorola, headquartered ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc. announced Monday a plan to
reduce its 105,000-employee workforce by some 2,500 people through
a program emphasizing what the electronics company called
``enhanced voluntary severance.''
   ``This is aimed primarily at salaried employees,'' said Motorola
spokesman Chuck Sengstock. ``We've improved our normal voluntary
severance package. Those applying who are accepted will now receive
two weeks' severance pay for each year of service.''
   The program, which is restricted primarily to Motorola's U.S.
operations, goes into effect immediately, Sengstock said. He said
most of those being urged to take the severance package work in the
company's communications and semiconductor products groups.
   ``If we do not have enough people volunteering for severance,
some involuntary severances may occur, but we won't know about that
for at least six weeks,'' said Sengstock. ``We're hoping we can
meet our goals through voluntary severance, normal attrition and
internal business transfers.''
   The company said a pretax provision of approximately $43 million
to cover the cost of the severance would be reflected in
third-quarter earnings to be announced next week.
   ``We retain our confidence in the company's growth prospects,''
said company president George Fisher. ``This program simply
reflects what we at Motorola consider to be good and prudent
management and provides a means for us to reduce our cost base
through a voluntary process which is in the best interest of our
employees.''
   The package will be offered to workers at selected Motorola
facilities until approximately mid-November, Sengstock said. He
mentioned plants in Chicago; Phoenix; Austin, Texas; Fort Worth,
Texas; Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; and Boynton Beach, Fla., as among the
facilities where salaried employees would be encouraged to take
severance.
   Motorola, headquartered in this Chicago suburb, has plants or
other facilities at some 24 locations in the United States,
Sengstock said.
</TEXT>
