<FIRST>r f AM-BankofBoston     10-02 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank of Boston,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Bank Announces It Will Take a Loss to Cover Shaky Loans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of Boston Corp., expressing concern about the
economy, announced Monday it was diverting $370 million from its
earnings to increase its reserve for possible loan losses.
   Ira Stepanian, chairman and chief executive officer, said based
on current estimates, Bank of Boston will have a third-quarter loss
of approximately $125 million after placing the money in its
reserve for credit losses.
   But he said Bank of Boston should end the first nine months of
1989 with a profit.
   ``It's a good deal of money,'' said bank spokesman Wayne Taylor.
``It's certainly a big hit for us.''
   In a separate matter, Stepanian said the bank has taken steps to
strengthen its internal controls, real estate lending and review of
credit risk, as suggested by federal regulators after a review by
the office of the Comptroller of the Currency.
   ``The issues raised by the regulators are ones we take very
seriously,'' Stepanian said in a prepared statement.
   On the new reserve, Stepanian said the bank was taking a
leadership position similar to 1987, when it shifted money to cover
loans to Third World countries.
   Among the reasons he cited for Monday's action were continued
weakness in the real estate industry and ``further signs of
softness in general economic conditions.'' The bank already had 100
percent reserves against its non-trade-related lending to Third
World countries.
   Also, Taylor said, one of the bank's business customers assumed
a large amount of debt for a transaction, and now the bank is
concerned that the company might have trouble paying off the loan.
   He declined to name the company or the amount of the loan.
   By shifting money into the reserve account, ``it doesn't just
forgive the debt,'' Taylor said.
   ``We're taking it off the books so it doesn't just hang there,''
he said, adding that the bank would still try to recover the money.
   The additional reserve, combined with $70 million in charge-offs
for bad loans in the quarter, brings the total reserve to about
$945 million, or 3.5 percent of total loans and leases.
   Stepanian said the bank expects to enter an agreement with the
federal agency in which the board of directors will review steps to
improve its performance in those areas cited in the governmental
review.
</TEXT>
