<FIRST>r f BC-Drexel-Headquarters     10-02 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drexel-Headquarters,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Lease Renegotiated for About Half the Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. will retain its New
York headquarters at least until 2004 but with about half the space
currently occupied, under terms of a renegotiated lease announced
Monday by the investment banking firm that recently settled
widespread fraud charges.
   Drexel said it had reached agreement with landlord Olympia &amp;
York, a large real estate concern that owns many New York
properties, to restructure and extend for 10 years Drexel's lease
on its world headquarters in southern Manhattan. The lease had been
due to expire in about four years.
   Within two years Drexel expects to consolidate most of its New
York-based operations into 700,000 square feet in one building, vs.
1.5 million square feet in four locations now, the firm said.
   Financial details of the restructured lease weren't disclosed,
but Drexel said in a statement it will ``result in a substantial
cash savings over the next three and a half years.''
   Drexel was once the fifth-biggest Wall Street firm but underwent
a drastic restructuring earlier this year, after agreeing to settle
securities fraud charges that stemmed from a prolonged federal
investigation.
   As part of the settlement, Drexel pleaded guilty to six felonies
and paid more than $650 million in fines, penalties and interest.
   The firm eliminated its retail operations and terminated about
4,000 employees of its 9,300 workforce worldwide. The New York
staff was cut by 1,345 people to 3,635.
</TEXT>
