<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2204EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Honeywell-NEC     10-02 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Honeywell-NEC,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honeywell Sells Its 50 Percent Stake In HNSX Supercomputers To NEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. has sold to NEC Corp. of Japan
its 50 percent ownership in HNSX Supercomputers Inc., the
Massachusetts company that markets NEC supercomputers in the United
States and Canada.
   Terms of the agreement were not disclosed Monday.
   HNSX, based in Burlington, Mass., had been jointly owned by
Honeywell and NEC since its inception in 1986. Honeywell said the
venture is no longer within its ``strategic focus.''
   The Minneapolis-based controls maker and defense contractor lost
$435 million in fiscal 1988 and announced a sweeping restructuring
in July. Earlier Honeywell had sold its other computer operations.
   The HNSX deal puts NEC in complete control of its attack in the
U.S. against Minneapolis-based Cray Research.
   Cray is the world's largest supercomputer maker, but NEC threw
America's long-term dominance of the industry into question in
April when it announced it will introduce the world's fastest
supercomputer next year.
   Supercomputers are considered crucial to national security
because they are heavily used for designing nuclear weapons. They
also are used for such tasks as scientific research, oil
exploration and weather forecasting.
   The U.S. government has strongly discouraged federal agenies and
universities that receive government grants from buying
Japanese-made supercomputers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
