<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2259EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Lockheed     10-02 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Lockheed,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockheed To Take $165 Million in Charges Against 3rd-Quarter Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. said Monday it would
take a charge of about $165 million against its third-quarter
profits because of overruns on fixed-price contracts.
   The writeoffs will result in an after-tax loss of about $35
million for the three months ended Sept. 31, Daniel N. Tellep,
Lockheed's chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.
   The charges stem mainly from a subcontract for wing parts on the
C-17 transport that McDonnell Douglas Corp. is building for the Air
Force and a contract to modify 12 EP-3E patrol planes for the Navy.
   Also included in the charge are overruns on some smaller
fixed-price development contracts and certain other programs,
Lockheed said.
   Lockheed's initial cost figure was $1.3 billion for the C-17
wing work, and $59.8 million for the EP-3E modifications.
   Lockheed spokesman Bob Slayman said the company is continuing
efforts to persuade the government that Lockheed should be paid
more because hundreds of changes were made in design specifications
after the contracts were made.
   ``The assumption was these were build to (blue) print,'' he
said. ``But then there were many changes made in those prints.''
   Despite the expected third-quarter loss, Slayman said Lockheed
expected the year to be profitable as a whole.
</TEXT>
