<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-CSX     10-02 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-CSX,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Strike Blamed for Profit Decline at CSX</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CSX Corp.'s third-quarter profit declined,
due in part to the United Mine Workers strike against Pittston Coal
Group Inc., the Richmond-based railroad, barge and natural
resources company said Monday.
   CSX said third-quarter earnings totaled $94 million, or 91 cents
per share, compared with $120 million, or 75 cents a share, for the
same period last year. Revenue for the quarter totaled $1.9
billion, $1 million less than last year's third quarter.
   The disparity in the per-share earnings between the two quarters
reflects an ongoing share-repurchase program.
   In addition to lower coal traffic caused by the ongoing coal
strike, which began April 5, CSX cited an overall weakening of the
economy's industrial sector as well as service disruptions and
damage caused by Hurricane Hugo for its lower earnings.
   The company said earnings for the first nine months of 1989
totaled $327 million, or $3.10 per share, compared with earnings of
$25 million, or 11 cents a share, for the first nine months of
1988. Last year's results reflected a post-tax special charge of
$492 million, or $3.16 per share.
   Revenue for the first nine months was $5.7 billion, compared
with $5.5 billion for the same 1988 period.
</TEXT>
