<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2344EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Armstrong-Belzbergs     10-02 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Armstrong-Belzbergs,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belzbergs Seek Special Stockholders Meeting In Armstrong Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian family considering a hostile
takeover of Armstrong World Industries Inc. has asked the board of
directors to allow a special stockholders meeting.
   Lancaster-based Armstrong, which manufactures interior
furnishings, said in a news release Monday it is examining the
request from the Belzberg family of Vancouver, British Columbia,
which has interests in real estate and a financial company.
   The family's petition asks the board to amend its articles of
incorporation to allow investors holding 20 percent of the
company's stock to call a special meeting.
   According to the petition, two companies controlled by the
Belzbergs own 4.56 million shares, or 9.85 percent of the company.
The shares were purchased for $181 million this summer.
   The petition, which was filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, indicates the Belzbergs have not acquired any more
Armstrong stock since announcing their initial stake July 5.
   Under Pennsylvania law, only investors holding at least 10
percent of a company's stock can file amendment petitions. The
Belzbergs were joined in the action by United Funds Inc. and United
Vanguard Fund Inc., which together own nearly 800,000 shares.
   Armstrong's stock closed Monday at 44.62{, up $1.37{, on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   The petition also seeks to waive the Pennsylvania business
combination statute, which is intended to discourage takeovers.
   The Belzbergs asked the U.S. District Court in Philadelphia to
approve the petition's requests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
